<head> <title> Ethics and Computing -  Preface</title> <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body>

<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" background="../../sand.gif">
<FORM ACTION=https://secure.computer.org/cgi-bin/cspress/shopcart.bat METHOD=POST>
<INPUT TYPE=Hidden NAME=catnumber VALUE="bp07130">


<h3><CENTER><B><I>Ethics and Computing <BR>
edited by Kevin Bowyer </B></I></CENTER></P></h3>

<h2 align=center>To the Reader </h2>

<hr>

<P>Becoming a computing <I>professional</I> must involve more than just learning about machines and how technology works. There is a real need to develop an understanding of the ethical and social implications involved in computing as well.  How computing professionals decide to handle such issues as hacking, privacy, safety-critical software, whistle blowing - even the use of resources - will greatly affect how they are viewed by the rest of society. Fortunately, both the major accreditation programs in the US and the most widely embraced professional codes of ethics recognize the need for computer professionals to live responsibly. <I>Computing Curricula 1991</I>, a report produced by the ACM-IEEE Computer Society Joint Curriculum Task Force, says this about the social and professional context of computing:
<blockquote><p>Undergraduates also need to understand the basic cultural, social, legal and ethical issues inherent in the discipline of computing.  They should understand where the discipline has been, where it is, and where it is heading. They should also understand their roles in this process, as well as appreciate the philosophical questions, technical problems, and aesthetic values that play an important part in the development of the discipline.
<p>Students need to develop the ability to ask serious questions about the social impact of computing and to evaluate proposed answers to those questions. Future practitioners must be able to anticipate the impact of introducing a given product into a given environment. Will that product enhance or degrade the quality of life? What will the impact be on individuals, groups, and institutions?
<p>Finally, students need to be aware of the basic legal rights of software and hardware   vendors and users, and they also need to appreciate the ethical values that are the   basis for those rights.  Future practitioners must understand the responsibility that   they will bear, and the possible consequences of failure.  They must understand their   own limitations as well as the limitations of their tools.  All practitioners must make   a long-term commitment to remaining current in their chosen specialties and in the   discipline of computing as a whole.</blockquote>
<p>The material in this text is designed to fulfill these requirements. Throughout the text, I emphasize the need for readers to <I>think for themselves</I> about the issues.  Many of the exercises are based on what I have learned from interacting with students in a course I teach at the University of South Florida,  "Ethics, Professionalism and Social Responsibility in Computer Science & Engineering." The course is required for an undergraduate degree in either computer science, computer engineering or information systems.  The course is also open to students in other majors, and I have had students from other engineering majors, as well as from non-engineering departments like English.  On the basis of my understanding of today's students and my perceptions of the educational needs in our industry, I formed three primary goals for this text:
<ul>
<li>Foster a greater awareness of the ethical considerations that arise in the computing profession.
<li>Encourage you to strive for high ethical standards.
<li>Encourage a serious commitment to professionalism and socially responsible behavior.
</ul>

<p>My secondary goal is to give you the opportunity to hone your critical-thinking and communication skills, both written and oral. In my course, for example, each student makes at least one short presentation to the class and completes several written assignments, which are graded for both content and style.  In this text, I have included both original material and reprints, case studies (where applicable) and two types of sample assignments.  The worksheets will help you review the chapter's basic concepts.  The additional assignments provide more in-depth exploration, primarily by inviting you to analyze particular events and their outcomes.
<p>I also strived to create a text with a scope different from that of other texts that could support a course related to ethics and computing. I believe that, although there are a number of excellent texts available (see list of References for Chapter 1), none of them do quite the appropriate and complete job of covering the subject matter. Some are concerned primarily with one topic, such as whistle blowing or intellectual property.  Others are broader than a single topic, but still omit substantial coverage of some vital topics.  Yet others are already somewhat out of date. To address these shortcomings, I have spent a substantial amount of time and effort in collecting, organizing, writing and revising the material in this text. I tried to select the most current material possible, and to stay with material that is as specifically relevant to the computing profession as possible. (In connection with staying current, I have provided World Wide Web pointers to organizations and background resources in a number of areas.)  However, deciding what material to include is a subjective undertaking, and I am sure that there is room for improvement. I invite you to send suggestions for deletions, additions, or modifications to kwb@csee.usf.edu.
<p>My hope is that you will find the text both informative and challenging.  It is of course important that you become better informed through studying this text.  But that alone is not enough.  It is also important that you are challenged to honestly assess your internal sense of ethics and are motivated to strive for higher ethical standards. My goals will be met if you come away with a deeper understanding of the ethical issues you are likely to confront and you find yourself able to formulate and hold to the highest possible ethical standards.

