<HTML><HEAD><TITLE> Distributed Objects  -  Preface</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" 
background="../../sand.gif">


<h3><CENTER><B><I>Distributed Objects: Methodologies for Customizing Systems Software, 
<br>by Nayeem Islam</I></B></CENTER></P></h3>

<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">PREFACE</H1>

<hr>

<P>Message-passing systems allow architecture-independent
parallel and distributed programming.
On particular hardware architectures, however,
performance is an important issue for parallel
and distributed applications.
Restructuring parallel message-passing applications
using better parallel decompositions can
improve their performance [KGGK94].
Even after such restructuring has
been performed, however, and the most appropriate
parallel decomposition performed
by an application programmer, for communication-
intensive applications a significant amount
of the application's execution time may still
be spent in the message-passing system.</P>

<P>An inadequacy of many current message-passing systems
is that they do not take a global view of using
application communication patterns to increase
performance.
For example, for parallel applications
running on a local area network there are
numerous ways to guarantee reliable message
delivery since local area networks
can lose messages.
The popular message-passing library Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM)
[Sun90] employs an alternative
that generates an acknowledgment message for
each application-level message.
This is efficient for an application
that uses a single asynchronous message
transmission, but it is inefficient for request-response
[Che88a] and more complex communication
styles [BPG<sup><small>+</small></sup>94].
A global view of the communication patterns in an
application can generate fewer overall network messages
by piggybacking acknowledgments on
regular communications or by using a single
acknowledgment for a group of messages.
Such optimizations can improve the performance of
applications on distributed systems.</P>


<P>Experiments  demonstrate that these message-passing system optimizations are highly application dependent; that is, communication patterns vary from
application to application. A single message-passing implementation therefore
cannot perform well for all applications.
This suggests the need for customized message-passing
systems: An optimized message-passing system is
custom built for each application.
To
maximize application performance, the subsystems of
an operating system, such as its message-passing system, must be
tailored to the needs of the application.</P>

<P>The optimization problem for message-passing
applications is not limited to distributed
systems; it appears in other architectures.
The performance of message-passing applications
on a bus-based, shared-memory multiprocessor is
also dependent on application communication patterns.
For example, there are a variety of ways to
implement multicast on a shared-memory
multiprocessor, but a naive\break
implementation using
shared variables will be slower than one
using explicit
data copying because it suffers
from contention for the multicast buffer.</P>

<P>Similarly, application-specific scheduling improves
the performance of applications on both distributed
and shared-memory multiprocessor systems.
In particular, gang
scheduling is generalized for parallel applications on
both types of systems.
Distributed gang scheduling reduces
the variability of execution times
in parallel applications and allows the easy transition of distributed
systems from special purpose to general purpose.</P>

<P>To generate application-specific optimizations, a set of
characterizing attributes of applications is presented in this book.
These attributes are determined by\break
examining a representative class of
parallel and distributed applications, and the usefulness of each attribute is determined experimentally.
Each attribute guides the minimization of operating system overhead.
For example, communication pattern is an application attribute that reveals
how to generate message-passing systems on unreliable
networks to minimize the number of acknowledgment messages, thus reducing
operating system overhead.</P>

<P>A sample tool kit of implementations is also presented to exploit the set of application attributes.
When an optimized message-passing system is required for a new application,
the attributes of the application dictate how  best to use the tool kit to minimize
overhead.
For example, given a multicast communication pattern
in a distributed-system application, the
attributes select an implementation that
minimizes the number of acknowledgment messages.
The tool kit is extensible, and new optimizations can be incorporated.</P>

<P>Optimization results are presented for both
parallel and distributed applications.
The parallel applications studied include Simplex and adaptive quadrature.
The distributed applications are client-server
programs used in distributed system services including name servers and distributed schedulers.
 Although only a small number of attributes characterize
the applications studied,
the combinations of these attributes
lead to many
possible
implementations.</P>

<P>Since there is a large number of
different optimizations,
they are organized using an extensible object-oriented
framework. An alternative would be to embed the
optimizations in a compiler; however, compilers
customarily do not generate message-passing system
implementations for the programs they compile.
Message-passing libraries such as
PVM [Sun90] and Express [Cor88] and the
message-passing primitives of operating systems such as
V [Che88a], Mach [Lop91], and
Amoeba [TvRvS<sup><small>+</small></sup>90] are difficult to
extend with multiple optimizations because there
is no methodology for incrementally adding new
algorithms and techniques.
Object-oriented frameworks directly support incremental,
per-application specializations.
They also allow
easy porting of the message-passing and scheduling
system to new hardware
architectures.</P>

<P>The object paradigm supports an implementation technology
that directly captures the structure of objects in an application
domain, making the transition from design to implementation easier than
in other approaches.
Object-oriented programming techniques have been
used extensively for application programs and some
popular object-oriented application frameworks exist, but
there is a dearth of such frameworks for systems software.
Traditionally, operating systems designers have been reluctant to
use object-oriented frameworks because the languages used to
implement them performed poorly.
With the availability of
efficient compilers for object-oriented languages such
as C++, however, it is possible to build
efficient object-oriented operating systems.</P>

<P>The object-oriented framework
approach classifies the components used in
customized schemes
 into a few of basic components that can be represented by
classes. These classes are organized into class
hierarchies.
The class hierarchies include components for a
variety of message-passing and scheduling
primitives and implementations
of those primitives.
For any application, the
message-passing and scheduling system
 support is customized by
selecting a combination
of components based on application
attributes.
Two types of subclassing are presented: one for functionality, which
is common in object-oriented systems; and the other  for
performance, which is less common in most system designs.
This book
presents the use of
objects in system software, an area in which software engineers
have traditionally shied away from using objects.
But objects are a natural way of implementing an operating system that
is designed to be customizable.</P>

<P>Since C++ has certain deficiencies for designing large-scale systems,
library support is included to help in the construction of large-scale C++
programs. This support includes first-class classes,
dynamic code loading, and first-class frameworks.
A system shell design is presented that allows one to view the
design of the operating system at runtime.</P>

<P>The notion of customized implementations for operating
systems is not new. Haberman et al.
[HFC72] recognized
the need for systems with multiple implementations
and introduced
the concept of a family of operating systems.
Each family member is designed for a set of
applications with similar attributes.
This book takes Haberman's notion one
step further by advocating the use of an operating
system customized for each application.</P>

<P>The customized operating approach grew out of the author's
work on the object-oriented operating system \choices.
Readers interested in the Choices
operating system will
find more information in the reference list
[CI93a, CIM92, CIMR93].</P>

<P>This book discusses research in the
design of operating systems, parallel programming techniques,
and software engineering.
Five main topics are discussed in
this book.
<OL>
<LI>New message-passing optimizations for applications running on
a distributed system  of unreliable networks.</LI>
<LI>New message-passing optimizations for applications running on
a bus-based, shared-memory multiprocessor.</LI>
<LI>Optimized scheduling for applications on both a distributed system and a shared-memory multiprocessor.</LI>
<LI>The characterization of a set of
parallel and distributed applications to determine
the attributes relevant to the construction
of optimized message-passing and scheduling systems.</LI>
<LI>A software architecture that uses
object-oriented frameworks to manage the multiple
message-passing and scheduling systems and organize
them for selection. The frameworks allow
easy porting of the message-passing and scheduling
systems to new architectures.</LI>
</OL>
</P>

<h3><LEFT><B>Outline of the Book</B></LEFT></h3>

<P>Because of this book describes a methodology for
building customized system software using object-oriented frameworks,
it will appeal
to practicing software engineers who build large software systems
that must be customized to suit the specific needs of a customer or
an environment. For those building embedded systems,
the book demonstrates how generic
objects can be systematically specialized
to solve specific problems. Since the customization methodology
has been used in an area in
which customization is not normally used (that is, operating systems and system software) it has been stress tested.
While traditional customization
has been used to provide appropriate functionality, this book
demonstrates how one might customize  objects for performance.
The book also presents detailed performance experiments to show that
the customization approach presented does not adversely affect
application performance.</P>

<P>The book will be of value to graduate students studying operating systems, parallel
programming, and object-oriented programming.
Of particular interest to the graduate student is the way in which
the three areas of computer science are integrated.
The book also includes a discussion chapter that will be  useful to
anyone who wants an introduction to the area of customized
system software.</P>

<P>The approach advocated in this book is not limited to operating systems per se.
A general customization methodology is presented that can be used in a
variety  of applications and middleware domains, including
real-time software, client-server software, and embedded systems.
Increasingly, customers are demanding
customized solutions; hence, the techniques discussed in this book
will be useful to practitioners in those areas as well. In particular, the methodology
closely ties code to customer requirements. This link is missing from many methodologies and was chosen
because it allows code to be developed quickly.</P>

<P>Chapter 1 describes
the optimization methodology;
it discusses the types of applications and system customizations
covered in this book. This chapter describes the steps that
a programmer must follow in order to create a customized system
for an application. Chapter 2 describes
the software engineering methodology that is used in  coding
the system customization. It describes object-oriented frameworks,
and techniques for creating customized software in C++.
This chapter contains many  useful
programming tips for engineering large
systems in C++.
This chapter will be of interest to object-oriented programmers.</P>

<P>Chapter 3 presents the attributes of
parallel and distributed applications that
are used to design and implement optimized
message-passing and scheduling systems on
a bus-based, shared-memory multiprocessor and a
distributed system.
This chapter will be of interest to parallel
programmers.</P>

<P>Chapter 4 describes how to select optimizations
in the message-passing system framework using the
application attributes described in Chapter 3.
Chapter 5 describes the major abstractions in the message-passing
framework and demonstrates the use of the techniques described
in Chapter 2.
These two chapters will be  of interest to
researchers in object-oriented design and programming, and\break
to those designing
and implementing communication systems for
an operating\break
system.</P>

<P>The optimizations for message passing
on distributed systems appear in Chapters 6 and 7. Chapter 6 discusses the general
methodology for generating message-passing
optimizations on distributed systems and
how to use the various optimizations. Chapter 7 presents parallel application performance results on
a distributed system and the performance of distributed system services.
Chapters 8 and 9 discuss optimized message passing on a bus-based,
shared-memory multiprocessor. Chapter 8 describes details
of optimization selection on a bus-based, shared-memory multiprocessor, and Chapter 9 presents application performance.</P>

<P>Chapter 10 describes the design
and implementation of optimized scheduling systems.
This chapter discusses a generalization of
gang scheduling on a distributed
system and a bus-based, shared-memory multiprocessor.
Chapter 11 presents a detailed discussion of
related approaches to customizations of systems software.
Chapter 12 draws conclusions from
the work presented in this book and identifies
avenues for future research.</P>

<P>Appendix A describes the hardware
architectures of the distributed system and the bus-based, shared-memory multiprocessor
on which the experiments discussed in this book
were conducted.
Appendix B lists the programming
interfaces used for parallel applications.
The glossary lists terms relating to object-oriented programming,
parallel systems, and operating system the are used in the book.</P>


<P><B>Chapters of Particular Interest to Operating Systems Programmers.</B>
Chapters 6 and 7 will be of
particular interest to distributed  operating systems designers and
implementers. Chapters 8 and 9 will be
of particular interest to operating systems designers of shared-memory
parallel systems.</P>

<P><B>Chapters of Particular Interest to Parallel Systems Programmers.</B>
Chapters 3, 6, 7, 8, 9 and Section 4.2
contain material of interest to parallel
application writers and parallel system designers.
Those interested in the performance issues
 of the message-passing system are referred to
Chapters 6, 7, 8, and 9.</P>

<P> <B>Chapters of Particular Interest to Object-Oriented Programmers.</B>
Those interested in object-oriented design issues are referred to
Chapters 2, 5, and 10.</P>

