<h3><CENTER><B><I>Distributed Objects: Methodologies for Customizing Systems Software, by Nayeem Islam
<br>Sample Chapter </I></B></CENTER></h3>


<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">CHAPTER 1</H1>
<hr>

<h3>Programming Model and Customization Methodology</h3>


<P>The goal of this chapter is to describe the approach to system
software optimization used in this book. This chapter describes the types of 
applications for which system-level optimizations can be generated, 
and briefly outlines the process of optimization from 
the perspective of an application programmer.
The chapter introduces the two subsystems that will be studied and 
optimized in this book: message passing and scheduling.
It describes abstractly how these subsystems will be customized to
increase application performance.</P>


<P>The processes of parallel and distributed applications can 
communicate through either message passing or shared variables.
This book focuses on applications that are written in the message-passing style.  A variety of interfaces and implementations of 
message passing exist, and given a particular interface, there are many ways
of implementing message passing on the hardware architecture.
Depending on how the 
message-passing system is used by the application,  
a number of implementations can improve performance. 
Similarly, various types of scheduling algorithms may be used
by different classes of applications. </P>

<P>For any given interface for a subsystem, such as message passing
or scheduling, there are potentially many implementations.
Thus, a software structure that is easily extensible to new optimizations is required. Object-oriented frameworks
provide such an organization.</P> 

<h3><B>1.1 Parallel and Distributed Application Model</B></h3>

<P>One of the main purposes of writing a parallel program is to 
reduce the execution time of an application [HQ91, CG90].  
Parallel programs have been used to solve many 
scientific problems [FJL<SUP><SMALL>+</SMALL></SUP>88] and commercial applications.</P> 

<P>Most parallel applications are structured as distinct parallel
processes that communicate to collectively solve a problem.
Thus, there is a strong connection among the processes of a 
parallel application.
This connection manifests itself through frequent communication between
the processes.
For example, in a parallel version of the adaptive quadrature
algorithm, different processes compute the integral below the function for 
different subranges. A central process sums all the values 
submitted by the various processes and terminates the computation when the 
integral has been computed.</P>

<P>Distributed applications, on the other hand, are often written for
fault tolerance, availability, and resource sharing.
Typically, the various processes of the application are 
loosely coupled; that is, they communicate infrequently.
For example, a file service manages files (on a remote disk) for
a group of users. A variety of clients could be using this file service
for their files. When users need access to their files they
contact the file service, which retrieves the data from the disk.
The file server is a shared resource.</P>

<P>Each application uses the communication interface differently.
The different uses 
can be exploited to improve the underlying 
message-passing implementation. The user of the interface may
provide hints on how the interface will be used. 
These hints can be used by the programmer or system to select the appropriate
implementation. One approach is that hints are provided as user annotations.</P>

<P>Whether parallel or distributed applications are being considered, the 
processes of the applications must be scheduled on physical processors.
The scheduling may be customized based on how often the processes 
communicate. Thus, the scheduling system can also be customized.
The purpose of this book is to describe the construction of 
a software framework that can be configured to satisfy the needs of
an application; that is, an application-specific instance of 
the operating system may be instantiated through this software 
framework. </P>

<! Reference is to big graphic (about 500 pixels wide)>
<a href=do-fig1.gif>
	<! Displayed image is 150 pixels wide>
<center><IMG SRC="do-fig1a.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="1" width=150></center>
</a>
<center><font size=-1><i>Click for a closer look</i></font></center>

<P><center><b> Figure 1.1.  The system environment</b></center></P>

<P>An abstract view of the system environment is shown 
in Figure 1.1.  It shows 
that parallel and distributed applications are 
supported by an operating system, 
which in turn is supported by a hardware architecture.
The operating system implements the message-passing and scheduling primitives and must support the different 
communication paradigms of the applications. 
It is possible, however, to build most of the 
more complex communication primitives from
simple send-and-receive primitives. 
In most operating systems, the underlying network
protocols are generic or are typically suited for a single style of
interaction. If, however, multiple network protocols exist or
a methodology exists for extending the network protocols, the
application could perform better. One approach is 
to explicitly require that the programmer
rewrite the application to use newer, more optimized primitives. 
For example, many operating systems and 
message-passing libraries provide 
 a set of routines that are optimized 
for collective communication [BPG<SUP><SMALL>+</SMALL></SUP>94, Com89].
If the library interface changes, the application
program must change as well.
In the second implicit approach, the application program
does not have to be rewritten. Thus, message-passing 
optimizations and application development
proceed independently.
The communication pattern and other application
attributes can be used to design optimized message-passing systems.
This second approach is the most important advocated
in this book.
Sometimes the interface of a subsystem 
must be extended; such extensions will also be addressed.</P> 

<P>The next section discusses some design
alternatives for message-passing systems.
Some of the common interfaces for message passing and scheduling are included, and a high-level view of the optimization process is presented.</P>

<h3><B>1.1.1 Message Passing</B></h3>
 
<P>Parallel and distributed applications are structured as concurrent 
processes that communicate using message passing.  The message-passing model includes both asynchronous
[Agh86] and synchronous message passing.
In the message-passing model, processes communicate by 
sending messages to endpoints of 
communication, such as ports or channels.</P>

<P>The channels [And91b] or ports [Ras86]
are often named in message-passing systems.
When two processes communicate, one process invokes
the <TT>send</TT> operation on a channel or
port, and the other process
invokes a <TT>receive</TT> operation on the same channel
or port.
Messages that are sent but not yet received
are placed in the message queue associated with
that port or channel.</P>

<P>Figure 1.2 shows an 
example of two processes
communicating through message passing 
using ports. It shows process 1 sending a message 1 
to port2.  Process 2 
then invokes the receive operation on
port2 and reads the message into its own
local buffer, message2. 
Process 2 then send a message 
to port1, and process 1 invokes the 
receive operation on port1 and reads the message
into its local buffer, message4.
Processes 1 and 2 are concurrent.
If process 2 has not executed
its <TT>receive</TT> operation, then messages are 
buffered for it until it
retrieves them from the system using a <TT>receive</TT>
call.</P>

<center><table>
<td width=200><tr><td>Process 1
<td width=100>Process 2<br>
<td width=200><tr><td>send(message1,port2)
<td width=100><b>.</b><br>
<td width=200><tr><td><b>.</b>
<td width=100>receive(message2,port2)<br>
<td width=200><tr><td><b>.</b>
<td width=100>send(message3,port1)<br>
<td width=200><tr><td>receive(message4,port1)
<td width=100><b>.</b>
</table></center>

<center><p><b>Figure 1.2.  Processes communicating through message passing.
</b></p></center>

<P>Several popular programming interfaces are variants of the interface
shown in Figure 1.2.  For example, 
the NX/2 operating system includes a set of message-passing
  primitives for asynchronous and synchronous
  communication [Pie86].
Two calls implement synchronous message passing.</P>

<OL>
<LI><PRE>csend(type,buffer,length,node,pid)</PRE></LI> 
<LI><PRE>crecv(typesel,buffer,length)</PRE></LI>
</OL>

<P>The <TT>csend</TT> call does not return until the message has been
  put on the network and the buffer specified by the application
  is free to be used again.
A <TT>csend</TT> call does not necessarily wait for
  a corresponding <TT>crecv</TT> to occur at the destination process.
The <TT>crecv</TT> call selects an incoming message by type and receives it
  in a buffer.
This call is blocking, and it does not return until the
  message is in its buffer.
Similarly, calls are supported by the PVM [Sun90];
both procedural and object-oriented interfaces are supported.
Procedural interfaces are supported to enable the porting of
a large number of existing applications. The object-oriented 
message-passing interface is 
given in Chapter 5 and Appendix 5.</P>


<P>The message-passing interfaces required for 
distributed applications may be different from 
those required by parallel applications.
For example, many distributed systems require
request-response style message passing, whereas
parallel applications often exploit
asynchronous message passing.
Request-response style message passing
is often used to support the 
language-level mechanism known as remote procedure
call (RPC) [BN84]. 
Other types of 
interfaces exist, including those that 
support ``generative'' and ``rendezvous'' 
style communication [And91b].</P>

<P>Many message-passing systems support special 
primitives for group or collective communication.
An example of group communication is
a broadcast, where one process sends a message to all
other processes in the system.
Some message-passing systems
provide special implementations for collective 
communication
such as broadcast.</P>

<P>The <TT>send</TT> and <TT>receive</TT> calls are 
implemented by a message-passing system.
To move a message between processes, a protocol
must be obeyed between the sending and the 
receiving processes.
The job of the message-passing system is to 
implement this protocol on behalf of application
processes. Message-passing protocols can be 
implemented on a distributed system 
built from unreliable networks 
or on a shared-memory multiprocessor.</P>

<P>On distributed systems, the implementation of 
a message-passing protocol requires the use
of connection management and error 
handling because the underlying network hardware 
is unreliable.  How such protocols are implemented affects
the performance of parallel and distributed 
applications running on them.
There are two important types of connection management: 
timer based (such as that used in the VMTP protocol) 
and handshake based (such as that used in the TCP 
protocol). On distributed systems, 
message-passing protocols must recover from lost, 
corrupted, and disordered messages.
Message-passing protocols employ error-handling 
mechanisms that wait for certain events to occur
and take corrective action when these events
do not occur. Many protocols generate explicit 
acknowledgments for each message sent, which helps 
in the detection of lost messages.</P>

<P>For example, there are a variety of ways to 
implement the pattern implicit in 
Figure 1.2 on a distributed 
system. On unreliable networks, acknowledgments are generated
to detect lost messages. Naive implementations that
generate too many acknowledgments suffer from  poor
performance.</P>
 
<P>In an implementation of the message-passing system, 
the send from process 2 to process 1 can be used as an
acknowledgment of the original message
from process 1 to process 2.
If the pattern repeats in a loop,
the send from process 1 to process 2 could 
be used as an acknowledgment of a send from
process 2 in the previous iteration.
A naive implementation would generate a 
separate acknowledgment packet for each
message. By knowing how the
application uses the primitives,
it is possible to generate half as many network
messages.</P>

<P>In another example, application-level
message types are used to order system-level multicast messages. 
There are three types of ordering constraints 
for multicast messages [MS91].

<OL>
<LI>Single-source ordering. If two messages
originate at the same site and they are addressed to the same multicast group, all destinations get them in the same relative order.</LI>
<LI> Multiple-source ordering. If two messages
originate at two different sources, all destinations get the messages in the same relative order.</LI>
<LI> Multiple-group ordering. If two messages are 
delivered to two processes, they are 
delivered in the same relative order even if the 
processes belong to two different but overlapping 
multicast groups and the
messages originate from two different sites.</LI>
</OL>

<P>Parallel applications discussed in this book require
static groups with single- and multiple-source ordering.
To permit the porting of applications between
shared-memory and distributed systems, message-passing systems
are implemented on shared-memory multiprocessors.
A message-passing protocol on a shared-memory
multiprocessor employs control and data transfer 
mechanisms between the sending and the receiving 
processes.
On such architectures there are a variety of methods 
for passing data between address spaces, 
including by value and by reference. 
The performance of these data-transfer mechanisms
depends on the memory architecture.
The shared data structures of the various 
message-passing structures
may use any of a variety of locking algorithms.</P>

<h3><B>1.1.2 Scheduling</B></h3>

<P>In uniprocessors, scheduling is deciding which
process to run and when to run it on the processor. 
In multiprocessors, multicomputers, and
distributed systems, scheduling has another dimension: One must decide
which process must run, when it must run, and  where it can run.
When parallel applications (that is, those with more than one process)
are run on systems with more than one processor, 
gang scheduling can be used to increase the throughput of the 
system, and 
decrease the response time for the application.
The term <I> gang scheduling</I> refers to giving more than one
processor to an application at once, and making sure that
the processes of the application run on the group of processors
at approximately the same time.
Gang scheduling may be preemptive or non-preemptive.</P>

<P>The scheduling system may also be customized to the needs of a workstation 
owner or to those of an application.
When gang scheduling is implemented on a distributed
system, it can be customized in a variety of ways. 
For example, application-specific resources
can be monitored in a system. The rate at which such a resource is
monitored can be specified for different applications. 
One application may require that each of its processes run on a dedicated 
workstation; another may require its nodes to be multiprogrammed.
A typical operating system or system library call to 
schedule the processes of an application on <TT>NUMNODES</TT> 
processors is shown below.</P>

<PRE>schedule(program name, NUMNODES);</PRE>

<P>The underlying system will implement <TT>schedule</TT>
to suit the needs of the application.  An object-oriented interface is shown in Chapter 10 and Appendix B.

<h3><B>1.1.3 Object-Oriented Frameworks</B></h3>

<P>Clearly, there are many possible
optimizations for message-passing 
systems and scheduling systems. 
Object-oriented frameworks are used for designing 
customizable operating systems.
Object-oriented frameworks define sets of classes and their interactions.
A framework comes with guidelines on how instances of classes 
are used together and how they may be subclassed to address the needs of the user. Object-oriented frameworks
have been used to design and implement applications, but their
use in system software development is new.</P>

<h3><B>1.2 The Optimization Approach</B></h3>

<P>In order to optimize system software, three questions must be answered.

<OL>
<LI> What part of the system software can be optimized?</LI>
<LI>What application attributes can be exploited to generate optimizations?</LI>
<LI>What system software structure will allow optimizations
to be easily created and organized for selection based on the application attributes?</LI>
</OL>

<P>This book provides answers to these three questions. In particular,
the optimization of the message-passing and scheduling subsystem of 
an operating system is considered in detail.</P>

<P>The approach advocated in this book is that application attributes can be used to select or create optimized implementations of system services for individual applications, as well as for classes of applications that can be similarly characterized.  When a programmer wants to develop an application and is optimized operating system services for that application, the following strategy is employed.  First, the application is written by the programmer.  Although the applications considered in this book were written in C and C++ they could have been written in any language.  Next, the application is characterized by the programmer using a predetermined set of attributes.  In order to determine the attributes, the program may be run on an instrumented version of the operating system.  Once determined, these attributes are used to select the appropriate system level customized objects.  A selection tool helps in this process.  The customization profile that describes the system objects is then passed to the operating system through the system shell.  A special system call, <TT> inform</TT>, is used to implement this functionality.</P>

<PRE> inform ( framework name, concrete class name list )</PRE>

<P>The operating system then instantiates the appropriate framework, and the application is run on the optimized operating system.  This is the typical model of application execution.</P>

<P>If the application programmer wishes to use special optimizations rather that hose chosen with the selection tool, he or she can code his or her own optimizations.  Such optimizations are performed by extending an existing object-oriented framework that implements a particular subsystem.  For example, to generate a new instance of a message-passing systems is customized.  Extensions can be created only in C++ since the object-oriented frameworks were designed in C++.  If the customizations must run in protected or kernel mode, then these optimizations are dynamically loaded into the operating systems.</P>

<P>The selections tool is invoked, and the inform method is invoked as shown.  The application is then run on the customized operating system.  As the number of optimizations increases and stabilizes, fewer new optimizations will be performed.</P>

<P>The extension technique described is general and can be used on any application domain.  The optimizations provided by one application programmer should not adversely affect other applications.  Therefore, two levels of applications developers are defined: system level and user level.  A system-level application developer can perform customizations that reside in the kernel or in user-level libraries.  A user-level application developer can only perform optimizations at the user level.  The scheduler customizations presented are meant for system-level developers.  Much of the message-passing optimizations discussed, however, can be performed either at user-level or system-level.</P>

<P>In summary, once the optimization coding is complete, there are three steps in the optimization process for an application (see also Figure 1.3).</P>

<! Reference is to big graphic (about 500 pixels wide)>
<a href=do-fig2.gif>
	<! Displayed image is 150 pixels wide>
<center><IMG SRC="do-fig2a.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="1" width=150></center>
</a>
<center><font size=-1><i>Click for a closer look</i></font></center>

<P><center><b> Figure 1.3.  The process of creating an optimized implementation <br>of a system service tailored to an application.</b></center></P>
<p></p>
<OL>
<LI> Characterize the application using predefined attributes.  This may involve running the application on an instrumented version of the operating system.</LI>
<LI> Using these attributes, select the system class that is best suited to the application.  If no appropriate match is found, perform the appropriate coding to create a new optimization.</LI>
<LI> Configure the operating system to run the application with requested system objects.  The operating system may be monitored and the information used to make optimization selection for the next run of the application.</LI>
</OL>

<P>These techniques for the message-passing system are described in Chapter 4 ; for the scheduling system they are described in Chapter 10.</P>

<h3><B>1.3 Summary</B></h3>

<P>Parallel and distributed applications are written as concurrent processes that communicate through message passing.  The message passing may be asynchronous or synchronous.  Message-passing systems provide implementations for explicit data movement primitives, such as <TT>send</TT> and <TT>receive</TT>.  A variety of ways exist to implement message-passing primitives on various architectures, including distributed systems and bus-based, shared-memory multiprocessors.  Distributed systems consist of unreliable network hardware, and the message-passing system must guarantee reliable message delivery.  The performance of the message-passing system on distributed systems is sensitive to the error-handling mechanisms implemented to manage message loss.  On shared-memory multiprocessors, the design and performance of the message-passing system is sensitive to the memory architecture.</P>

<P>Optimizations of a message-passing system can be created by using application-specific information.  These optimizations can then be configured into the operating system to create a customized operating systems for the application.  Parallel applications benefit from specialized scheduling disciplines such as gang scheduling.  Finally, object-oriented frameworks are a valuable technique for organizing customizable message-passing and scheduling systems.</P>


<hr>

