<HTML><HEAD><TITLE> Advances in Concurrency Control and Transaction Processing  -  Introduction</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" 
background="../../sand.gif">

<h3><CENTER><B><I>Advances in Concurrency Control and Transaction Processing, <br>by Krithi Ramamritham and Panos K. Chrysanthis</I></B></CENTER></P></h3>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER"> Chapter 1</H1> 

<hr>



<h2>Introduction</h2>

<p>Databases are being deployed in more and more complex application domains to store and manipulate information that stresses the limits of the functionality as well as performance of traditional transaction processing techniques. The list of such applications includes CAD/CASE (Computer-Aided Design/Computer-Aided Software Engineering), network management. multimedia. and workflows. This list is growing. Further, the ability of transactions to hide the effects of concurrency and failures makes them appropriate building blocks for structuring reliable distributed systems in general. Industry is embracing transactions in a big way, with a near explosion occurring in usage, requirements, and sophistication of transaction processing [220]. Enormous strides have been made in improving the performance of traditional transactions. At the same time. advances have been made to address the inherent limitations of the traditional data and transaction models as well as the traditional correctness criteria. Broadly speaking, recent accomplishments in the area of transaction processing can be classified into: </p>

<ol><li> Techniques based on sophisticated extensions to traditional concurrency control, recovery. and commit processing protocols. These do not affect the way transactions are pranced.

<li>Techniques that depend on a transaction programmer to provide additional input parameters which enable the system to be more clever in processing transactions while satisfying serializability. the traditional correctness criterion. 


<li> Techniques that exploit the semantics of the data items and the operations defined 
on them, the structure of the database. the structural and behavioral properties of the activities in the database, and the correctness requirements of the applications. We refer to these techniques as semantics-based transaction processing techniques.</li>
</ol>

<p>This text is devoted to an in-depth coverage of these topics. It intends to show that after a mild hiatus in the early-to-mid 1980s, the area of transaction processing has become, once again, a very active and challenging area with numerous results of theoretical and practical importance. At the same time, given the nature of the applications that motivated the recent surge of activity. and the thirst for even greater performance, many challenges and open problems remain. In addition. a better understanding of the existing results, in terms of their relative strengths, weaknesses and appropriateness, is also warranted.

<p>Thus, we are aiming this text at various audiences: For researchers and doctoral students to get a quick overview of the area and get a feel for what has been accomplished and, more important, for what remains to be done; for practitioners to appreciate the fact that many recent results can and must be exploited as we strive to build databases with improved functionality and performance requirements. Given the diversity of the audience, we feel that the general form of a tutorial text is the most appropriate one for the presentation of the material, and hence we will subsequently refer to this text as a Tutorial." The actual papers discussed at length in the various sections are not included as part of the text because they have been selected from established journals and conferences and hence should be accessible to the reader. Furthermore, many of them are also easily available through the World Wide Web.

<p>Even though we do include some work that involves performance enhancements to traditional transaction processing, our focus is on extensions to the traditional transaction model, concurrency control, techniques applicable to complex data objects, and relaxations of the standard correctness criteria. To place the extensions in perspective, we discuss the transaction processing issues that arise in the context of active databases, real-time databases, and heterogeneous databases. We also discuss possible directions for future research and development in transaction processing.

<p>It is not our intention to cover traditional transaction processing in this tutorial. However, to make this text self-contained we have included an overview of transaction processing. concurrency control, and recovery concepts in the next chapter. We refer the reader to the recent comprehensive book by Gray and Reuter [134] for a very detailed and thorough treatment of transaction processing in general, with emphasis on traditional transactions. A more formal and shorter introduction can be found in the book b, Bernstein. Hadzilacos. and Goodman [45].

<p>The rest of this introductory chapter is organized as follows. In Section 1.1, <I>(not included in this chapter sample)</I> we elaborate on the motivation behind semantics-based transaction processing and introduce the concept of advanced transactions which, given the needs of advanced database applications, offer better support than that provided by traditional transactions. We conclude this chapter by describing the structure of the remainder of the tutorial. </p>



<h3>1.2 Overview of the Tutorial</h3>

<p>In order to make this tutorial self-contained, Chapter 2 discusses the motivation behind transactions and outlines the properties that enable transactions to mask the effects of concurrency and failures. In this chapter we briefly review concurrency control, recovery, and commit processing techniques that ensure the properties of traditional transactions. Readers already familiar with traditional transaction processing can skip this chapter.

<p>In a database system, in order to keep the useful processor utilization high, it is essential that the system performance be maintained at a high level and the overheads at a low level by optimizing the transaction processing strategies. Also, as we discussed in the previous sections, it is essential to address the new functionality requirements imposed by emerging applications. As mentioned in the beginning of this chapter, the techniques that have been developed to address these requirements can be categorized as follows: </p>

<ol>
<li>Techniques based on sophisticated extensions to the traditional concurrency control, recovery, and commit processing protocols. These do not affect the way transactions are programmed.

<li>Techniques that depend on a transaction programmer to provide additional inputs to the system, with which the system can be cleverer in processing transactions while satisfying serializability.

<li>Techniques that exploit the semantics of the data items and the operations defined on them, the structure of the database, and the correctness requirements of the transactions and the application.</li>
</ol>

<p>Chapter 3 includes a discussion of several techniques that are exemplars of the first and second approaches. Chapters 4, 5, and 6 deal with the third approach. that is, techniques based on the semantics of the objects, the semantics of the transaction model, and the semantics of the correctness criterion, respectively.

<p>Specifically, Chapter 3 is devoted to techniques that are intended to improve upon the performance of databases that adopt traditional approaches such as serializability and locking. Also, escrow transactions, altruistic locking, proclamations, and transaction chopping are presented as means to improve concurrency with minimal changes (from the user's perspective). ARIES, a comprehensive recovery technique that has been implemented in many commercial databases, is also discussed. along with an in-depth comparison of several commercially realized two-phase commit protocols. Chapter 4 concerns concurrency control for arbitrary abstract data type objects. Between them, the proposed techniques exploit different types of concurrency semantics including the semantics of the operations, the operation input/output values. and the organization of the object. Problems and correctness associated with concurrent accesses to the database index object are discussed, along with some possible solutions. A method for extracting concurrency from abstract data type objects is also presented. A discussion of multilevel transactions is also included to show how to handle concurrency and recovery aspects of complex objects.

<p>In order to fill the need for more flexible transaction models that can support the requirements of emerging applications, various advanced transaction models have been proposed. Chapter 5 includes a representative subset of the proposed advanced transaction models and ends with a technique to synthesize such models. (We also refer the reader to a book edited by Elmagarmid [108], containing articles devoted to specific advanced transaction models.) Whereas traditional transactions are based on a narrow interpretation of the notions of visibility, consistency recovery. and permanence, and provide atomicity, serializability, and permanence, the flexibility of a given advanced transaction model depends on the way these four notions are combined. Compared with the traditional transaction model, these models associate more "lenient" transaction properties to provide enhanced functionality while increasing the potential for improved performance.

<p>Many different alternatives to serializability have been proposed in the literature. These range from the standard serializability notion to eventual consistency 1297]. Quasi-serializability [106], predicatewise serializability [178], and so on, are points that lie within this range. Eventual consistency can be viewed as a "catch-all" term with different connotations-for example, requiring consistency "at a specific realtime," "within some time" or "after a certain amount of change to some data," or enforcing consistency "after a certain value of the data is reached," and so on. Whereas serializability and its relaxations are. in general. application and transaction model-independent criteria, eventual consistency. as the examples above show, are application and transaction model-specific. Chapter 6 examines the new correctness criteria in detail. Some of these arise from specific application considerations while others are motivated by the nature of the underlying database system. Cooperative applications are examples of the former. Multidatabases are examples of the latter. Besides considering correctness criteria that arise from relaxing serializability, this chapter also discusses correctness requirements that arise in multidatabases and real-time and active databases.

<p>Given the variety of advanced transaction models, correctness criteria, and new database applications covered in this tutorial (in Chapter 7), we have attempted to provide a bird's-eye view of the relationship between the different proposals. To this end, we present a taxonomy of new correctness criteria and relate the proposed concurrency control techniques and transaction models to these criteria.

<p>A quick review of the papers discussed in the tutorial and of the long list of papers in the bibliography at the end of the tutorial shows that the time has come to apply the ideas in practice rather than. for example, develop yet another advanced transaction model. As it turns out. many of the recent trends in commercial transaction processing make one feel optimistic. Chapter 8 summarizes these trends by discussing transaction processing support found in recent database products. But a lot more needs to be done, in terms of further research and development, in taking recent conceptual advances into the marketplace. This chapter lists the opportunities that lie ahead for researchers as well as practitioners, given the gap that separates the world of theory/concepts and the world of practice. Chapter 8 ends with a discussion of one of the major trends in high performance database design-the use of multiple processor/node systems.

<p>Papers discussed in this tutorial were the basis for graduate-level courses on advanced transaction processing taught at the University of Massachusetts, University of Pittsburgh, and at the Indian Institute of Technology, Madras. We are grateful to Yousef Al-Houmaily, Mohan Kamath, Lory Molesky, Arvind Naithrakashyap, Cris Pedragal-Martin, Jay Shanmugasundaram, and Gary Walborn for their comments on previous versions of this tutorial. Support for our database research from the National Science Foundation grants IRI-9109210, IRI-9210588, IRI-9314376, and IRI-95020091 is gratefully acknowledged. </p>
<hr>

