<html><head><title>IEEE Expert - The Future of Lisp</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img src="../../../expert.gif"><p><a href="../trends.htm">Trends and Controversies</a><ul><p><nobr><b>The Future of Lisp</b></nobr> | <nobr><a href="stilisp.htm">Why the AI community still needs Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="dylan.htm">The Dylan language</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="brief.htm">A Brief Look at C++</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="java.htm">The Java programming language</a></nobr><p><H2> The Future of Lisp </h2><p><b> Craig Knoblock, University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute </b><br><p>The Lisp programming language has been around since the earlydays of AI and is widely used in both research and development.Its strengths include built-in support for symbols and lists,dynamic linking for incremental development, automatic memorymanagement, an extensive library of primitive functions, and excellentdevelopment environments. The combination of these features makesit an ideal language for quickly building and refining prototypes.The last few years have seen a great deal of discussion aboutwhether Lisp is still the best language for building intelligentsystems. Issues such as the size of executables and the speedof execution have made languages such as C and C++ appear veryattractive. In addition, a number of languages, such as Dylan,C++, and Java, have begun offering some of the features that originallymade Lisp so attractive.<P>We have assembled a distinguished group of experts on variouslanguages to discuss the direction language development is takingand the key strengths of the different languages. The particularlanguages discussed here are Lisp, Dylan, C++, and Java. HowardShrobe, who was the technical director for Symbolics, Inc., willdescribe the key features that make Lisp such a useful languagefor AI. Scott Fahlman, who has been involved in both the developmentof Common Lisp and Dylan, will describe how Dylan addresses someof the shortcomings of Lisp while providing its most desirableproperties. Bjarne Stroustrup, the designer and original implementorof C++, will describe the key features of C++, including thosethat are particularly relevant to Lisp programmers. Finally, GuySteele, Jr., who was involved in the design of both Common Lispand Scheme, wrote the widely used reference manual on Common Lisp,and is now involved in the development of the Java language, willpresent the motivation and key features of Java.<P><B>Craig A. Knoblock </B>is a senior research scientist at theUniversity of Southern California's Information Sciences Instituteand a research assistant professor in USC's Computer Science Department.He received his BS in computer science from Syracuse Universityin 1984, and both his MS and PhD in computer science from CarnegieMellon in 1988 and 1991. His current research interests are ondeveloping and applying planning, machine learning, and knowledgerepresentation techniques to the problem of information gatheringand integration. Contact him at <a href=mailto:knoblock@isi.edu> knoblock@isi.edu</a><p><br><B>Interesting URLs</B><P><B>Lisp</B><P><a href=http://www.cs.rochester.edu/u/miller/Lisp-History.html> http://www.cs.rochester.edu/u/miller/Lisp-History.html</a><br><a href=http://www.stat.ucla.edu/develop/lisp> http://www.stat.ucla.edu/develop/lisp</a></ul><P><BR><hr><P><BR><p><nobr><b>The Future of Lisp</b></nobr> | <nobr><a href="stilisp.htm">Why the AI community still needs Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="dylan.htm">The Dylan language</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="brief.htm">A Brief Look at C++</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="java.htm">The Java programming language</a></nobr><p><i><A HREF="../../../expert.htm">IEEE Expert Online</A></i> | <a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a> | <a href="../../../feature.htm">Features</a> | <A HREF="../../../ai-www/ai-www.htm">AI on the WWW</A> | <A HREF="../../../board/board.htm">Editorial Board</A><BR><p><P> <A HREF="../../../../pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</A> | <A HREF="../../../../../cshome.htm">Computer Society home page</A> </P><p>Send comments and questions about <i>IEEE Expert Online</i> to Anne Humphreys and Managing Editor Dick Price, <a href=mailto:ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu,dprice@computer.org>ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu and dprice@computer.org</a></p><p>Send general comments and questions about the IEEE Computer Society's Web site to <a href=mailto:webmaster@computer.org>webmaster@computer.org</a></p><P><font size=-1><i>Copyright (c) Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, Inc. All rights reserved.</P><P>Personal use of this material is permitted. However, permission to reprint/republish this material for advertising or promotional purposes or for creating new collective works for resale or redistribution must be obtained from the IEEE. For information on obtaining permission, send a blank email message to info.pub.permission@ieee.org</P><P>By choosing to view this document, you agree to all provisions of the copyright laws protecting it.</i></font></P></body></html>
