</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>IEEE Expert - Why AI still needs Lisp</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img src="../../../expert.gif"><p><a href="../trends.htm">Trends and Controversies</a><ul><p><nobr><a href="lisp.htm">The Future of Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><b>Why the AI community still needs Lisp</b></nobr> | <nobr><a href="dylan.htm">The Dylan language</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="brief.htm">A Brief Look at C++</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="java.htm">The Java programming language</a></nobr><p><h2>Why the AI community still needs Lisp</h2><P><B>Howard Shrobe, ARPA and MIT</B><P>Lisp has been the main AI programming tool since its invention.What, other than stubbornness, accounts for this longevity? <P>Part of the popularity, of course, stems from the unusually richand dynamic development environments that have traditionally accompaniedLisp systems. These make a broad class of information available-includingcall trees, class hierarchies, and location of source code-sothat the programmer experiences a &quot;hypercode environment,&quot;to use Scott Fahlman's term. In addition, dynamic linking anddebugging allows a programmer to inspect the whole state of aprogram at its point of failure, to make an incremental fix, andcontinue from that spot.<P>Beyond this, however, Lisp is unique in two ways. First, it isan unusually broad spectrum language. If one needs to prototypequickly, Lisp provides a very high level language with a veryrich, highly dynamic environment especially suited to prototyping.If, however, one needs performance and robustness, that is alsoavailable-these advantages have been demonstrated even for performinghighly numerical computations at or above the level of C or C++.<P>Much more significantly, however, Lisp is the ideal language forcreating and embedding other domain- or problem-specific languages.The term embedding is significant. Other languages are certainlyuseful for writing interpreters or compilers for new languages,but there is a world of difference between this approach and theembedding approach. An embedded language has new control structuresand expresses new metaphors, but it also sees all the capabilitiesof the underlying language (such as Lisp). So the developer ofthe new language need not reimplement all the basic structuresthat any language needs. An embedded language extends the underlyinglanguage; it doesn't replace it. Furthermore, many embedded languagesmay co-exist within the common underlying Lisp medium.<P>Why is this of specific importance to AI? Much of what we tryto do when building a knowledge-based system is to define an ontology,a way of looking at the world, that is appropriate to that domain.We also try to pick standard, high-level problem-solving methodsand tailor them to that domain.<P>Each ontology and method has its own natural mode of expression;after all, an ontology's function is to tell you how to look atthe world, what to attend to, and what to ignore. In model-baseddiagnosis, for example, one attends to discrepancies between expectationsand observations and to the causal pathways leading to the observations.In rule-based diagnosis, one attends to rules of thumb that probabalisticallyexplain the symptoms. A system, like Mycin, that approaches diagnosisas rule-based reasoning, obviously wants a clear linguistic expressionfor rules and rule-based reasoning. A model-based system likeGDE emphasizes behavioral models and causality and provides mechanismsfor constraint suspension and truth maintenance.<P>Thus, each of these approaches naturally calls for its own programminglanguage that highlights exactly the things its ontology and problem-solvingmethods tell us are important. Each of these is then realizedas an embedded language in Lisp, as an extension of an underlyingclear and general-purpose computational medium. But in most cases,the domain is broad enough that heterogeneity is inevitable. Inthe real world, model-based diagnosis, for example, is rarelyused in isolation. Every hardware tech quickly learns to firstcheck that the machine is plugged in, which is an instance ofrule-based reasoning.<P>Most AI systems, and certainly those that aspire to model significanthuman competence, will embody many ontologies and problem-solvingmethods, each covering part of the domain. It is here that Lispexcels, for each of these different viewpoints is embedded inthe common underlying soup of Lisp. Within this medium the differentmodes of expression can co-exist and communicate naturally.<P>What about Lisp makes this possible? First, it is highly dynamic.Users can add new types and syntax to the running program at anytime. Second, it is very high level; it takes care of storagemanagement, guaranteeing both the integrity of memory and itsefficient reuse. Together, these mean that a system can both persistover long periods and still significantly change. Third, it isa higher order language that can express patterns of computationas higher order functionals. For example, one can express theidea of traversing a DAG (directed acrylic graph) as a functionalthat takes a root, a child producer, and an operator. Lisp startsat the root and then repeatedly applies the operator to an opennode after which it calls the child producer to that node to geta new set of open nodes.<P>Finally, and from this point of view, most significantly, thelanguage has a natural and simple means of reflecting and manipulatingits own syntax. Lisp's syntax is an uniform expression syntax:it applies a prefix operator to a set of arguments (which arethemselves expressions handled in the same way). Expressions arereflected as list structure and macros are just normal Lisp proceduresthat transform old list structure into new list structure. Usersadd new operators to the language as macros of this kind; theycan arbitrarily transform the expression they handle, thus introducingnew control structures. Macros can also introduce new ways ofdefining things to the language. DEFCLASS, the operator that definesa Common Lisp Object System (CLOS) class, need not be a built-inof the language-it has no special status.<P>When you wish to give linguistic expression to a problem-solvingmethod and its representations, these are the natural tools touse. Think of the patterns of computations that are used in thedomain, create higher order functionals to represent these, andthen use macros to &quot;pretty up&quot; this idea's linguisticpresentation. Also, think of the kinds of entities that existin the world, and then create defining forms that let you easilydescribe these entities to the system.<P>With all these virtues, why does Lisp have a bad reputation? Historyaccounts for much of this. For example, when the MIT Lisp Machinewas first being designed in the mid to late 1970s, we took theperspective that memory and instruction speed were going to becheap and that we should design a system that exploited this availabilityof resources. The first version of the Lisp machine required adedicated 80-Mbyte disk and about 4 Mbytes of memory. As the systemgrew, its requirements became even more unreasonable: one neededat least a 300-Mbyte disk.<P>At the time, these seemed like unreasonable demands, so the ideathat Lisp was overly large and expensive became common knowledge,even to those with no direct experience. But today, you can'tbuy a disk that <I>small</I>. Indeed, Microsoft Office currentlytakes up more of my disk than either of the Lisp Systems I haveon the machine. (Incidentally, the Lisps that ran on stock hardwarewere never as large as the Lisp Machine system.)<P>Ironically, now that the era of cheap hardware resources has finallyarrived, many people believe that Lisp is too much of a resourcehog to use. In my view, the complexity of modern AI programmingdictates that we use some of those abundant hardware resourcesto leverage the one truly scarce resource-our people. Lisp representsan approach with unique power for the AI community. We shouldkeep it.<p><B>Howard Shrobe </B>is currently serving as assistant directorof ARPA's Information Technology Office in the areas of intelligentsystems and software engineering. In his real life he is a memberof the research staff of the MIT AI Lab. He received his PhD andMS from the MIT AI Lab and his BS from Yale. Between 1982 and1992, he was technical director and Vice President of Technologyat Symbolics, Inc. Contact him at <a href=mailto:hes@ai.mit.edu> hes@ai.mit.edu</a><p><B>Interesting URLs</B><P><B>Lisp</B><P><a href=http://www.cs.rochester.edu/u/miller/Lisp-History.html> http://www.cs.rochester.edu/u/miller/Lisp-History.html</a><br><a href=http://www.stat.ucla.edu/develop/lisp> http://www.stat.ucla.edu/develop/lisp</a></ul><P><BR><hr><P><BR><p><nobr><a href="lisp.htm">The Future of Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><b>Why the AI community still needs Lisp</b></nobr> | <nobr><a href="dylan.htm">The Dylan language</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="brief.htm">A Brief Look at C++</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="java.htm">The Java programming language</a></nobr><p><i><A HREF="../../../expert.htm">IEEE Expert Online</A></i> | <a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a> | <a href="../../../feature.htm">Features</a> | <A HREF="../../../ai-www/ai-www.htm">AI on the WWW</A> | <A HREF="../../../board/board.htm">Editorial Board</A><BR><p><P> <A HREF="../../../../pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</A> | <A HREF="../../../../../cshome.htm">Computer Society home page</A> </P><p>Send comments and questions about <i>IEEE Expert Online</i> to Anne Humphreys and Managing Editor Dick Price, <a href=mailto:ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu,dprice@computer.org>ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu and dprice@computer.org</a></p><p>Send general comments and questions about the IEEE Computer Society's Web site to <a href=mailto:webmaster@computer.org>webmaster@computer.org</a></