<html><head><title>IEEE Expert - The Dylan language</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img src="../../../expert.gif"><p><a href="../trends.htm">Trends and Controversies</a><ul><p><nobr><a href="lisp.htm">The Future of Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="stilisp.htm">Why the AI community still needs Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><b>The Dylan language</b></nobr> | <nobr><a href="brief.htm">A Brief Look at C++</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="java.htm">The Java programming language</a></nobr><p><h2>The Dylan language</h2><P><b>Scott E. Fahlman, Carnegie Mellon University</b><P>Dylan is a new object-oriented DYnamic LANguage developed by AppleComputer, with input from Harlequin Inc., Carnegie Mellon University,and many other groups and individuals. Probably the best way foran AI-literate audience to understand Dylan is this: Dylan isan attempt by (mostly) veteran Common Lisp implementors to repackagethe best ideas from Lisp in a form that will be more attractiveand practical for developing mainstream software applications.If Dylan becomes popular for mainstream applications, it willfree AI and expert-system programmers from having to choose betweenlife in the Lisp ghetto or the C++ minefield.<P>Lisp users have always understood that Lisp is more than justan AI language. As Howie Shrobe just pointed out, it is the premierlanguage for evolutionary development of software (defined asany development where you cannot specify precisely what you wantbefore programming begins). Fortunately, the world is finallybeginning to understand that almost all software development isevolutionary in this sense, whether we like it or not. Studieshave shown that for successfully deployed software applications,about 70% of the expense arises after first deployment of thesystem. Initial time-to-market is critically important, and ina successful system the development never ends. So we need languagesand environments that support quick prototyping and easy modificationof programs once they are written, but without sacrificing toomuch runtime performance.<P>If evolutionary development is so important and if Lisp is sogood for this purpose, why hasn't it conquered the world of mainstreamsoftware development? Some would point to Lisp's unconventionalsyntax. Others would point to bad timing or mistakes by the majorLisp software vendors. Still others would blame users who triedsome early or toy version of Lisp, hated the experience, and nevergave the language another chance. Most of us involved in Dylanfeel that the real problem with Lisp was more fundamental: itsdesigners and implementors did not put enough emphasis on thedelivery of efficient, compact software applications. Dylan attemptsto rectify this problem.<P>Beginning with Interlisp and the various Lisp machines, Lisp systemshave provided very extensive suites of tools and libraries toaid the software developer. That is one major source of Lisp'spower for evolutionary development. Unfortunately, most Lisp systemsforce you to carry much of this development environment aroundat runtime, even when an application is well tested, shrink-wrapped,and ready for delivery. The Dylan systems currently being developedwill provide comparable (or better) program development environments,but careful language design has separated the development environmentfrom the delivery environment. When the testing and modificationare over, the user can ask Dylan to spit out a fast, tight applicationprogram, which should be competitive in size and performance withthe corresponding C program. If users want to make further modifications,they go back to the development environment for that.<P>Let's compare Dylan and Common Lisp:<UL><LI>Dylan's object-oriented facilities are modeled after CommonLisp/CLOS, with some simplifications. Dylan has generic functions,multiple inheritance, multiple argument dispatch, and the abilityto create new classes at runtime. Dylan does not allow redefinitionof classes at runtime, though most Dylan environments will allowthis during program development. Dylan does not yet support ameta-object protocol, though we would like to add one later.<LI>In Dylan, the object-oriented facilities were designed infrom the start, not grafted onto an existing language as in CommonLisp or C++.<LI>Like Common Lisp, Dylan provides automatic storage managementwith garbage collection, which is essential for fast developmentof reliable software. Manual storage management is tedious anda major source of subtle bugs. Modern garbage-collection techniquesmake garbage collection much less obtrusive than in older Lispsystems.<LI>While the early versions of Dylan used a Lisp-like parenthesizedsyntax, we later decided to adopt an algebraic infix syntax similarto that of C and Pascal. While some of the Dylan designers (includingme) prefer parenthesized syntax, we decided that it was more importantto lower the entry cost for mainstream programmers.<LI>A language designed for evolution and fast prototyping mustprovide extensive libraries of pre-existing functions. This raisesthe level at which programs are written. Common Lisp bundles mostof these functions into the core language, which makes the languageharder to learn and tends to bloat the runtime environment. Dylanwill provide similar richness, but in the form of separate libraries.The core Dylan language is very lean. The Dylan development environmentswill provide tools to help programmers find the libraries theyneed and ensure that all the libraries used are mutually consistent.<LI>Dylan provides a system of class sealing and type declarationsthat allows the compiler to resolve most method dispatches atcompile time, though some runtime dispatches are still possible.This provides a good balance between efficiency and flexibility.<LI>While it is not required by the language design, most Dylanenvironments will rely on some form of hypercode. Instead of representinga program as a linear string of characters in a file, hypercodetreats a program as a richly interlinked database of objects:pieces of code, comments, documents, pictures, edit history, testinghistory, and so on. An integrated collection of viewers, browsers,and editors access the hypercode.</UL><P>Taken together, these features of Dylan will make it an even betterlanguage for evolutionary software development than Common Lisp,while producing applications with runtime size and efficiencycomparable to that of C. Complete but low-performance implementationsof Dylan are available now; high-performance Dylan environmentsshould become generally available before the end of 1996.<P>It is perhaps worth comparing Dylan briefly to Java. Java is alsoan object-oriented dynamic language, although its heritage owesmore to C++ than to Common Lisp. In terms of features, it is almosta subset of Dylan: it lacks multiple inheritance, multiple argumentdispatch, closures, sealing, and some of Dylan's built-in datatypes.While Java may be a fine language for building simple web-mobileapplets, Dylan should prove to be a better choice for complexprograms. And Dylan can also be a good language for building safe,Web-mobile code.<p><B>Scott E. Fahlman </B>is a principal research scientist in theComputer Science Department of Carnegie Mellon University, wherehe has been on the faculty since 1978. His BS, MS, and PhD degreesare all from MIT. He currently directs CMU's Gwydion project,which is developing an innovative programming environment forthe Dylan language. Earlier, he was one of the core group thatdesigned Common Lisp, and he led the CMU Common Lisp implementationproject. Fahlman also does research on learning algorithms forneural networks and on high-performance processing of biologicalimages. Contact him at <a href=mailto:sef+@cs.cmu.edu</a> sef+@cs.cmu.edu</a><p><B>Interesting URLs</B><P><B>Dylan</B><P><a href= http://www.legend.gwydion.cs.cmu.edu:80/gwydion/>http://www.legend.gwydion.cs.cm u.edu:80/gwydion/ </a><br><a href=http://www.cambridge.apple.com/dylan/dylan.html> http://www.cambridge.apple.com/dylan/dylan.html</a><br><a href= http://www.harlequin.com/>http://www.harlequin.com/</a></ul><P><BR><hr><P><BR><p><nobr><a href="lisp.htm">The Future of Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="stilisp.htm">Why the AI community still needs Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><b>The Dylan language</b></nobr> | <nobr><a href="brief.htm">A Brief Look at C++</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="java.htm">The Java programming language</a></nobr><p><i><A HREF="../../../expert.htm">IEEE Expert Online</A></i> | <a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a> | <a href="../../../feature.htm">Features</a> | <A HREF="../../../ai-www/ai-www.htm">AI on the WWW</A> | <A HREF="../../../board/board.htm">Editorial Board</A><BR><p><P> <A HREF="../../../../pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</A> | <A HREF="../../../../../cshome.htm">Computer Society home page</A> </P><p>Send comments and questions about <i>IEEE Expert Online</i> to Anne Humphreys and Managing Editor Dick Price, <a href=mailto:ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu,dprice@computer.org>ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu and dprice@computer.org</a></p><p>Send general comments and questions about the IEEE Computer Society's Web site to <a href=mailto:webmaster@computer.org>webmaster@computer.org</a></p><P><font size=-1><i>Copyright (c) Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, Inc. All rights reserved.</P><P>Personal use of this material is permitted. However, permission to reprint/republish this material for advertising or promotional purposes or for creating new collective works for resale or redistribution must be obtained from the IEEE. For information on obtaining permission, send a blank email message to info.pub.permission@ieee.org</P><P>By choosing to view this document, you agree to all provisions of the copyright laws protecting it.</i></font></P></body></html>
