<html><head><title>IEEE Expert - A Brief Look at C++</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img src="../../../expert.gif"><p><a href="../trends.htm">Trends and Controversies</a><ul><p><nobr><a href="lisp.htm">The Future of Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="stilisp.htm">Why the AI community still needs Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="dylan.htm">The Dylan language</a></nobr> | <nobr><b>A Brief Look at C++</b></nobr> | <nobr><a href="java.htm">The Java programming language</a></nobr><p><h2>A Brief Look at C++</h2><P><B>Bjarne Stroustrup, AT&amp;T Bell Laboratories</b><P>This note describes some key aspects of C++ and its developmentover the years. The perspective is that of an experienced C++user looking at C++ as a practical tool. No attempts are madeto compare C++ to other languages, although I have tried to answersome questions frequently asked by Lisp programmers.<P>Like all living languages, C++ has grown and changed over theyears. For me, the improvements to C++ have seemed almost glaciallyslow and inevitable; they are natural developments of C++'s owninternal logic and deliberate responses to the experiences ofhundred of thousands of users. To many who wanted to use C++ aggressively,this growth has been frustratingly slow and timid. To some whoconsidered C++ only infrequently, the developments have seem likeunpredictable lurches into the unknown. To others, C++ has simplybeen something peripheral about which little concrete was known,but about which a multitude of strange rumors persisted.<P>However you look at it, C++ has developed significantly sinceits first appearance. Consider a simple function that sorts acontainer and then counts the number of entries between Dahl andNygaard:<P><img src="code1.gif"><P>A container is seen as a sequence of elements from begin() toend(). An iterator identifies an element in a container.<P>This template function will work as described for any containerthat conforms to the conventions of the C++ standard library withelements that can be compared to string literals. For example:<P><img src="code2.gif"><P>The types vector, list, and string are parts of the standard C++library.<P>Naturally, we need not build the string values Dahl and Nyggardinto our little function. In fact, it is easy to generalize thefunction to perform an arbitrary action on a range of values ofarbitrary types in a container of arbitrary type.<P>Clearly, this style of programming is far from traditional C programming.However, C++ has not lost touch with C's primary virtues: flexibilityand efficiency. For example, the C++ standard library algorithmsort() used here is for many simple and realistic examples severaltimes faster than the C standard library qsort() function.<P><B>The C++ standard. </B>C++ is a statically typed, general-purposelanguage relying on classes and virtual functions to support object-orientedprogramming and templates to support generic programming, whichprovides low-level facilities to support detailed systems programming.That fundamental concept is sound. I don't think this can be provenin any strict sense, but I have seen enough great C++ code andsuccessful, large-scale projects using C++ to satisfy me of itsvalidity.<P>By 1989, the number of C++ users, independent C++ implementors,and tool providers made standardization inevitable. The alternativewas to allow C++ to fracture into dialects. In 1995, the AmericanNational Standards Institute (ANSI) and International StandardsOrganization (ISO) C++ standards committees reached a level ofstability of the language and standard library features and adegree of precision of the description that allowed them to issuea draft standard.[1] A formal standard is likely in late 1996 orearly 1997.<P>During standardization, significant features and libraries wereadded to C++. In general, the standards process confirmed andstrengthened the fundamental nature of C++ and made it more coherent.Elsewhere I have described the new features and some of the reasoningthat led to their adoption, along with discussions of older featuresand features that were considered but didn't make it into C++.[2]<P><I>Language features. </I>Basically, Standard C++ is the languagedescribed in <I>The C++ Programming Language</I>[3] with namespaces,runtime type information, and a few minor features added. Amongthe many minor improvements, the refinements to the template mechanismsare the most significant.<P>Here is one of the classical examples of object-oriented programmingin C++:<P><img src="code3.gif"><P>Class Shape is an abstract class-a type that specifies an interface,but no implementation. We can define specific types that conformto that interface. For example, this defines circle to be a kindof shape:<P><img src="code4.gif"><P>We can now manipulate all kinds of shapes through their commoninterface. For example, this function rotates a vector of arbitraryShapes r degrees:<P><img src="code5.gif"><P>For each shape, the appropriate rotate() is called. In particular,if the shape rotated is a circle, Circle::rotate() is called.Consider reading shapes from a stream:<P><img src="code6.gif"><P>Here, we use the dynamic_cast operator to check that the objectsreally are shapes. Any kind of shape, for example a circle, isacceptable. We throw an exception if encountering an object thatis not a shape.<P>This example is rather trivial. However, the techniques presentedand the language features supporting them have helped constructsome of the largest and most demanding applications ever built.<P><I>The standard library.</I> The lack of a solid standard libraryhas always been one of C++'s greatest weaknesses. This lack causeda proliferation of incompatible &quot;foundation libraries,&quot;and diverted novice C++ programmers from getting real work doneinto designing basic library facilities. The latter was particularlynasty because it is far harder to design and implement good basiclibrary facilities than using them. This lack of a standard libraryforced many programmers to deal with advanced C++ features beforethey had mastered the basics.<P>We can classify the facilities provided by the standard libraryas follows:<UL><LI>Basic runtime language support (for allocation, RTTI, andso forth).<LI>The standard C library (with very minor modifications to minimizeviolations of the type system).<LI>Strings and I/O streams (with support for international charactersets and localization).<LI>A framework of containers (such as, vector, list, and map)and algorithms using containers (such as general traversals, sorts,and merges).<LI>Support for numeric computation (complex numbers plus vectorswith arithmetic operations, BLAS-like and generalized slices,and semantics designed to ease optimization).</UL><P>The main criteria for including a class in the library was thatit would somehow be used by almost every C++ programmer (bothnovices and experts), that it could be provided in a general formwithout adding significant overheads compared to a simpler versionof the same facility, and that simple uses should be easy to learn.Essentially, the C++ standard library provides the most commonfundamental data structures together with the fundamental algorithmsused on them.<P>Every algorithm works with every container without the use ofconversions. This framework, conventionally called the STL,[4] isextensible in that users can easily provide containers and algorithmsin addition to the ones provided as part of the standard and havethese work directly with the standard containers and algorithms.<P><B>Tools, environments, and libraries. </B>The stability resultingfrom by the near-completion of the standard is causing a boomin work on programming environments, libraries, and tools. Traditionally,the C++ world has directed much of its effort at producing a languagethat could work effectively for significant industrial projectseven in the absence of advanced tools and environments. This hasnot stopped excellent C++ tools and environments from appearing,but the evolution of the language has been a significant dragon the C++ implementation and tools communities.<P>I expect that really great program development environments willbecome almost universal over the next few years. Already, featurespeople had deemed impossible for C++ are available in shippedproducts. For example, Sun's C++ implementation allows you tostop an executing program at a breakpoint, rewrite a function,and restart using the new function. For decades, people usinginterpreted and dynamically typed languages have taken such thingsfor granted. However, it is one interesting and significant steptoward my goal of having a program development environment thatcombines the strengths of a statically typed language with thebenefits of a sophisticated environment like the ones usuallyassociated with dynamically typed languages.<P>One benefit of a large user community is the availability of libraries.By now, there is a bewildering variety of C++ libraries, but boththe differences between compilers and the lack of a standard libraryhave hampered the development of libraries. The former problemhas led to unnecessary segmentation of the community, and to theemergence of libraries especially designed to allow cross-platformdevelopment. The latter problem forced library developers to re-inventbasic concepts, such as string and list, over and over again.Although it will takes years to work these problems out of thesystem, we now have an alternative and can get on with more importantand interesting tasks.<P>Automatic garbage collection is possibly the issue over whichthe C and Lisp communities have traditionally been most at odds.The Lisp community was certain that memory management was fartoo important to leave to users, and the C community was surethat memory management was far too important to leave to the system.C++ takes an intermediate approach. Automatic garbage collectionis possible, but not compulsory in C++. Traditionally, this simplymeant that C++ programs didn't use automatic garbage collection.Now, however, both commercial and free garbage collectors forC++ have found their way into nonexperimental use. <P>The performance of these collectors is respectable, and in particular,far better than the pessimistic predictions repeatedly voicedover the years. Even where a garbage collector isn't used, welldesigned C++ programs suffer far less from memory management problemsthan traditional C programs. Memory management is often encapsulatedin user-defined types so users don't have to allocate and deallocatememory directly. In particular, standard containers such as string,vector, and list do their own memory management and provide variable-sizeddata structures.<P><I>Programming styles. </I>C++ is a multiparadigm language, meaningthat it was designed to support a range of styles. No single languagecan support every style, but a variety of styles can be supportedwithin the framework of a single language. Where this can be done,significant benefits arise from sharing a common type system,a common toolset, and so forth. These technical advantages translateinto important practical benefits such as enabling groups withmoderately differing needs to share a language rather than havingto apply a number of specialized languages.<P>For starters, C++ supports traditional C-style programming. Otherstyles emphasize the use of classes, abstract classes, class hierarchies,and templates to express concepts and relationships between conceptsdirectly, cleanly, and affordably.<P>Much of the work on styles[5] and patterns[6] in the C++ communityhas focused on finding ways to express ideas from a variety oflanguages and systems in a way that C++ programmers can effectivelyand efficiently use in writing larger production systems. Theemphasis is on effective use of C++'s flexible and extensiblestatic type system.<P><B>References</B><P>1. &quot;The Working Papers for the ANSI-X3J16/ISO-SC22-WG21 C++Standards Committee,&quot; A. Koenig, ed., Am. Nat'l StandardsInst., New York, 1995.<P>2. B. Stroustrup, <I>The Design and Evolution of C++, </I>Addison-Wesley,Reading, Mass., 1994.<P>3. B. Stroustrup, <I>The C++ Programming Language, 2nd ed., </I>Addison-Wesley,1991.<P>4. A. Stepanov and M. Lee, &quot;The Standard Template Library,ISO Programming Language C++ Project,&quot;  Doc, No. X3J16/94-0095,WG21/N0482, Int'l Standards Org., Geneva, 1995.<P>5. A. Koenig and B. Stroustrup, &quot;Foundations for Native C++Styles,&quot;<I> Software Practice &amp; Experience</I>, Vol.25, No. S4, Dec. 1995.<P>6. E. Gamma et.al., <I>Design Patterns</I>, Addison-Wesley, 1994.<p><B>Bjarne Stroustrup</B> is the designer and original implementorof C++ and the author of <I>The C++ Programming Language</I> and<I>The Design and Evolution of C++</I>. His research interestsinclude distributed systems, operating systems, simulation, design,and programming. He is the head of AT&amp;T Bell Labs' Large-scaleProgramming Research department and an AT&amp;T Bell LaboratoriesFellow. He is actively involved in the ANSI/ISO standardizationof C++. He received a Cand. Scient. degree in mathematics andcomputer science from the University of Aarhus, Denmark, in 1975,and a PhD in computer science from Cambridge University, England,in 1979. Contact him at <a href=mailto:bs@research.att.com>bs@research.att.com</a><p><B>Interesting URLs</B><P><B>C++</B><P><a href=http://info.desy.de/user/projects/C++.html> http://info.desy.de/user/projects/C++.html</a><br><a href=http://bach.cis.temple.edu/accu/c-links/> http://bach.cis.temple.edu/accu/c-links/</a></ul><P><BR><hr><P><BR><p><nobr><a href="lisp.htm">The Future of Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="stilisp.htm">Why the AI community still needs Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="dylan.htm">The Dylan language</a></nobr> | <nobr><b>A Brief Look at C++</b></nobr> | <nobr><a href="java.htm">The Java programming language</a></nobr><p><i><A HREF="../../../expert.htm">IEEE Expert Online</A></i> | <a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a> | <a href="../../../feature.htm">Features</a> | <A HREF="../../../ai-www/ai-www.htm">AI on the WWW</A> | <A HREF="../../../board/board.htm">Editorial Board</A><BR><p><P> <A HREF="../../../../pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</A> | <A HREF="../../../../../cshome.htm">Computer Society home page</A> </P><p>Send comments and questions about <i>IEEE Expert Online</i> to Anne Humphreys and Managing Editor Dick Price, <a href=mailto:ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu,dprice@computer.org>ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu and dprice@computer.org</a></p><p>Send general comments and questions about the IEEE Computer Society's Web site to <a href=mailto:webmaster@computer.org>webmaster@computer.org</a></p><P><font size=-1><i>Copyright (c) Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, Inc. All rights reserved.</P><P>Personal use of this material is permitted. However, permission to reprint/republish this material for advertising or promotional purposes or for creating new collective works for resale or redistribution must be obtained from the IEEE. For information on obtaining permission, send a blank email message to info.pub.permission@ieee.org</P><P>By choosing to view this document, you agree to all provisions of the copyright laws protecting it.</i></font></P></body></html>
