<html><head><title>IEEE Expert - The Java programming language</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img src="../../../expert.gif"><p><a href="../trends.htm">Trends and Controversies</a><ul><p><nobr><a href="lisp.htm">The Future of Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="stilisp.htm">Why the AI community still needs Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="dylan.htm">The Dylan language</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="brief.htm">A Brief Look at C++</a></nobr> | <nobr><b>The Java programming language</b></nobr><p><h2>The Java programming language</h2><P><b>Guy L. Steele, Jr., Sun Microsystems Laboratories</b><P>The Java language is a small, simple, object-oriented programminglanguage (designed and implemented by James Gosling, Arthur vanHoff, and their colleagues) that is attracting a lot of interestfor use on the World Wide Web. The Web's hypertext markup language(HTML) allows Web users to access text, pictures, sound clips,and movies using browsers with a simple point-and-click interface.HTML also allows very simple forms of interaction using buttonclicks and forms, but the computation that supports the interactiontakes place on the server machine.<P>The Java system is designed to allow a Web user to access programs.With the same ease that a click pulls text or a picture into thelocal client machine for display, a click in a Java-capable browsercan retrieve a program to be executed on the local machine. Thisprogram can then compute screen presentations, interact with theuser, and communicate with the server that provided it and perhapswith other network sites.<P>This simple concept raises some important language design issues:<UL><LI>Browsers run on many kinds of computers, so Java programsmust be platform-independent, that is, easily executed on differentplatforms.<LI>Because programs are downloaded over the network, a compactrepresentation is desirable to minimize latency before start ofexecution.<LI>Programs should be capable of performing interesting and usefulwork but not so powerful that they can corrupt data, invade privacy,or propagate viruses.</UL><P>The Java language looks very much like a restricted subset ofC++. Such programs are compiled to a byte-coded instruction setfor a virtual stack machine. The instruction set is designed tobe fairly compact for fast transmission of programs through thenetwork. Each Java-capable Web browser must implement an interpreterfor the instruction set of this virtual machine. On-the-fly compilationtechnology, similar to that used in the SELF project, is beingdeveloped to allow a browser to automatically translate heavilyused Java code into native machine code.<P>Why not just use C++ with a compiler targeted to such a virtualmachine? The answer is that, for this application, C++ is toodangerous: it fails to enforce certain elementary safety properties,such as that an array reference actually accesses an element ofthe array rather than some unrelated memory location. Type castsallow the programmer to treat any region of memory as if it wereof any specified data type. Used well, such facilities can beuseful and powerful; but all too many C and C++ programmers failto code the safety checks necessary to defend a program from malicioususe or even innocently intended but unexpected input. (The famousMorris Internet worm exploited, among other tricks, the failureof certain C programs to guard against buffer overflow when datarecords were larger than anticipated.)<P>The Java design tackles the problem of guaranteeing safety andsecurity in three ways. First, the language is designed to preventdangerous coding practices. Array accesses and type casts thatcannot be checked for correctness at compile time are checkedat run time. Dynamically allocated data structures cannot be freedexplicitly, resulting in dangling pointers; the Java runtime systemprovides automatic garbage collection. Second, compiled Java programsare subjected to a verification process before execution by abrowser. The verifier ensures that the compiled code in fact satisfiesthe Java type safety constraints and contains the required codefor runtime checks. Thus a mutant compiler cannot be used to spoofthe browser. Third, there are protocols for programmable authenticationusing, for example, cryptographic methods to ensure that codethat purports to come from a trusted source is the real thing.<P>The primitive Java data types include four sizes of integers (8,16, 32, and 64 bits), two sizes of floating-point numbers (32and 64 bits, IEEE 754), character (16 bits, Unicode), and Boolean(true/false). One of the principal purposes of the Boolean datatype is to catch the extremely common C programming error of writing&quot;if (a=b) ...&quot; when &quot;if (a==b) ...&quot; was intended;if a and b are not of type Boolean, then &quot;if (a=b) ...&quot;in a Java program will provoke an error message from the compiler.Unicode was chosen because the Java system is intended for usein the World Wide Web, not the ISO-LATIN-1 Wide Web; the use ofUnicode will, we hope, make it that much easier to provide trulyinternational support.<P>All other data types, including arrays and character strings,are objects. Every object is an instance of some class, and everyclass is represented by a class object. The Java language supportssingle implementation inheritance but multiple interface inheritance.<P>A class declaration can define fields (class and instance variables)and methods (functions that take arguments may return values).Every class (except Object, which is at the root of the classhierarchy) has a superclass. A class may inherit implementationsfor some of its methods from its superclass; a class may alsooverride a method definition in its superclass by providing itsown definition for the method. Methods may also be overloaded;that is, two method definitions may have the same name if theytake different numbers of arguments or different type of arguments.Overload resolution is performed at compile time, using the compile-timetypes of the arguments. For example, for the method call<pre>monster.mash(boris)</pre><P>there may be several definitions of the method mash. The compile-timetype of the variable boris determines the method signature tobe used for the eventual runtime method lookup. Thus Java methodsare not true multimethods; this is a little less flexible butshifts much of the work of overload resolution from run time tocompile time. On the other hand, the runtime type of the valueof the variable monster is used for the method lookup; this runtimetype may be a subclass of the compile-time type of monster, andsuch a subclass may have overridden the mash method with its owndefinition.<P>An interface is like a class except that it contains no executablecode; only method signatures are declared. A class may claim toimplement more than one interface; the compiler verifies thatthe class (or one of its superclasses) indeed provides an implementationof every method mentioned in each interface. A variable whosedeclared type is a class may refer only to objects of that classand its subclasses, but a variable whose declared type is an interfacemay refer to an object any class that implements the interface.This arrangement gives much of the declarative flexibility ofmultiple inheritance while preserving the implementation simplicityand speed of single inheritance.<P>There are no pointers in the Java language. A variable whose valueis an object actually contains a reference to that object, andseveral variables may reference the same object. So there arepointers at the implementation level, but pointers do not appearexplicitly within the Java type system.<P>Java expression operators and statements are almost exactly thoseof C. Because there are no pointers, there is no unary * or &amp;operator. Also, there is no goto statement. Statements may belabeled, however, and such labels may be used in break and continuestatements. There is a try...catch...finally... statement similarto the try statement of Modula-3, allowing structured handlingof errors and exceptions in a way that can be type-checked bythe compiler.<P>The Java language explicitly supports multithreaded programmingand synchronized access to shared data. Standard Java librariessupport text I/O, simple two-dimensional graphics, user interfacedevices (such as windows and buttons), and network access.<P>The widespread adoption of HTML has made possible the cooperativeyet decentralized (should I say &quot;anarchic&quot;?) constructionof a huge shared hyperlinked database, accessible to millionsof users on a wide variety of hardware platforms. So far the databaseis largely passive; it must be browsed. With the advent of Javawe have the possibility for the cooperative yet decentralizedconstruction of a huge shared hyperlinked software system, accessibleto millions of users on a wide variety of hardware platforms.The Java system has been designed in the best way we know howto make this process as easy, safe, useful, and robust as possible.It will be very interesting to see how it comes out.<p><B>Guy L. Steele, Jr., </B>is a distinguished engineer at SunMicrosystems and has also been an assistant professor of computerscience at Carnegie Mellon and a senior scientist at ThinkingMachines Corp. He received his AB from Harvard in 1975 and hisSM and PhD from MIT in 1977 and 1980. He has published more thantwo dozen papers on the subject of the Lisp language and Lispimplementation, including a series with Gerald Jay Sussman thatdefined the Scheme dialect of Lisp. With Samuel Harbison he wrotethe widely-used <I>C: A Reference Manual </I>(Prentice Hall).He was one of the core group that designed Common Lisp and wrote<I>Common Lisp: The Language </I>(Digital Press). He is also acoauthor of <I>The High Performance Fortran Handbook </I>(MITPress). He is currently writing <I>The Java Language Specification</I>(Addison-Wesley). Contact him at <a href=mailto:gls@livia.east.sun.com> gls@livia.east.sun.com</a><p><B>Interesting URL</B><P><B>Java</B><P><a href=http://java.sun.com> http://java.sun.com</a></ul><P><BR><hr><P><BR><p><nobr><a href="lisp.htm">The Future of Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="stilisp.htm">Why the AI community still needs Lisp</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="dylan.htm">The Dylan language</a></nobr> | <nobr><a href="brief.htm">A Brief Look at C++</a></nobr> | <nobr><b>The Java programming language</b></nobr><p><i><A HREF="../../../expert.htm">IEEE Expert Online</A></i> | <a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a> | <a href="../../../feature.htm">Features</a> | <A HREF="../../../ai-www/ai-www.htm">AI on the WWW</A> | <A HREF="../../../board/board.htm">Editorial Board</A><BR><p><P> <A HREF="../../../../pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</A> | <A HREF="../../../../../cshome.htm">Computer Society home page</A> </P><p>Send comments and questions about <i>IEEE Expert Online</i> to Anne Humphreys and Managing Editor Dick Price, <a href=mailto:ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu,dprice@computer.org>ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu and dprice@computer.org</a></p><p>Send general comments and questions about the IEEE Computer Society's Web site to <a href=mailto:webmaster@computer.org>webmaster@computer.org</a></p><P><font size=-1><i>Copyright (c) Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, Inc. All rights reserved.</P><P>Personal use of this material is permitted. However, permission to reprint/republish this material for advertising or promotional purposes or for creating new collective works for resale or redistribution must be obtained from the IEEE. For information on obtaining permission, send a blank email message to info.pub.permission@ieee.org</P><P>By choosing to view this document, you agree to all provisions of the copyright laws protecting it.</i></font></P></body></htm