<HEAD>
<TITLE> Abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <HR> <A NAME=tex2html37 HREF=section3_1.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html35 HREF=hainesm.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html31 HREF=hainesm.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html38 HREF=section3_1.html> Introduction</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html36 HREF=hainesm.html>On the Design of </A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html32 HREF=hainesm.html>On the Design of </A>
<HR> <P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION0000100000000000000> Abstract</A></H2>
<P>
<em>Lightweight threads are becoming increasingly useful for supporting 
parallelism and asynchronous control structures in applications and 
language implementations.
However, lightweight thread packages for distributed memory systems 
have received little attention.
In this paper, we introduce the design of a runtime interface,
called Chant, that supports communicating threads in a distributed
memory environment.
In particular, Chant is layered atop standard message passing and 
lightweight thread libraries, and supports efficient point-to-point and 
remote service request communication primitives.
We examine the design issues of Chant, 
the efficiency of its point-to-point communication layer,
and the evaluation of scheduling policies to poll 
for the presence of incoming messages.
</em>
<P>
<HR>

</BODY>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>haines@icase.edu <BR>
Mon Aug  1 14:13:52 EDT 1994</I>
</ADDRESS>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT27-B30-333</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA037-000720-B047-159</DOCOLDNO>
