<HEAD>
<TITLE> Introduction</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <HR> <A NAME=tex2html47 HREF=section3_2.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html45 HREF=hainesm.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html39 HREF=subsectionstar4_1.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html48 HREF=section3_2.html> Background</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html46 HREF=hainesm.html>On the Design of </A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html40 HREF=subsectionstar4_1.html> Abstract</A>
<HR> <P>
<H1><A NAME=SECTION0001000000000000000> Introduction</A></H1>
<P>
<A NAME=secintro><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A>
<P>
Threads are becoming increasingly useful for supporting
parallelism and asynchronous events in applications and 
language implementations, for both parallel and sequential machines.
Threads are used in simulation systems <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#csim>[23]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#Grun91>[10]</A> (to 
represent asynchronous events that can be mapped onto single or
multiple processors);
they are used in language implementations <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#Muel93>[19]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#pc>[17]</A>
(to provide support for coroutines, Ada tasks, and C++ method invocations);
and they are used in runtime systems for 
interoperability <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#pcr>[27]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#FKO93>[9]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#panda>[4]</A>.
In light of their increasing use, 
many independent lightweight thread libraries have 
been designed and implemented for workstations and 
shared memory multiprocessors <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#SunLWP>[24]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#BEG93>[20]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#Muel93>[19]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#BLL88>[3]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#ABL91>[1]</A>.
In addition, the Portable Operating System Interfaces (POSIX) committee has 
adopted a standard interface (1003.4a) for lightweight 
threads called <em>pthreads</em> <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#posixthreads>[15]</A>.
<P>
Despite their popularity in shared memory environments,
lightweight thread packages for distributed memory systems
have received little attention.
This is unfortunate: in a distributed memory system,
lightweight threads can overlap communication with computation
(latency tolerance) <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#HaBo93d>[11]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#FeMcN92>[7]</A>;
they can efficiently emulate virtual processors <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#NiHe93>[21]</A>;
and they facilitate dynamic scheduling and load balancing <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#Cho82>[6]</A>.
However, there is no widely accepted implementation of a
distributed memory threads package.
We introduce the term <em>talking threads</em> to represent the 
notion of two threads in direct communication with each other,
regardless of whether they exist in the same address space or not.
Our goal is to design and implement an efficient 
talking threads package based on accepted standards for 
lightweight thread and communication libraries.
This system will be used to support <em>Opus</em> <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#opuslcpc94>[18]</A>,
our task parallel extensions to High Performance Fortran,
and will also provide portable runtime support for other 
languages and systems wanting to exploit task (or thread) parallelism.
<P>
In this paper, we describe the design of our runtime system for
talking threads called <em>Chant</em>.
Chant is capable of supporting both point-to-point (i.e. send/receive)
and remote service request (e.g., remote procedure call)
primitives using standard lightweight thread and communication libraries.
Point-to-point communication primitives
are currently used to support most existing message passing programs,
including those generated by parallelizing 
compilers <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#KoMe91>[16]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#HKT92>[14]</A>,
and form a basis for most portable communication libraries <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#pvm>[25]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#p4>[5]</A>.
Remote service request primitives are 
used to support RPC-style communications <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#splitc>[26]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#RoSa93>[22]</A>,
client-server applications, and put/get operations.
<P>
The remainder of the paper is organized as follows:
Section <A HREF=section3_2.html#secback>2</A> provides background on lightweight thread
and communication libraries.
Section <A HREF=section3_3.html#secdesign>3</A> discusses the design of Chant, and 
Section <A HREF=section3_4.html#secexp>4</A> provides experimental results designed to 
test point-to-point communication between threads.
Section <A HREF=section3_5.html#secrr>5</A> examines related research projects, and 
we conclude in Section <A HREF=section3_6.html#secconc>6</A>.
<P>
<HR> <A NAME=tex2html47 HREF=section3_2.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html45 HREF=hainesm.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html39 HREF=subsectionstar4_1.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html48 HREF=section3_2.html> Background</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html46 HREF=hainesm.html>On the Design of </A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html40 HREF=subsectionstar4_1.html> Abstract</A>
<HR> <P>
<HR>

</BODY>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>haines@icase.edu <BR>
Mon Aug  1 14:13:52 EDT 1994</I>
</ADDRESS>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT27-B30-334</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA037-000720-B047-183</DOCOLDNO>
