<HEAD>
<TITLE> Communication Libraries</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <HR> <A NAME=tex2html77 HREF=section3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html75 HREF=section3_2.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html71 HREF=subsection3_2_1.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html78 HREF=section3_3.html> Design</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html76 HREF=section3_2.html> Background</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html72 HREF=subsection3_2_1.html> Lightweight Thread Libraries</A>
<HR> <P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION0002200000000000000> Communication Libraries</A></H2>
<P>
Communication systems for distributed memory architectures have 
traditionally been provided by the computer vendors, such as 
<em>NX</em> from Intel and <em>Vertex</em> from nCUBE.
In response to the increasing demands of portability, 
several public-domain communication libraries have been established
that provide a portable message passing interface over a wide variety 
of systems.  Among these libraries, p4 <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#p4>[5]</A> and PVM <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#pvm>[25]</A>
have received the most attention.
In an effort to unify the message passing community and 
entice vendors to support a single message passing interface,
the Message Passing Interface (MPI) Forum was established.
The aim of this forum was to 
establish a message passing interface that could be supported directly
by vendors (for efficiency) and would provide a portable interface
for compilers and application programmers.
However, neither the MPI standard nor the other communication
libraries mentioned provide direct support for message passing 
among threads<A NAME=tex2html3 HREF=hainesm.foot.html#76><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/foot_motif.gif"></A>.
<P>
<A NAME=79><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><P><A NAME=extendedlayers><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="" SRC="_3889_figure*77.gif"><P>
<P>
Chant adopts the MPI standard for its system-level communication interface,
and directly uses the MPI support for communication in a heterogeneous
system via the MPI derived data types.
Therefore, the Chant user-level interface is an extension of the POSIX
pthreads interface, with the addition of communication operations 
that have MPI-like syntax and semantics.
The system-level interface is defined directly in terms of 
pthreads and MPI.
<P>
<HR>

</BODY>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>haines@icase.edu <BR>
Mon Aug  1 14:13:52 EDT 1994</I>
