<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html86 HREF=hainesm.html>On the Design of </A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html80 HREF=subsection3_2_2.html> Communication Libraries</A>
<HR> <P>
<H1><A NAME=SECTION0003000000000000000> Design</A></H1>
<P>
<A NAME=secdesign><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A>
<P>
Chant is designed as a layered system 
(as shown in Figure <A HREF=subsection3_2_2.html#extendedlayers>1</A>),
where efficient point-to-point communication provides the basis for
implementing remote service requests and, in turn, remote thread operations.
We now present a discussion of the design issues for supporting
efficient point-to-point communication (Section <A HREF=subsection3_3_2.html#secp2p>3.2</A>),
remote service requests (Section <A HREF=subsection3_3_3.html#secrsr>3.3</A>), and 
remote thread operations (Section <A HREF=subsection3_3_4.html#secthreadops>3.4</A>).
However, we first describe the design of a global thread in Chant,
called a <tt>chanter</tt>.
The Chant user interface, defined as an extension of pthreads,
is given in <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#HCM94>[13]</A>.
<P>
<HR>
