<HEAD>
<TITLE> Global Threads</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <HR> <A NAME=tex2html101 HREF=subsection3_3_2.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html99 HREF=section3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html93 HREF=section3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html102 HREF=subsection3_3_2.html> Point-to-Point Communication</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html100 HREF=section3_3.html> Design</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html94 HREF=section3_3.html> Design</A>
<HR> <P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION0003100000000000000> Global Threads</A></H2>
<P>
<A NAME=secglobal><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A>
<P>
Chant extends the pthreads interface and functionality with a 
new thread object, called a <tt>chanter</tt> thread.
A <tt>chanter</tt> thread is, both conceptually and functionally,
an extension of a <tt>pthread</tt>, where the <tt>pthread</tt> has
been extended with a global thread identifier and the state necessary to
operate on a remote processor.
Chant uses a 3-tuple to define a global thread identifier, composed of a
process group identifier (<tt>group</tt>), a process rank within the group
(<tt>process</tt>), and a thread rank within the process (<em>thread</em>).
This follows from the definition of processes and groups in MPI.
<P>
We can refer to the <em>context</em> of a thread as the unique
process defined by the doublet &lt;<tt>group, rank</tt>&gt;.
A context is defined as a single addressing space, and so all
communication between threads in different contexts must be
message-based, whereas communication between threads within the
same context can utilize shared memory primitives.
In addition to this <em>global identifier</em>, a <tt>chanter</tt> thread
maintains a pointer to the underlying <tt>pthread</tt>, whether locally
or in another context.
Thus a <tt>chanter</tt> thread is simply a wrapper for a local pthread,
and any of the pthread operations may be applied to the underlying 
<tt>pthread</tt> once the wrapper is removed on the local context<A NAME=tex2html4 HREF=hainesm.foot.html#320><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/foot_motif.gif"></A>.
<P>
<HR>

</BODY>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>haines@icase.edu <BR>
Mon Aug  1 14:13:52 EDT 1994</I>
</ADDRESS>
</DOC>
