<HEAD>
<TITLE> Point-to-Point Communication</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <HR> <A NAME=tex2html111 HREF=subsection3_3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html109 HREF=section3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html103 HREF=subsection3_3_1.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html112 HREF=subsection3_3_3.html> Remote Service Requests</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html110 HREF=section3_3.html> Design</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html104 HREF=subsection3_3_1.html> Global Threads</A>
<HR> <P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION0003200000000000000> Point-to-Point Communication</A></H2>
<P>
<A NAME=secp2p><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A>
<P>
Point-to-point communication is defined by the fact that both the sending
thread and receiving thread agree that a message is to be transferred.
Although there are various forms of send and receive primitives,
the understanding on both sides that a communication is to 
occur makes it possible for the operating system to efficiently 
handle the message transfer without buffer copies or user-level interrupts,
assuming that the receive is registered with the operating 
system before the message arrives.
However, if a message arrives before the corresponding receive has
been posted, the operating system will be forced to copy the incoming 
message into a system buffer, since it does not yet know the user-space
destination.
The Chant point-to-point communication layer ensures that no additional
message buffer copies are performed beyond those required by the 
underlying message passing system to handle asynchronous messages 
that arrive before a receive can be posted.
For many high-performance multicomputers with low-latency communication,
this assurance is tantamount to efficient message passing.
<P>
The basic point-to-point operations are <em>send</em> and <em>receive</em>,
where a send operation creates a message and places it into the network
with a given destination, and the receive operation takes a message from 
a specified source and removes it from the network.  Both of these basic
operations can be <em>blocking</em> or <em>nonblocking</em>, with different
degrees of blocking (such as <em>locally-blocking</em> or 
<em>globally-blocking</em>).  For a more thorough treatment of message
passing concepts, the user is encouraged to read the MPI standard <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#mpi>[8]</A>
or related message passing documents.
<P>
We now examine the issue of passing a message from one thread to 
another in greater detail.
To support thread-to-thread communication, Chant must
provide solutions to the following problems:
<P>
<UL><LI> <em>Identifying</em> source and destination threads in messages.
When the operating system receives a message, the header must
contain sufficient information so that the message can be
delivered without having to be copied to an intermediate buffer
for processing.  Thus, the entire global thread identifier must appear
in the header (or signature) of the message.  Since most message
passing systems do not provide an explicit field in the header
for a thread identifier within a context, one must be created.
Chant does this by overloading the user defined <tt>type</tt> field provided
by all message passing systems.  Though this limits both the
number of user-defined types and number of distinct thread
ranks within a context, the alternative would be
to store the thread identifier in the body of the message,
which would require buffer copies on both the sending side (to insert
the thread id) and the receiving side (to remove the thread id).
Chant assumes the burden of correctly packing and unpacking the 
global thread identifier into the message header.
<P>
<LI> <em>Polling</em> for outstanding messages.
The problem of waiting for a message to arrive is solved by polling for
incoming messages, and is done either by the operating system or 
user-level code.
Operating system polling either blocks the entire process
while the operating system spins and waits (typical blocking receive),
or allows the process to continue execution and generates an interrupt when
a message arrives (interrupt-driven reception).
Neither of these solutions are desirable.
Blocking the entire process disables the opportunity to
execute other (ready) threads, effectively disabling a
primary feature of using threads.
User-level interrupts can be disruptive to processor pipelines 
and caches <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#RoSa93>[22]</A>, and are problematic for programmers using 
a non-preemptive threads package, since interrupts effectively make the
system preemptive.
Finally, many message passing libraries, including the proposed MPI standard,
do not support interrupt-driven message reception.
<P>
The alternative to operating system polling (and interrupts) is to
perform user-level polling, in which some piece of user-level code is
responsible for checking for the completion of message receptions.
Although user-level polling avoids the problems of blocking and 
interrupts, it suffers from the inability to respond quickly to 
asynchronous requests, and thus may be an unacceptable implementation
option for real-time applications.
<P>
Chant employs user-level polling, either
by the individual thread that initiates the receive operation,
or by the thread scheduler (or a system-level thread) on behalf of 
the receiving thread.
The <em>thread-polls</em> method has the advantage of
not having to register receive operations with the system,
and will work for any underlying thread package.
However, this approach results in unnecessary context switching 
overheads in the case when a thread is re-scheduled for execution 
but cannot complete the receive operation.
The <em>scheduler-polls</em>
method requires a thread to register a receive with the
scheduler.  It is then removed from the ready queue and placed on
a blocking queue until the message arrives.
This avoids the overhead of scheduling a thread that is not
really ready to run, but forces the scheduler to poll for
outstanding messages on each context switch, and
requires modification of the scheduler.
Alternatively, a hybrid of thread-polls and scheduler-polls
can be utilized, in which a single communication thread takes the
place of the scheduler to restart waiting threads once their
message arrives.  This avoids unnecessary context switching as well
as the need for modifying the scheduler, but requires that this 
thread be scheduled often.
<P>
In Section <A HREF=subsection3_4_2.html#secexppolling>4.2</A>, we address the scheduling decision 
in detail and evaluate various polling options and their influence
on the scheduling of ready threads.  Our goal is to determine which 
polling option yields the best schedules over a variety of simulated
workloads.
Our results indicate that, although some form of scheduler 
polling for the threads results in the best performance,
having the threads poll for themselves is only slightly worse in the 
average case.
This result is significant because some underlying lightweight thread 
packages won't allow modification of the scheduler's 
activities <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#Muel93>[19]</A>,
but all packages can safely implement the thread-polls policy.
</UL>
<P>
<HR> <A NAME=tex2html111 HREF=subsection3_3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html109 HREF=section3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html103 HREF=subsection3_3_1.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
