<HEAD>
<TITLE> Remote Thread Operations</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <HR> <A NAME=tex2html129 HREF=section3_4.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html127 HREF=section3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html123 HREF=subsection3_3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html130 HREF=section3_4.html> Experimental Results</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html128 HREF=section3_3.html> Design</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html124 HREF=subsection3_3_3.html> Remote Service Requests</A>
<HR> <P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION0003400000000000000> Remote Thread Operations</A></H2>
<P>
<A NAME=secthreadops><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A>
<P>
As well as adding communication primitives to a lightweight thread
interface, Chant must support the existing lightweight thread
primitives that are inherited from the underlying thread package,
and extend them to provide a coherent interface for global threads.
This implies that thread functions which are not affected by the 
location of a thread remain supported but unchanged, while those
sensitive to the location of a thread be extended to work with
<tt>chanter</tt> threads.  In some cases, this amounts to invoking 
a remote procedure call which will execute the desired function 
on a thread within a specified context.
In most cases, however, some additional ``glue'' is needed to 
ensure the proper semantics of the operation.  For example,
consider the <tt>pthread_chanter_join()</tt> operation, which
blocks the calling thread until the specified thread has 
completed.  For two threads within the same context, this 
operation is handled by the underlying library call for join,
<tt>pthread_join()</tt>.
However, when the calling thread and argument thread are in
separate contexts, executing the join in the remote context
is not sufficient since pthreads has no knowledge of the 
calling thread in another context.
Therefore, a remote join is accomplished by adding,
to the list of exit handlers for the argument thread,
a routine which will send a message back to the calling context
with the effect of unblocking the calling thread.
Also, since a remote thread creation involves passing the thread
function across context boundaries, <tt>chanter</tt> thread
functions must be registered with the RSR server thread
before the remote create operation is issued.
Each remote thread operation requires a different level of 
support, but the essential work is always handled by the 
underlying thread package.
<P>
The result is a user-level interface that is a logical extension
of pthreads, and for which global thread identifiers can be 
passed into standard routines (such as join), while maintaining
the semantics of the underlying thread primitives.
<P>
<HR> <A NAME=tex2html129 HREF=section3_4.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html127 HREF=section3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html123 HREF=subsection3_3_3.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html130 HREF=section3_4.html> Experimental Results</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html128 HREF=section3_3.html> Design</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html124 HREF=subsection3_3_3.html> Remote Service Requests</A>
<HR> <P>
<HR>

</BODY>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>haines@icase.edu <BR>
Mon Aug  1 14:13:52 EDT 1994</I>
