<HEAD>
<TITLE> Point-to-Point Communication Overheads</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <HR> <A NAME=tex2html151 HREF=subsection3_4_2.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html149 HREF=section3_4.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html143 HREF=section3_4.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html152 HREF=subsection3_4_2.html> Message Polling</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html150 HREF=section3_4.html> Experimental Results</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html144 HREF=section3_4.html> Experimental Results</A>
<HR> <P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION0004100000000000000> Point-to-Point Communication Overheads</A></H2>
<P>
<A NAME=secexpoverhead><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A>
<P>
In the first experiment, we measure the cost of sending and receiving 
messages on the Paragon using two processes and the NX primitives,
and compare this to the cost of sending and receiving messages
between two threads on two Paragon processors (one per processor)
using Chant.
In a sense, this is a worst-case scenario for a thread system.
Chant is using the exact same communication calls as the process version,
and having to add some amount of overhead per message to handle
packing and unpacking the message header with the thread identifier,
as well as a possible context switch.
However, we are not providing extra computation threads whose computations
could overlap the communication latencies.
<P>
<A NAME=156><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><P><A NAME=overheaddat><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="" SRC="_3889_table148.gif"><P>
<A NAME=161><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><P><A NAME=overheadplot><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="" SRC="_3889_figure159.gif"><P>
<P>
Table <A HREF=subsection3_4_1.html#overheaddat>1</A>
(also depicted in Figure <A HREF=subsection3_4_1.html#overheadplot>2</A>)
gives the results of this experiment in terms 
of average time per message (<IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="" SRC="_3889_tex2html_wrap596.xbm">) and overhead relative to the 
process-based method.  
To get accurate results, each test consisted of 100,000 message exchanges,
and each test was repeated four times.
The numbers given represent an average of these runs.
For the thread-to-thread communication, we actually implemented two 
polling policies: thread-based polling and scheduler-based polling.
The numbers presented in Table <A HREF=subsection3_4_1.html#overheaddat>1</A> and 
Figure <A HREF=subsection3_4_1.html#overheadplot>2</A> represent the thread-based polling technique.
Since a context switch is needed to invoke the scheduler, 
the scheduler-based polling technique incurs an extra context switch
for each receive operation, while the thread-based polling technique
is optimized to avoid the context switch when there are no other 
threads on the ready list.
As a result, the scheduler-based polling method runs 5%slower
(on average) than the thread-based scheduling method.
<P>
These results indicate that Chant adds only a small amount of overhead 
(averaging 5%) to the underlying point-to-point communication layer
of the Paragon.
<P>
<HR>

</BODY>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>haines@icase.edu <BR>
Mon Aug  1 14:13:52 EDT 1994</I>
