<HEAD>
<TITLE> Message Polling</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <HR> <A NAME=tex2html159 HREF=section3_5.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html157 HREF=section3_4.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html153 HREF=subsection3_4_1.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html160 HREF=section3_5.html> Related Research</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html158 HREF=section3_4.html> Experimental Results</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html154 HREF=subsection3_4_1.html> Point-to-Point Communication Overheads</A>
<HR> <P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION0004200000000000000> Message Polling</A></H2>
<P>
<A NAME=secexppolling><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A>
<P>
In Section <A HREF=subsection3_3_2.html#secp2p>3.2</A> we introduced the problem of 
polling for outstanding messages in point-to-point communication.
We now take a closer look at that problem by measuring three 
scheduling algorithms and determining their effect on the performance
of the system.
<P>
Recall that there are essentially two methods of polling
for an outstanding message: 
having the receiving thread poll for itself,
which we refer to as the <em>thread polls</em> algorithm, 
and having the scheduler (or system thread) poll on the 
receiving thread's behalf, called <em>scheduler polls</em>.
The scheduler polls method is based on a list of polling requests
that are examined at each scheduling point to see if any outstanding
messages have arrived.
Ideally, this would be implemented as a single call to the 
communication system, inquiring whether <em>any</em> of the outstanding 
receive requests have been satisfied.
If so, the value returned, such as the tag,
would designate a 
waiting thread, which could then be enabled for execution.
On some communication systems this functionality is provided;
for example, MPI provides the <tt>MPI_TEST_ANY</tt> primitive,
which will test for 
the completion of any outstanding requests from a given process.
However, on other systems, such as NX and p4,
this functionality is not directly supported.
Therefore, the algorithm needs to be modified so that each outstanding 
request will be tested in turn.
This implies that all posted receives are checked at <em>each</em>
context switch.
When a polling request is finally satisfied, the corresponding
thread is then scheduled for execution.
We refer to this version of the scheduler polling algorithm as
<em>scheduler polls (WQ)</em>, where WQ stands for ``waiting queue.''
<P>
Another variation of the scheduler polling strategy
is to eliminate the list of polling requests altogether.
As with the <em>thread polls</em> method, all threads waiting 
for messages are left on the ready list.
However, each thread stores its receive request handle
in its thread control block (TCB), which is a data structure 
that defines a thread and its state.
When the scheduler is invoked to perform a context switch,
it selects the next available TCB from the ready list and 
determines if a receive request is pending.
If not, the thread's context is restored and the thread resumes 
execution.
Otherwise, the pending message is polled for by the scheduler.
If the message has arrived, the thread is restored, otherwise
the TCB is placed back on the ready list and the next TCB is
retrieved.
The advantage of this approach is that it does not have to 
poll for all outstanding requests at each context switch,
yet unlike the <em>thread polls</em> method,
the overhead of fully restoring a thread's context is not 
incurred if the thread is not ready to execute.
The disadvantage of this approach is that response time to 
messages may be slowed, since requests are only checked according
to the position of the threads on the ready list.
We refer to this version of the scheduler polling algorithm as 
<em>scheduler polls (PS)</em>, where PS stands for ``partial switch''.
<P>
<A NAME=187><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><P><A NAME=threadcode><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="" SRC="_3889_figure180.gif"><P>
<P>
Using the point-to-point communication layer of Chant, we encode
the above three polling algorithms
and test the system to measure their relative performance.
Figure <A HREF=subsection3_4_2.html#threadcode>3</A> presents the thread code used in the 
experiment, where
the parameters <tt>alpha</tt> and <tt>beta</tt> 
represent the number of iterations for a generic
computation, and were modified to affect the average number of 
outstanding receive requests (or waiting threads) at each 
scheduling point.
By increasing <tt>alpha</tt>, we increase the number 
of threads waiting for outstanding requests.
Intuitively, increasing the time between the posting of a receive and the 
execution of the corresponding send will increase the number 
of threads waiting for messages.
<P>
<A NAME=322><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><P><A NAME=poll100dat><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="" SRC="_3889_table*194.gif"><P>
In the first experiment, 
fix <tt>beta</tt> at 100 and vary <tt>alpha</tt> from 100 to 100000,
then run the experiment with two processors and 12 threads per processor,
with each thread performing 100 iterations of the outer send/receive loop.
Table <A HREF=subsection3_4_2.html#poll100dat>2</A> presents these results, where <em>Time</em> represent the 
total running time (ms) of the test,
<em>CtxSw</em> represents the total number of complete
context switches performed, and <em>msgtest</em> 
represents the total number of <tt>msgtest</tt> calls attempted.
The data indicates that the <em>scheduler poll (PS)</em> algorithm 
yields the lowest running times.
This is because the <em>thread polls</em> algorithm must perform full
context switches at each scheduling opportunity to check for the 
completion of a message, while the <em>scheduler polls (PS)</em>
algorithm need only perform a partial switch to check for outstanding 
messages.  This can be seen by comparing the total number of context switches
for the two methods.
However, the <em>thread polls</em> algorithm performs,
on average, only 10%worse than the <em>scheduler polls (PS)</em>
algorithm.  Thus, for a thread package that does not support the 
ability to modify the scheduler's behavior as required for the 
<em>scheduler polls (PS)</em> algorithm, we have found that only a
10%degradation of performance will result from using the 
<em>thread polls</em> algorithm, which can be applied to any 
lightweight thread package.
The data also shows that the <em>scheduler polls (WQ)</em> algorithm
performs much worse than the other two, as a result of having to 
check all outstanding requests at each scheduling opportunity.
As we can see from the number of <tt>msgtest</tt> calls performed 
by the three algorithms,
the <em>scheduler polls (WQ)</em> algorithm performs far more <tt>msgtest</tt>
calls than the other two algorithms, accounting for its degraded 
performance.
However, the <em>scheduler polls (WQ)</em> algorithm does achieve the lowest
number of context switches of the three methods, since threads are
only switched when they are ready to run.  For systems that 
could implement this algorithm as intended, with a 
single <tt>msgtestany</tt> call rather than a test for each individual message,
we expect the relative performance of this algorithm to change.
We hope to test this hypothesis on a future version of Chant using 
the MPI communication system, which supports the <tt>msgtestany</tt>
functionality.
<P>
The same results are obtained when we vary the average number of waiting
threads.  Both 
Table <A HREF=subsection3_4_2.html#poll0dat>3</A> (<tt>beta = 0</tt>) and
Table <A HREF=subsection3_4_2.html#poll1000dat>4</A> (<tt>beta = 1000</tt>) show that 
<em>scheduler polls (PS)</em> performs best while the number of
<tt>msgtest</tt> calls by <em>scheduler polls (WQ)</em> degrades its
performance.
<P>
<A NAME=323><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><P><A NAME=poll0dat><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="" SRC="_3889_table*246.gif"><P>
<A NAME=324><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><P><A NAME=poll1000dat><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="" SRC="_3889_table*270.gif"><P>
