<HEAD>
<TITLE> Related Research</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <HR> <A NAME=tex2html169 HREF=section3_6.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html167 HREF=hainesm.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html161 HREF=subsection3_4_2.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html170 HREF=section3_6.html> Conclusions</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html168 HREF=hainesm.html>On the Design of </A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html162 HREF=subsection3_4_2.html> Message Polling</A>
<HR> <P>
<H1><A NAME=SECTION0005000000000000000> Related Research</A></H1>
<P>
<A NAME=secrr><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A>
<P>
Chant provides an extension to the pthreads interface for supporting
distributed memory communication primitives, including point-to-point
and remote service request operations.
<P>
There have been several application systems which have employed
lightweight threads capable of interprocessor communication,
such as <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#NiHe93>[21]</A><A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#HaBo93c>[12]</A>, however they do not attempt to 
provide a usable interface to communicating threads.
<P>
NewThreads <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#FeMcN92>[7]</A> provides an object-oriented thread
library for the Intel IPSC/860 which supports point-to-point
communication between <em>ports</em>.
Ports provide a global namespace for communication and
are mapped to threads using a global namespace server.
The thread interface resembles Presto <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#BLL88>[3]</A>,
which is a thread library for shared memory multiprocessors.
Although communication using ports facilitates thread migration
(since the port is migrated with the thread), 
most existing message passing programs and parallelizing compilers
do not support this form of addressing.
<P>
Nexus <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#FKO93>[9]</A> defines a runtime interface to support
interoperability among programming languages for distributed
memory multiprocessors, in which a small set of thread primitives
is defined (excluding priority-based scheduling and thread-local data).
Rather than thread-to-thread communication, the system uses
remote service requests as its basic communication facility
between processor contexts.
<P>
Panda <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#panda>[4]</A> provides a portable platform for the support of
parallel programming languages, namely Orca, and
provides an interface for threads (a cross between cthreads and
pthreads), a remote procedure call mechanism, and totally-ordered
group communication among the threads.  However, direct point-to-point
communication primitives are not supported.
<P>
There are many generic lightweight thread packages for
uniprocessor or shared memory multiprocessor systems, including
cthreads <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#BEG93>[20]</A>, Presto <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#BLL88>[3]</A>,
the Sun lightweight process library (LWP) <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#SunLWP>[24]</A>,
Fastthreads <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#ABL91>[1]</A>,
and a public-domain library implementation of 
pthreads <A HREF=bibliography3_8.html#Muel93>[19]</A>.
None of these packages, however, directly address the issue of
communication between threads in different address spaces.
<P>
<HR>

</BODY>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>haines@icase.edu <BR>
Mon Aug  1 14:13:52 EDT 1994</I>
</ADDRESS>
