<HEAD>
<TITLE> Conclusions</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <HR> <A NAME=tex2html179 HREF=sectionstar3_7.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html177 HREF=hainesm.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html171 HREF=section3_5.html><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/previous_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html180 HREF=sectionstar3_7.html> Acknowledgments</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html178 HREF=hainesm.html>On the Design of </A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html172 HREF=section3_5.html> Related Research</A>
<HR> <P>
<H1><A NAME=SECTION0006000000000000000> Conclusions</A></H1>
<P>
<A NAME=secconc><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="http://www.icase.edu/~haines/images/invis_anchor.xbm"></A>
<P>
Threads are an emerging model for supporting
parallelism and asynchronous events in applications and
language implementations, for both parallel and sequential machines.
Despite their popularity and utility,
lightweight thread packages for distributed memory systems have
received little attention.
<P>
In this paper, we introduce the notion of <em>talking threads</em> as
a set of lightweight threads capable of communication in a 
distributed memory environment, and describe the design of a 
talking threads system called <em>Chant</em>.
Chant is capable of supporting both point-to-point
(e.g., send/receive) and remote service request
(e.g., remote procedure call) communication primitives.
Chant presents the user with an interface that extends
pthreads, the POSIX standard interface for lightweight threads,
with a global thread object called a <tt>chanter</tt>.
Portability and efficiency are achieved by providing 
employing a system interface that relies on existing libraries
(pthreads and MPI) for providing lightweight thread 
and communication capabilities.
<P>
We have implemented Chant as a layered runtime system, and 
are currently running on a network of Sun workstations and 
the Intel Paragon multicomputer.  We have determined that the
relative overhead of the Chant point-to-point communication layer
against NX on the Intel Paragon averages less than 6%.
We have also implemented and measured three message polling 
policies and found that having the threads poll for their
own outstanding messages can cause unnecessary context switches,
and that having the scheduler poll on behalf of threads can 
be an efficient alternative.
<P>
We are currently using Chant to support the Opus language project,
as well as determining the effectiveness of using lightweight threads
for improving the efficiency of certain scientific and graphics
applications.
Additional information on Chant, including an electronic copy of 
this and other papers, papers can be found at:
<tt>http://www.icase.edu/<IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="" SRC="_3889_tex2html_wrap598.xbm">haines/html/chant.html</tt>
<P>
<HR>

</BODY>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>haines@icase.edu <BR>
Mon Aug  1 14:13:52 EDT 1994</I>
