<HTML><HEAD><TITLE> Physical Layer Interfaces and Protocols  -  Preface</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" 
background="../../sand.gif">

<h3><CENTER><B><I>Physical Layer Interfaces and Protocols, by Uyless Black</I></B></CENTER></P></h3>

<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">PREFACE</H1>

<hr>

<P>A recurring frustration for the data communications user is the difficulty in or inability to decipher vendors&#39 descriptions of their physical layer products, such as modems and multiplexers. For example, typical sales brochures or specification sheets describe a modem in such terms as &#34 . . . conforms to EIA-232/V.24 and V.28 recommendations. . . . full duplex channel separation on a two-wire circuit is achieved by frequency division . . . subchannels employ four-phase (dibit) shifts of 45&#176, 135&#176, 225&#176, and 315&#176 . . . signaling rate is 2400 baud with a 9600 bit/s line speed. . . .&#34.</P>

<P>Such a description almost sounds like a foreign language. Indeed it is, if the user does not take the time to learn what the terms actually mean.</P> 

<P>The experienced data communications professional may understand all these terms but does not have a ready reference to use in comparing the many physical layer interfaces available today. The required references and standards are published in separate documents by several different organizations.</P>
<P>This book (1) explains the concepts and ideas associated with physical layer protocols and (2) provides the reader with a convenient summary of the industry&#39s most widely used physical layer interface standards.
The book focuses primarily on the physical interfaces between a user device (e.g., computer, terminal) and a communications line interface device (e.g., modem, data service unit, multiplexer). The book emphasizes the systems used on the public telephone network and, therefore, serial communications. Much of the material, however, is applicable to private-wired systems as well.</P>

<P>Several of the interfaces are used on either analog or digital lines. Indeed, many of these protocols make no distinction between signaling techniques because they describe only the user side of the physical layer interface and do not describe the communications (line) side. The book concentrates on the user-device side of the interface, since many data communications users are charged with cabling and connector selection between the user device and the communications line termination equipment, such as a modem or multiplexer. Where applicable, the line side is also described.</P>

<P>A considerable portion of the book is devoted to the ITU-T V series recommendations. Until the past few years, the V series were of limited interest in North America, although they are used extensively in Europe. The ITU-T interfaces are now widely used in North America as well, surpassing the Bell standards&#39 interfaces in acceptance by vendors.</P>

<P>A section is devoted to digital interfaces. The T1 carrier system and the digital data system (DDS) are examined because of their wide use.</P>

<P>While this guide explains many physical layer interfaces in some detail, the reader should obtain vendor descriptions or the specific standards manual for a more thorough examination of a product or standard.</P>

<hr>

