<HTML><HEAD><TITLE> Physical Layer Interfaces and Protocols  -  Sample Chapter</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" 
background="../../sand.gif">

<h3><CENTER><B><I>Physical Layer Interfaces and Protocols, by Uyless Black
<br>Sample Chapter </I></B></CENTER></h3>


<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">CHAPTER 5</H1>
<hr>

<H2>THE V SERIES MODEMS</H2> 

<P>This chapter provides a reference guide for readers who need information on the specific types of ITU-T-specified modems. Most of these modems use the "foundation" V specifications explained in Chapter 3. Each V series modem is described in relation to the material in Table 2-1. The older modems, such as V.21, are retained in this second edition as a basis of comparison to the newer modems.
For more detail, refer to the ITU-T publication <I>Data Communications over the Telephone Network: Recommendation for the V Series.</I> The ITU-T address is provided in Appendix A.</P>

<P><B>Coding Architecture for V.17, V.32, 
V.32bis, and V.33</B></P>

<P>Before we examine the V Series modems, it will prove helpful to pause briefly to state that the V.17, V.32, V.32bis, and V.33 modems use similar techniques for the coding and decoding of user bits and the modulation and demodulation of these bits onto or from the carrier (The reader may wish to review the material in Chapter 1 on trellis coded modulation).</P>
All these modems use a variation of the scheme depicted in Figure 5-1. The Q bits represent the bits that are sent to the modem from the user DTE across the EIA-232/V.24 transmit interchange circuit. The bits are designated Q1<SUB>n</SUB> through Q6<SUB>n</SUB> in Figure 5-1 to show that one to six bits may be examined by the modem at one time. The n designates the sequence of the bit in each group.</P>

<P><center><b> Figure 5-1.  Coding Architecture for V.17, V.32bis, and V.33 Modems</b></center></P>
<! Reference is to big graphic (about 500 pixels wide)>
<a href=fig-51.gif>
	<! Displayed image is 150 pixels wide>
<center><IMG SRC="fig-51a.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="1" width=150></center>
</a>
<center><font size=-1><i>Click for a closer look</i></font></center>

<P>The manner in which the bits are grouped depends upon the bit rate of the modem. For example, a V.32 modem processes four bits at a time. Since V.32 operates at 2400 baud, the bit rate is 9.6 kbits/s (4 x 1400 = 9600). As another example, the V.17, V.32bis, and V.33 modems can operate at 14.4 kbits/s. These configurations use bits Q1<SUB>n</SUB>  through Q6<SUB>n</SUB>  to achieve a bit rate of 14.4 kbits/s (6 x 2400 = 14,400).</P>

<P>The differential encoder processes bits Q1<SUB>n</SUB>  and Q2<SUB>n</SUB>  in accordance with specific encoding rules to produce bits Y1<SUB>n</SUB>  and Y2<SUB>n</SUB>  (these rules are explained in each ITU-T recommendation). In turn, these bits are input to a convolutional encoder that produces as output Y0n, Y1<SUB>n</SUB>, and Y2<SUB>n</SUB>. These bits are then fed into the signal element mapping operation that produces a signal structure for the output signal. Examples of signal structures are shown later in this chapter.</P>

<P>The number of Q3<SUB>n</SUB>  through Q6<SUB>n</SUB>  bits that accompany the Y bits into the signal element mapping operation varies and depends upon the bit rate of the modem. As stated earlier, the use of Q1<SUB>n</SUB>  through Q6<SUB>n</SUB>  bits yields a bit rate of 14.4 kbits/s. Lesser rates simply use fewer Q inputs into the encoders and signal element mapping.</P>

<P><B>V.17: A Two-Wire Modem for Facsimile Applications with Rates up to 14,400 Bits/s</B></P>

<P>V.17 was published by the ITU-T in 1991 to define the operations for a modem used exclusively for high-speed facsimile applications. This modem operates at rates of up to 14.4 kbits/s in the synchronous mode, although it is capable of transmitting and receiving traffic at rates of 7.2, 9.6, 12.0 and 14.4 kbits/s.</P>

<P>The V.17 architecture is quite similar to several ITU-T recommendations for modems published in the 1984 Red Book and the 1988 Blue Book. For example, it uses a coding scheme similar (but not identical) to V.32 for the 9.6 kbits/s operation (see Table 5-25). Its signal structure (constellation pattern) for 9.6 kbits/s is also quite similar to V.32 (See Figure 5-3). Since these operations are discussed later in this chapter, they will not be repeated here, but be aware that V.17 uses slightly different bit patterns from V.32.</P>

<P><B>V.19: Modems for Parallel Data Transmission Using Telephone Signaling Frequencies</B></P>

<P>Frequencies on this type of modem are used to transmit the character sets in Table 5-1. This recommendation allows the push-button telephone to be used for sending data. For example, a user can key in a bank account number through a telephone by using the telephone push buttons.</P>

<Table Border=1 Width=80% Align=center Colspec="L20 L20 L20 L20 L20 ">
<Caption Align=Top><b>TABLE 5-1.  V.19 Frequency Pairs</b></Caption>

<!-- Row # 1 -->
<Tr><Td align=center>&nbsp;</Td><Td align=center><B><Center>B1 = 1209 Hz</B></CENTER></Td><Td align=center><B><Center>B2 = 1336 Hz</B></CENTER></Td><Td align=center><B><Center>B3 = 1447 Hz</B></CENTER></Td><Td align=center><B><Center>B4 = 1633 Hz</B></CENTER></Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 2 -->
<Tr><Td align=center><Center>A1 = 697 Hz</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>1</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>2</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>3</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>A</CENTER></Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 3 -->
<Tr><Td align=center><Center>A2 = 770 Hz</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>4</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>5</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>6</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>B</CENTER></Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 4 -->
<Tr><Td align=center><Center>A3 = 852 Hz</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>7</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>8</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>9</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>C</CENTER></Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 5 -->
<Tr><Td align=center><Center>A4 = 941 Hz</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>*</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>0</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>#</CENTER></Td><Td align=center><Center>D</CENTER></Td></Tr>

</Table>

<P><B>V.20: Parallel Data Transmission Modems Standard for Use in the General Switched Telephone Network</B></P>

<P>The frequencies in Table 5-2 are recommended for systems where a large number of sending stations transmit to a central station. As shown in the table, one frequency from each group can be transmitted simultaneously.</P>

<Table Border=1 Width=80% Align=Center Colspec="L20 L20 L20 L20 L20 ">
