<FONT SIZE="2"><small><SUP>1</SUP></small> All essential interchange circuits and any others that are provided shall comply with the requirements of recommendation V.24. All interchange circuits indicated by an X shall be properly terminated in the data equipment and in the data circuit-terminating equipment in accordance with the appropriate recommendation. <br>
<small><SUP>2</SUP></small> Not essential for four-wire full duplex continuous carrier operation.</FONT></P>

<P><B>V.27bis 4800/2400 Bit/s Modem with Automatic Equalizer Standardized for Use on Leased Telephone-Type Circuits</B>
<P>The characteristics of V.27bis are very similar to V.27, except this recommendation uses different equalization techniques and provides for 2000 or 4800 bit/s speeds. Its use is more prevalent in Europe than in North America. Its principal characteristics are as follows:
<OL>
<LI>It operates in an FDX or HDX modem over four-wire leased circuits or in an HDX over two-wire leased circuits.
<LI>At a 4800 bit/s operation, modulation is eight-phase differentially encoded as described in recommendation V.27.
<LI>At a reduced rate capability at 2400 bits/s, it uses four-phase differentially encoded modulation as described in recommendation V.26, alternative A.
<LI>It may include a backward (supervisory) channel at modulation rates up to 75 baud in each direction of transmission.
<LI>It includes an automatic adaptive equalizer.
</OL>
<P>Most vendors include features such as adaptive equalization, automatic retraining, scrambling, and extensive tests and diagnostics.
<P>Modulation occurs with an 1800 Hz carrier. Power levels conform to V.2. Modulation is at 4800 bits/s with 1600 baud and 2400 bits/s with 1200 baud. The encoding schemes for these two techniques are described in Tables 5-19 and 5-20. The V.24 circuits are used as shown in Table 5-21.

<P></P>

