<Tr><Td align=left>120</Td><Td align=left>Transmit Backward Channel Line Signal</Td><Td align=left>&nbsp;</Td><Td align=center>X</Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 20 -->
<Tr><Td align=left>121</Td><Td align=left>Backward Channel Ready</Td><Td align=left>&nbsp;</Td><Td align=center>X</Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 21 -->
<Tr><Td align=left>122</Td><Td align=left>Backward Channel Received Line Signal Detector</Td><Td align=left>&nbsp;</Td><Td align=center>X</Td></Tr>

</Table>
<FONT SIZE="2"><small><SUP>1</SUP></small> All essential interchange circuits and any others that are provided shall comply with the requirements of recommendation V.24. All interchange circuits indicated by an X shall be properly terminated in the data equipment and in the data circuit-terminating equipment in accordance with the appropriate recommendation.</FONT></P>

<P><B>V.27ter: 4800/2400 Bit/s Modem Standardized for Use in the General Switched Telephone Network</B>

<P>The majority of European PTT (postal and telegraph) administrations support either V.27bis or V.27ter. These interfaces are not used much in North America. The principal characteristics of this modem are as follows:

<OL>
<LI>It uses data signaling rate of 4800 bits/s with eight-phase differentially encoded modulation as described in recommendation V.27.
<LI>It operates at a reduced rate capability at 2400 bits/s with four-phase differentially encoded modulation as described in recommendation V.26, alternative A.
<LI>It may include a backward channel at modulation rates up to 75 baud.
<LI>It includes an automatic adaptive equalizer.
</OL>

<P>Modulation occurs at 1800 Hz. Power levels conform to V.2. Modulation patterns and codes are identical to the V.27 recommendation. The reduced rate uses V.26, alternative A. Refer to V.27 and V.26 for these descriptions. The V.24 circuits are used as shown in Table 5-22.

<P></P>

