<small><SUP>2</SUP></small> Not essential for continuous carrier operation. <br>
<small><SUP>3</SUP></small> A manual selector shall be implemented that determines the two data signaling rates selected by circuit 111. The manual selector positions shall be designated 9600/7200, 9600/4800, and 7200/4800. The ON condition of circuit 111 selects the higher data signaling rate, and the OFF condition of circuit 111 selects the lower data signaling rate. <br>
<small><SUP>4</SUP></small> Interchange circuits 140 and 141 are optional.</FONT></P>

<P><B>V.32: A Family of Two-Wire Duplex Modems Operating at Data Signaling Rates of up to 9600 Bits/s for Use on the General Switched Telephone Network and on Leased Telephone-Type Circuits</B>

<P>The V.32 modems were introduced into the industry in the mid to late 1980s. Their speed and superior signaling characteristics are such that their use has spread rapidly throughout the industry.
V.32 can operate at rates up to 9600 bits/s at FDX on a dial-up, two-wire telephone network. Many manufacturers offer a V.32 product. The principal characteristics of the modem are as follows:

<OL>
<LI>It provides FDX mode of operation on switched and two-wire, point-to-point leased circuits.
<LI>Channel separation is accomplished using echo cancellation techniques.
<LI>QAM is used for each channel, with synchronous line transmission at 2400 baud.
<LI>Any combination of the following data signaling rates may be implemented in the modems: 9600 bit/s synchronous, 4800 bit/s synchronous, and 2400 bit/s synchronous.
<LI>At 600 bits/s, two alternative modulation schemes, one using 16 carrier states and one using trellis coding with 32 carrier states, are provided for in this recommendation. Modems providing the 9600 bit/s data signaling rate shall be capable of interworking using the 16-state alternative.
<LI>Exchange of rate sequences are provided during start-up to establish the data rate, coding, and any other special facilities.
<LI>Asynchronous mode of operation must be studied further (see note 2). On certain international switched connections, it may be necessary to use a greater degree of equalization within the modem than would be required for use on most national general switched telephone network connections.
</OL>

<P>The frequency carrier operates in 1800 Hz. Transmitted power levels conform to V.2, and the modulation rate is 2400 baud. V.32 provides two alternative coding schemes for 9600 bits/s and one scheme for 4800 bits/s. The 9600 bit/s alternative uses either the nonredundant coding scheme or trellis coding.

<P>Nonredundant coding divides the data stream into four consecutive data bits (quad-bits) (see Table 5-25). The user data bits are designated Q1<SUB>n</SUB> , Q2<SUP>n</SUP>, Q3<SUP>n</SUP>, and Q4<SUP>n</SUP>, respectively. (The reader may wish to refer to Figure 5-1 for this discussion.) The first two bits in time Q1<SUB>n</SUB>  and Q2<SUB>n</SUB>  are coded into output bit values Y1<SUB>n</SUB> and Y2<SUB>n</SUB> and are used with Q3<SUB>n</SUB> and Q4<SUP>n</SUP>. Notice the values of Y1<SUB>n</SUB>  and Y2<SUB>n</SUB> are dependent on Q1<SUB>n</SUB> and Q2<SUB>n</SUB> and the previous output values of Y1<SUB>n</SUB> and Y2<SUP>n</SUP>. Also note that the encoding table shows the encoding scheme for the 4800 bit/s rate. With this speed, however, the Y1<SUB>n</SUB> and Y2<SUB>n</SUB> bits are used only to represent any combination of the input stream of Q1<SUB>n</SUB> and Q2<SUP>n</SUP>. That is, the 4800 bit/s scheme uses dibit encoding. The nonredundant modulation constellation is depicted in Figure 5-3. For 9600 bits/s, the 16 possible states are shown. For the 4800 bit/s rate, the constellation pattern is labeled with subsets A, B, C, and D to depict the output bits Y1<SUB>n</SUB> and Y2<SUB>n</SUB>:
<DT>
<DD>00 = A
<DD>01 = B
<DD>11 = C
<DD>10 = D
</DT>

<P><center><b> Figure 5-3.  16-Point V.32 Constellation Pattern</b></center></P>

