<!-- Row # 18 -->
<Tr><Td align=center>1</Td><Td align=center>1</Td><Td align=center>1</Td><Td align=center>0</Td><Td align=center>&nbsp;</Td><Td align=center>1</Td><Td align=center>1</Td><Td align=center>C</Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 19 -->
<Tr><Td align=center>1</Td><Td align=center>1</Td><Td align=center>1</Td><Td align=center>1</Td><Td align=center>&nbsp;</Td><Td align=center>0</Td><Td align=center>1</Td><Td align=center>B</Td></Tr>

</Table>

<P>The concepts of trellis coded modulation (TCM) are explained in Chapter 1; it may be useful to review the section entitled "Trellis Coded Modulation".

<P>The V.32 TCM modem creates an additional bit for every four bits. As was previously discussed, the data bits are encoded based on previous user data input.
<P>Trellis coding, like nonredundant coding, uses the quad-bit approach. However, bits Q1<SUB>n</SUB> and Q2<SUB>n</SUB>  are first coded into bit values Y1<SUB>n</SUB>  and Y2<SUB>n</SUB>, according to Table 5-26. These two bits are then input into an encoder that produces a fifth bit, Y0<SUB>n</SUB>. This redundant bit is based on various combinations of bits Y1<SUB>n</SUB>  and Y2<SUB>n</SUB>.

<P></P>

<Table Border=1 Width=80% Align=Center Colspec="L20 L20 L20 L20 L20 L20 ">
<Caption Align=Top><b>TABLE 5-26.  V.32 Trellis Encoding</b></Caption>

<!-- Row # 2 -->
<Tr><Td align=center colspan=2><B>Inputs</B><Td align=center colspan=2><B>Previous Outputs</B></Td><Td align=center colspan=2><B>Outputs</B></Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 3 -->
<Tr><Td align=center><B>Q1<SUB>n</SUB></B></Td><Td align=center><B>Q2<SUB>n</SUB></B></Td><Td align=center><B>Y1<SUB>n-1</SUB></B></Td><Td align=center><B>Y2<SUB>n-1</SUB></B></Td><Td align=center><B>Y1<SUB>n</SUB></B></Td><Td align=center><B>Y2<SUB>n</SUB></B></Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 4 -->
<Tr><Td align=center>0</Td><Td align=center>0</Td><Td align=center>0</Td><Td align=center>0</Td><Td align=center>0</Td><Td align=center>0</Td></Tr>

