<small><SUP>3</SUP></small> This circuit is not essential when only one data signaling rate is implemented in modem. <br>
<small><SUP>4</SUP></small> >This circuit is for use with the general switched telephone network only. V.32 also uses the V.25 recommendation for automatic dial and answer.
</FONT></P>

<P><B>V.32bis: A Duplex Modem Operating at Data Signaling Rates of up to 14,400 Bits/s for Use on the General Switched Telephone Network and on Leased Point-to-Point Two-Wire Telephone-Type Circuits</B>

<P>The V.32bis modems are relatively new to the industry and have only seen use since around 1990. The architecture of these modems is quite similar to that of the V.32 modems. A principal difference is that these modems operate at 14.4 kbits/s in contrast to the V.32 modems, whose top data rate is 9.6 kbits/s.
<P>The principal characteristics of the V.32bis modem are:
<OL>
<LI>It provides FDX modes of operation on point-to-point two-wire leased circuits on general telephone networks.
<LI>Channel separation is by echo cancellation techniques.
<LI>QAM techniques are employed on each channel with synchronous transmission line speeds of 2400 baud.
<LI>Synchronous transmission data rates are supported for many of these modems: 14,400 bits/s, 12,000 bits/s, 9600 bits/s, 7200 bits/s for trellis code operations and 4800 bits/s for non-trellis coded operations.
<LI>The V.32bis is compatible with the V.32 modems that operate in the 9600 and 4800 bits/s set range.
<LI>Exchange of rate sequences is provided during start up to establish the data signaling rate between the two modems.
<LI>Procedures are provided to alter the data signaling rate during the session without retraining the modems.
</OL>

<P>V.24 interchange circuits are required for V.32bis modems, as they are for all V series modems. The specific V.24 interchange circuits are summarized in Table 5-29. For signaling at 14.4 kbits/s, V.32bis employs techniques quite similar to V.32 bis. The principal difference is that at 2400 baud, six information bits and a redundant bit are employed for the purposes of TCM operations. Finally, the constellation pattern for V.32bis for signaling operating at 14.4 kbits/s is provided in Figure 5-5.</P>

<P></P>
<Table Border=1 Width=80% Align=Center Colspec="L20 L20 ">
<Caption Align=Top><b>TABLE 5-29.  V.32bis Interchange Circuits</b></Caption>

<!-- Row # 3 -->
<Tr><Td align=left VALIGN=BOTTOM><B>No.</B></Td><Td align=center><B>Interchange Circuit<small><SUP>1</SUP></small> Description</B></Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 4 -->
<Tr><Td align=left>102</Td><Td align=left>Signal Ground or Common Return</Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 5 -->
<Tr><Td align=left>103</Td><Td align=left>Transmitted Data</Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 6 -->
<Tr><Td align=left>104</Td><Td align=left>Received Data</Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 7 -->
<Tr><Td align=left>105</Td><Td align=left>Request to Send</Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 8 -->
<Tr><Td align=left>106</Td><Td align=left>Ready for Sending</Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 9 -->
<Tr><Td align=left>107</Td><Td align=left>Data Set Ready</Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 10 -->
<Tr><Td align=left>108/1<br>or<br>108/2</Td><Td align=left>Connect Data Set to Line<small><SUP>1</SUP></small><BR><BR>Data Terminal Ready<small><SUP>1</SUP></small></Td></Tr>

<!-- Row # 12 -->
