</Table>
<FONT SIZE="2"><small><SUP>1</SUP></small> This circuit shall be capable of operation as circuit 108/1 or circuit 108/2, depending on its use. <br>Operation of circuits 107 and 108/1 shall be in accordance with Section 4.4 of Recommendation V. 24.<br>
<small><SUP>2</SUP></small> When the modem is not operating in a synchronous mode at the interface, any signals on this circuit shall be disregarded. <br>Many DTEs operating in an asynchronous mode do not have a generator connected to this circuit. <br>
<small><SUP>3</SUP></small> When the modem is not operating in a synchronous mode at the interface, this circuit shall be clamped to the OFF condition. <br>Many DTEs operating in an asynchronous mode do not terminate this circuit.
</FONT></P>

<P><center><b> Figure 5-5.  V.32bis Constellation Pattern</b></center></P>
<! Reference is to big graphic (about 500 pixels wide)>
<a href=fig-55.gif>
	<! Displayed image is 150 pixels wide>
<center><IMG SRC="fig-55a.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="1" width=150></center>
</a>
<center><font size=-1><i>Click for a closer look</i></font></center>


<P><B>V.33: 14,400 Bit/s Modem Standardized for 
Use on Point-to-Point Four-Wire Leased 
Telephone-Type Circuits</B>

<P>In 1988 the ITU-T added a specification for a 14.4 kbit/s only modem. It is designed to operate over point-to-point four-wire leased telephone-type circuits. It operates in a manner similar to the V.32 modem, except that it encodes a redundant bit and six information bits for mapping into signal elements for a 2400 baud signal. Because of the success of X.32 and V.32bis, X.33 has not been extensively implemented.

<P><B>The Next Generation of V Series Modems: V.34</B>

<P>The ITU-T has had a higher speed modem, designated V.34, in development for the past several years. The new standard is also known in the industry as V.fast. In the United States, the Telecommunications Industries Association (TIA) TR-30.1 Committee is coordinating the V.34 work.1
<P>The V.34 architecture is based on trellis coded modulation and the QAM techniques discussed in the sections on V.32 and V.32bis. Its most noticeable difference is its speedÑa signaling rate of 28.8 kbits/s. Its symbol rate can range from 2400 to 3400.

<P><B>V.fast versus V.32terbo debate</B>

<P>Due to the slowness of the V.34 implementation, several vendors have formed an association to produce their own specification, which is known in the industry as V.32terbo. It is similar to V.32bis and uses the same coding scheme, but has more constellation points (either 56 or 512), which allows signaling rates of 16.8 kbits/s or 19.2 kbits/s.  
<P>The different modem manufacturers have lined up either behind V.fast or V.32 terbo. Some of the vendors believe that it is counterproductive to develop an interim standard and are waiting for the formal standard. Other vendors have grown weary of the slow process. They state that a standard is needed immediately and that an interim standard indeed will do no harm, but instead will move the industry forward quickly to a common approach.

<P><B>Automatic Interworking Between Automode Modems and Modems Conforming to Recommendations V.32, V.22bis, and V.22</B>

<P>Several readers of the first edition of this book inquired as to whether the EIA defined interworking procedures between the most common modems, notably V.22bis and V.32. The answer is yes, but the EIA (logically) defers to the ITU-T recommendations. The reader can obtain this information from (a) V.32, (b) V.22bis,  and (c) V.25.

<P><B>Wideband Modems</B>

<P>The ITU-T also publishes a number of recommended standards on wideband modems. These devices operate with high-frequency carrier signals and achieve a high data rate.

<P><B>V.35: Data Transmission at 48 Kbits/s Using 60-108 kHz Group Band Circuits</B>
<P>This modem operates at 48 kbits/s. The data signal is translated to the 60-108 kHz band as a sideband suppressed carrier AM signal. The carrier frequency operates at 100 kHz. The interface cable is a balanced twisted pair. 
<P>It is commonly (and erroneously) assumed that V.35 is specified as a 56 kbit/s interface. The actual ITU-T specification stipulates 48 kbits/s. Many systems, however, operate the V.35 at 56 kbits/s with the digital data system (DDS) offering originally established by AT&T. 
<P>It should also be noted that V.35 uses both the V.28 unbalanced interface and the balanced pair interface (see Table 5-30). V.35 makes use of V.24 circuits, as shown in Table 5-30.
<P></P>
<Table Border=1 Width=80% Align=Center Colspec="L20 L20 ">
