<FONT SIZE="2"><small><SUP>1</SUP></small> These functions are not included in ITU-T Recommendation V.35 but are provided in ISO 3593 on an optional basis.</FONT></P>

<P><B>V.36 Modems for Synchronous Data Transmission Using 60-108 kHz Group Band Circuits</B>
<P>This modem type is used on leased circuits as well as on several other kinds of facilities. V.36 actually stipulates six applications:
<OL>
<LI>Transmission of data between customers on leased circuits
<LI>Transmission of a multiplex aggregate bit stream for public data networks
<LI>Extension of a PCM channel at 64 kbits/s over analog facilities
<LI>Transmission of a common channel signaling system for telephony and/or public data networks
<LI>Extension of a single-channel-per-carrier (SCPC) circuit from a satellite earth station
<LI>Transmission of a multiplex aggregate bit stream for telegraph and data signals
</OL>
<P><B>Application 1</B>&#160 &#160  The recommended data signaling rate for international use is 48 kbits/s. For certain national applications or with bilateral agreement, the following data signaling rates are applicable: 56, 64, and 72 kbits/s.
<P><B>Applications 2, 3, and 4</B>&#160 &#160 For these applications, the recommended data signaling rate is synchronous at 64 kbits/s. For those synchronous networks requiring the end-to-end transmission of both the 8 and 64 kHz timing together with the data at 64 kbits/s, a data signaling rate of 72 kbits/s on the line is suggested.
<P><B>Application 5</B>&#160 &#160 The recommended data signaling rate for international use is synchronous at 48 kbits/s. For certain national applications or with bilateral agreement, the data signaling rate of 56 kbits/s is applicable.
<P><B>Application 6</B>&#160 &#160 The recommended data signaling rate is synchronous at 64 kbits/s. V.36 uses the V.24 circuits as described in Table 5-32.</P>

<P></P>
<Table Border=1 Width=80% Align=Center Colspec="L20 L20 ">
