<html>
<head>
   <title> Software Inspection: An Industry Best Practice -  Preface</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" 
background="../../sand.gif">

<h3 align=center><b><i> Software Inspection: An Industry Best Practice, <br>edited by David A. Wheeler, Bill Brykczynski, and Reginald N. Meeson, Jr.</i></b></h3>

<h1 align=center> FOREWORD</h1>

<p></p>
<hr>

<p><b>Inspections are now twenty years old, and they have decisively improved software quality, development cycle time, and overall maintainability! </b>

<p>I created the inspection process out of sheer frustration (and, yes, desperation) while managing a software project that had twice defeated more seasoned software development managers than myself. Despite the advice of well-meaning friends, I had recently switched from hardware development to the mysterious world of software development where almost everything was new to me and posed quite a challenge. What I found was chaotic and immeasurable. I quickly realized that to be effective, I had to understand my new environment and try to make order out of chaos. 

<p>Conventional software development wisdom at that time was to follow a traditional life cycle model in which steps were approached logically and sequentially. But this is not what I saw happening. Rather than one approach, several versions of that approach were followed simultaneously. The product was developed in a series of cycles that usually approximated the following sequence: 
<p>
<li>Specify some requirements; 

<li>Write a little code to satisfy a selected subset of those requirements; 

<li>Unit-test pieces of code, which together satisfy the requirements subset; 

<li>Integrate each subset of code into a system; 

<li>System-test the code in the system; 

<li>If the code satisfies the selected requirements subset, abstract the design from the code and write it in the form of a design specification; 

<li>Select another requirements subset, and continue until all requirements are satisfied, or at least include as many requirements subsets as possible in the available schedule time; 

<li>Write user documents to address all the requirements subsets that are included; 

<li>Ship system to users; and 

<li>Fix defects reported by users-while developers work on the next release. </li>
</ul>

<p>Completion criteria for the requirements specification amounted to it being "signed off". However, signing off a document did not necessarily signify that it was complete, correct, and unambiguous. To measure and track the completeness of design and code entities comprising a function between design start and integration end was infeasible: 

<p>There were no well defined traceable entities, or, when they existed, there were no completion criteria to track them against. 

<p>Immediately after a product release was shipped, work would start on the next release. Unfortunately, new release development was frequently interrupted to fix defects found by users in the previous release. Reworking those defects obviously detracted from the effort committed to the new release and often caused it to ship late, or to ship on time with fewer requirements satisfied, or to ship with more defects than it should. In addition, there was always a backlog of defects to be reworked while developing the new release. (If the percentage of total development effort devoted to fixing defects has a positive trend over several releases, it's possible to extrapolate when more effort will be spent on defect rework rather than on creating new product. This encourages continued extrapolation to the point where the organization will cease to be profitable.) 

<p>To manage software development-make a plan, measure accomplishment against the plan as the traceable elements were developed, and control the outcome to meet project objectives-as we tried to do in weekly "build meetings" required reconciling interpersonal communications among people who made perfect sense to themselves but not to each other. This left me with unanswered questions: 
<p>
<ul>
<li>What were the requirements, and were they understandable to the people responsible for satisfying them? 

<li>Was there really an accurate plan of how the system components fit together before system integration? 

<li>Did all the players have the same understanding of each component's definition? 

<li>What were the traceable units in the build plan, and was their relative granularity known? 

<li>How long did it take to complete testing when no one knew how much defect rework was involved? </li>
</ul>

<p>Answers to these questions were inconsistent, which prevented useful generalization. Also, the prevailing management climate was not sympathetic to answering these questions in order to improve planning for future development. The thrust was to "ship this function now!" So, a lot of very good people worked very hard, sorted out the crossed purposes in numerous miscommunications, and shipped products-time after time without much improvement between releases. When a project failed to meet its scheduled dates, we would reschedule and work harder using the same approach as before. Much innovative technical work was done but without much improvement in development methodology. Many products were shipped, but the human cost was high. The term "brute force development" applied to most projects. 

<p>In short, I found myself in an unmanageable software development world with a high potential for failure. (Others confided the same concerns to me, so I didn't feel too lonely.) Therefore, to help us manage despite prevailing development problems and to improve the quality of delivered software, I decided to modify the development process. 

<p>Absence of commonly agreed-upon, measurable completion criteria for requirements, design, code, and deliverables caused significant misunderstandings and rework. Clearly, eliminating this problem required measurable exit criteria for all development process operations. Exit criteria for the operations that created the work products were the first building blocks needed to support the inspection process. 

<p>Another issue was the pressure to reduce the number of defects delivered to customers. (A defect is an instance of a work product failing to satisfy the exit criteria of the operation in which it was created.) This dovetailed with the need to minimize defect rework, a large and uncontrolled component of development effort. (Estimates of defect rework ranged from 30 to 80 percent of total development effort.) To satisfy both these needs meant reducing the number of defects injected during development, and finding and fixing those defects as near to their point of origin in the process as possible. This led us to formulate the dual objectives of the inspection process: 
<p>
<ul>
<li>Find and fix all defects in the product. 

<li>Find and fix all defects in the development process that cause product defects.</li>
</ul>

<p>My development team and I modeled, measured, and implemented changes in the initial inspection process used for software products. We made changes in the process, adjusted the number of inspectors and their individual roles, measured the results of executing the process with these changes, and then interviewed the people involved in both inspection and development. We analyzed the results of each change, made refinements, and repeated the execution-refinement cycle until we had no further improvements. (This procedure was periodically executed for monitoring and enabling continuous improvement of both the inspection and development processes.) After numerous cycles through this procedure, the inspection process was eventually repeatable and, when executed by trained developers, it efficiently found the highest number of defects. 

<p>This work was done over a period of three and a half years, and it involved many products and releases. Several hundred developers and their managers participated; constructively, for the most part. The inspection methods did not delay any shipment, and customers were pleased with the product quality. Both proponents and critics-and the latter abounded-helped us more than they know (or sometimes intended). By the time 1 wrote "Design and code inspections to reduce errors in program development," an article for the IBM System Journal in 1976 and published in this book, I was confident that the process had been well wrung out in actual development and produced repeatable results. 

<p>As the inspection process evolved, we learned to concentrate our energies on finding those defects that computers could detect only with much effort. For example, compilers flag syntax errors, and lint-type compiler tools are good at finding procedure and standards violations. This frees human inspectors from mechanical checklist tasks and iets them concentrate on finding operational defects. Consequently, defect checklists were removed from the inspection process and used to specify development tools intended to assure that the product complied with the rules and standards required in the checklists. These tools cleaned out many mechanical problems before inspections were conducted. 

<p>As well as reducing the defects users found in software, the inspection process we created increased development productivity, because inspections found defects and removed them from all work products-requirements specifications, design, coding, test plans and test cases, and user documentation. In addition, these inspections identified (and caused to be fixed) defects in the development process that gave rise to product defects. 

<p>After we had convinced several development groups to use the inspection process properly, we continued to measure results. (Those who did not use it properly also contributed to our learning.) The inspection process fulfilled its design objectives and offered additional benefits, and our findings are again confirmed by this book as well as by reports available in the development community. Noteworthy benefits attributed to inspections include: 
<p>
<ul>
<li>reduction in user-reported defects; 

<li>increased customer satisfaction; 

<li>increased development productivity, evidenced by more function shipped in a given time or reduced development cycle time; 

<li>improvement in meeting committed schedules; 

<li>rapid cross-training of developers and maintainers on new products; 

<li>continuous process improvement through removal of systemic defects (which cause product defects); and 

<li>team building.</li>
</ul>

<p>Moreover, developers learn to avoid creating defects through participating in inspections that find defects in their own and others' work products, and inspections have eliminated the need to unit-test code in some cases. 

<p>Creating a methodology and persuading others to use it are two different things-I myself encountered everything from derision to exasperation but little acceptance from my peers. Even when third parties, with no stake in the methodology, reported how it had helped them, people resisted. Reluctance to change working habits continues to impede the accepted use of inspections. 

<p>One reason not to use the inspection process, expressed by developers and managers on tight delivery schedules, is the fear that inspections will lengthen schedules and delay shipments. Inspections absorb 20 to 30 percent of the effort during the first half of product development, which managers fear will add to the development cycle. Overlooked is the net reduction in development that results from defects found and fixed during inspections with less effort than that expended on fixing defects found in test. Reduced development effort, in turn, often leads to shortened delivery time. Although experience has shown that fear of delayed shipment is a myth, the fear sometimes causes managers to resist adopting inspections. 

<p>Additionally, mislabeling of process operations continues in the software industry. lf we insist on truth in advertising, "test" would be called "defect rework," because usually, far less than 50 percent of the test effort verifies that the product satisfies requirements while more than 50 percent is consumed with defect rework. This simple act of renaming would focus the attention of management (and financial auditors) on what is really occurring, and it might lead to their insisting on inspections to find defects and fix them at lower cost, leaving test to verify that the product satisfies its requirements. 

<p>Partial or improper implementation of the inspection process, which incorrectly executes the process, often produces inferior results and confuses the issue. Experience has shown that to get the best results from the inspection process, it's necessary to execute this process precisely and consistently. Similarly, experience has shown that all variations of inspection processes do not produce similar results. Thus, although inspections have been successful and proven their value over many years and many projects, there are still those who would rather not include inspections in their development processes. In fact, some organizations are still using the "brute force" method that we and many others abandoned twenty years ago. 

<p>Code inspections are more often discussed-and receive more attention-than inspection of requirement specifications, although the latter can produce even larger benefits. This could be because code is easier to inspect, as requirements are often improperly specified, or it could reflect some other process deficiency. Similarly, discussion of inspections of hardware and software systems design, logic design, test plans and cases, and user documentation tend to be underreported and/or underutilized. 

<p>Since their inception, inspections have had the dual objectives we mentioned earlier: to find defects in the product and in the process used to create the product. Finding product defects is so immediate and satisfying that generally the added step of identifying, and removing, development process defects is overlooked. Skipping this second step is shortsighted as it does not reduce defects injected in all future development, an essential element to "putting oneself out of the defect generation business." Fortunately, this book highlights the need to remove process defects to subsequently reduce defects injected into the product. 

<p>The relative roles of reviews, walk-throughs, and inspections are frequently confused. Both reviews and walk-throughs (essentially the same type of activity) and inspections are important in the development of work products. Reviews/walk-throughs are conducted during development to demonstrate and refine approaches, solicit and compare viewpoints, develop improvements, and identify problems and create solutions to them. Inspections, on the other hand, are conducted when a work product is asserted to be complete. The objective of inspection is to find defects only, not to undertake the activities of reviews/walk-throughs. 

<p>Experimentation has shown that when review/walk-through activities are included in the inspection or, indeed, when even one more objective is included, the defect-detection effectiveness of inspections is significantly degraded. Occasionally, reviews/walkthroughs are discussed as if they are competing activities and at other times as if one has evolved into the other. In practice, combining their activities creates an amalgam of disparate objectives and appears to lower their individual and combined effectiveness. The fact is that reviews/walk-throughs and inspections come into play at different times in software product development, and each adds unique value. When both are used separately, each contributes uniquely to the development of software that is well thought out and contains very few defects. 

<p>This book describes inspection methodology, and results obtained, in a variety of software products and development environments. The book reports on real development experiences with large and small software products. Consequently, it addresses the concerns of those interested in requirements specification, software engineering, software development management, process management, testing, quality assurance, maintenance and support, user document writers, and/or end users. 

<p>Inspections are a team sport with two aspects: first, the organized effort to have the inspection meetings and, second, the conduct of the meetings themselves. The team members, each playing an appointed role in the inspection process, include line managers (all levels), project managers, requirements specifiers, hardware and software designers, coders, integrators, testers, quality assurance specialists, user-document writers, product users, and marketing people. Like any team endeavor, successful inspections depend on (1) the individual ability of each team member, and (2) how well the individuals work as a team. You will see allusions to these two important factors in this book. 

<p>In 1976, when I first wrote about the inspection process, I had no idea of the extent of its impact. The results so far have been extremely gratifying. Nothing will be more satisfying in the future than to find that inspections are increasingly used for more diverse products and services, in software development as well as other areas. I will continue to work toward that goal. 

<p>If the claim is true that it takes 25 years for a methodology to have an impact on industry, then we can expect by the end of this decade to see the benefits of inspections more fully exploited. To heighten interest in, and stimulate use of, the inspection process so that it attains full fruition, this book offers much useful information and thus makes an important contribution to software engineering. It will help you too, if you make use of what you have learned. As it has been said, the only real value of knowledge is in using it. </p>

<p>Michael E. Fagan<br>
Potomac, Maryland<br>
March 1996</p>

<p>
<hr></p>

