<html>
<head>
   <title> Software Inspection: An Industry Best Practice -  Preface</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body>

<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" background="../../sand.gif">

<h3 align=center><b><i> Software Inspection: An Industry Best Practice, <br>edited by David A. Wheeler, Bill Brykczynski, and Reginald N. Meeson, Jr.</i></b></h3>

<h1 align=center> PREFACE</h1>

<p></p>
<hr>

<p>Our lives&#151;and the quality of our lives&#151;increasingly depend on the affordability, reliability, and availability of software. Emergency phone systems, advanced medical systems, military weapon systems, airplane navigation systems, and even household appliances depend on software. Improving the software development process is therefore vitally important to us all. 

<p>Software inspection, a peer review process, has been shown to decrease costs, decrease development time, and increase quality through a detailed examination of work-in-progress with the objective of identifying defects. Software inspections are very different from manufactured product inspections. Manufacturing inspections typically occur after a product is complete, whereas software inspections occur during development, providing early feedback on product quality. While the software inspection process does not solve all software development problems, strong evidence shows that it helps to improve overall software product quality. 

<p>In this book you will find detailed descriptions of the inspection process, explanations of how inspections improve software development practices, and documented practical results that have been achieved using inspections. Our intent is to give readers an easy to-use source of inspection reference material, organized by general category, and to explain how these different articles correlate. 

<p>The intended audience for this book ranges from software developers to researchers, including those involved in defining or improving software development processes. Portions of this book will also interest software development project managers who wish to fully understand inspection theory and practice before applying them. 

<p>This book is organized as follows: 
<p>
<OL>
<li> Introduction to Software Inspection&#151;A basic introduction to the software inspection process. 

<li> Experience Reports&#151;Examples of the use of inspection in software development or maintenance. 

<li> Process Measurement&#151;Describes advanced use of inspection data to improve software development processes and products (beyond simply correcting the specific defects defected). 

<li> Inspection of Products Other Than Code&#151;Key papers on inspecting noncode products. 

<li> Other Inspection-Related Work&#151;Miscellaneous papers on inspection. 

<li> Bibliography&#151;A list of all inspection-related articles we're aware of. 

<li> Bibliography Index&#151;Terms from the papers in the bibliography. 

<li> Bibliography Author List&#151;An index of all authors listed in the bibliography. 

<li> Glossary&#151;Terms relating to the software inspection process: </li>
</OL>

<p>The first five chapters contain reprints of key articles. Each chapter begins with an overview and describes how the articles at the end of the chapter relate. Next is a comprehensive bibliography. All references to inspection-related articles are cited in the bibliography. This is followed by an index, list of authors, and a brief glossary. The accompanying disk is an annotated version of the bibliography, containing not just the references but abstracts and our comments on the references. </p>

<p>David A. Wheeler<br>
Bill Brykczynski<br>
Reginald N. Meeson, Jr. <br>
March 1996</p>

