<html>
<head>
  <title> Automating Specification-Based Software Testing - Introduction</title>
  <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body>

<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" 
background="../../sand.gif">


<h3 align=center><b><i> Automating Specification-Based Software Testing, by Robert M. Poston</i></b></h3>

<h1 align=center>INTRODUCTION</h1>

<hr>
<p></p>
<p> Newcomers to automated software testing often think that all the automation they need is built into a capture-replay tool that runs or executes test cases. As people move further into automated software testing, however, they see that test case execution takes care of only one small part of their work. Test cases must be designed and created before they can be run and captured. Additionally, test cases should be evaluated after they are run, so the tester and the developer can confirm that the test cases and the software functioned or failed to function as expected. All three technical activities in the testing process-test case creation, execution, and evaluation-need to be performed and already are automated by commercially available tools. 

<p> Most tools described in this tutorial are available for sale in the commercial marketplace, making them accessible to many professionals. Commercially available testing tools usually are supported with user manuals and other documentation and are updated periodically through new product releases. 

<p> The automation of test case creation, execution, and evaluation implies that these are well-defined activities-widely understood and practiced. Automation also suggests that the theoretical underpinnings for each activity are documented. Therefore, this tutorial is not about deriving or analyzing theories of testing, which has been written about many times. Rather, it is about using automation to apply established, field-tested theories. Always the emphasis is on the practicing tester. How does understanding a particular theory or application of the theory help the tester gain insight into automated testing? 

<p> A unique aspect of this tutorial is that it focuses on testing software from specifications, not from code. The term <I>specification-based testing</I> means creating test cases from specifications. In this tutorial a specification is defined broadly to mean any description of expected behavior and characteristics of a software product. Software testers often are obliged to deal with specifications in a wide variety of forms and formats. A specification presented to a tester could be as formal as a document written in a specification language or as informal as a set of notes scribbled during a meeting. How to test from either formal or informal specifications is discussed in Chapter 1 of this tutorial.

<p>The two themes or concepts of this tutorial are specification-based testing and its automation. I recognize that both or either of these concepts may be difficult for some software practitioners to accept and implement. Although I am a long-time advocate of specification-based testing, many people I work with think that they should develop code and then create test cases from that code for the purpose of exercising it. (Creating test cases from code usually is called <I>code-based</I> testing but also is known as <I>product-based</I> or <I>white box testing</I>.) Code-based testers of my acquaintance often do not want to invest effort in another testing approach. I also have encountered resistance among people moving from manual to automated testing. Automated testing, no matter how desirable and ultimately advantageous, does require a new way of conceptualizing and working. This tutorial shows, however, that both specification-based testing and its automation are well worth consideration. 

<p> Code-based testing is not a theme of this tutorial, because I believe that code-based testing leads people into the faulty practice of testing code against itself. Code-based testing is addressed in this tutorial only to differentiate it from code coverage measurement and specification-based testing. While such differentiations often are not made in manual testing, they must be made in automated testing. (More about these necessary differentiations later in this Introduction.) An example in Appendix 2 highlights some of the problems inherent in code-based testing and offers one means to compare and evaluate code-based testing against specification-based testing. In Appendix 3 is a short list of references on code-based testing for those who want to read more about the approach. 

<p> Since 1981, as part of my ongoing work in software testing, I have introduced specification-based testing to people in more than 800 software development organizations in the United States and overseas. These introductions typically consisted of instructional sessions at least two days in duration. The majority of participants brought specifications and source code listings from their current projects to these sessions. My job was to help the participants use their specifications, and code if necessary, to develop test cases for their software. If time permitted, we also ran and evaluated the test cases during these sessions. 

<p> When I started these sessions in 1981, people had to create test cases by hand. Automated test case generators were not commercially available then. Although test execution and evaluation tools were marketed, many organizations I worked with had not purchased these tools. In my experience, executing and evaluating test cases also required considerable manual effort in the early 1980s. However, by 1987, I was observing significant advances toward automated software testing. Participants in my sessions were starting to use automated tools to create test cases from specifications, and oftentimes they had new versions of test execution and evaluation tools with which to run and measure test cases. Better still, graduates of those introductory sessions began to apply the tools, and their new knowledge of how to use them, on projects. 

<p> Of the many software practitioners I meet, most already have performed or read about code-based testing. What they usually do not know much about is specification-based testing. A little history reveals why code-based testing the better known of the two. 

<p>In the early days of software testing, as researchers in industry and academia became involved, they usually worked from code because that is all they had; most researchers did not have access to specifications from commercial or military projects. Even if engineers on such projects had been able to share specifications, researchers probably would have found that the specifications were incomplete, inconsistent, and ambiguous. People were not very good at writing specifications in the early days of software development. Standardized specification languages, modeling methodologies, and requirements recording tools were scarce then [DAVI90]. Code, in contrast, was written in standard languages that were consistently interpreted through execution, so code was far more amenable to analysis and tool building. Not surprisingly, then, for years the majority of papers, articles, and books about testing were research-oriented and addressed code-based testing. The information from those publications filtered through the software industry, reinforcing the idea that code-based testing was the preferred method to use. 

<h2> Distinguishing Code-Based Testing from Code Coverage Measurement</h2>

People who ask me about code-based testing usually have blurred it with code coverage measurements. Code-based testing is performed for the purpose of <I>creating</I> test cases. Code coverage measurements, on the other hand, are performed for the purpose of <I>evaluating</I> test cases and can be applied to either code-based or specification-based test cases.

<p> If code-based testing is not clearly and distinctly separated from code coverage measurement in automated software testing, confusion reigns. I often am called to software projects where people have misunderstood contracts and misused tools, because they did not distinguish between code based testing and code coverage measurement. To many a bewildered contractor I have had to explain: "Your contract does say that every statement and branch in the code must be exercised. But your contract also says that test cases must demonstrate that code performs as specified. You will be hard pressed to show conformance to or deviation from a specification unless you design test cases from the specification. When you run the specification-based test cases on the code, you then are supposed to make measurements to determine which statements and branches have been exercised." 

<p> The usual reason that this explanation is necessary is that somewhere in a military, government, or 
commercial software contract, a contractor reads the words, "every statement and branch in the 
code shall be exercised" and misconstrues these words to mean that test cases must be created 
from code. Time pressures mount, and in order to deliver the software product, the contractor 
usually will create and run some code-based test cases on the software. Then, in the interest of time, the contractor may skip the step of evaluating the test cases for pass/fail criteria (see page 18) and may not even compare test case results to the specification. As a result, poorly tested code is released, and customers soon start to complain that the delivered software contains failures. The contractor typically then turns to automation as a "magic bullet" way to speed execution of code-based test cases to get the same inconclusive results faster. In a situation like this, I often see testing tools haphazardly applied with little understanding of how the tools work or what jobs the tools do. (See Chapter 5 for the jobs testing tools perform.) 

<p> Provisions in software development and maintenance contracts calling for specification-based testing and code coverage measurements make good sense to me. I am against code-based testing, but I strongly encourage the use of code coverage measurements. Instead of creating test cases from code (that is, code-based testing), I want to create test cases from the specification (that is, specification-based testing). Then I want to run those specification-based test cases on the code and evaluate them to see how well they have covered the code (that is, code coverage measurement as described in detail in Chapter 4). Of course, I want appropriate tools to do these each of these jobs for me. The value of using automated specification-based testing with code coverage measurement is explained throughout this tutorial. 

<h2>Choosing to Automate with Specification-Based or Code-Based Testing </h2>

<p> When people test by hand, they work, consciously or unconsciously, from both the specification and the code. Testers who try to adhere to specification-based testing still have knowledge of the code and supplement the specification by envisioning how code should work. Likewise, code testers fill in and compensate for missing specification information. They often interview developers and users, for example, to discover expected behavior of the software. Pure specification-based or pure code-based testing is unlikely to occur when people test manually. 

<p> Tools, however, are not as smart or flexible as human testers. Today's commercially available, automated test case generators can process information only from code or only from the specification. No single generator can do both [STSC94, ENCY94, SQE94]. So as people move to automate their testing process, they must choose to create their test cases either from the specification or the code. This choice is crucial, because few organizations can afford to buy and use both specification-based and code-based test case generators for one project. (A third way of generating test cases automatically from test design languages is discussed briefly on page 26. However, for reasons described there, this type of test case generation is not treated as a mainstream option in this tutorial.) 

<h2>Following the Industry Move to Specification-Based Testing</h2>

<p> Little research was reported in specification-based testing until the mid- to late 1970s. But then, three situations began to prompt professionals to rethink how they were testing software. First, code-based testing was not working. Industry papers and books started to document and show by example that test cases designed from code were not reliable failure finders [GOOD75, HOWD76, HOWD80, BEIZ82, BEIZ90, PATR91]. (Refer to Appendix 2 for another example of how code-based testing does not work.) 

<p> The second thing that encouraged exploration of specification-based testing was the growing popularity of formal specification languages in the 1980s. This was a decade of exploding growth in both the communications industries and the software tool industry. As the numbers and types of communications systems and software tools increased, professionals needed specification languages to help them specify interfaces among systems and tools. In response to this need, standards makers in the communications and software development tool industry came forth with new, formal specification languages such as LOTOS, Estelle, Specification Description Language (SDL), Z (or Zed), ASN.1 [MORI90], and the Vienna Development Method (VDM) [WING90]. These languages enabled specifiers to record specifications that were complete, consistent, and unambiguous. The foundation for automated specification-based testing had been laid. 

<p> For all the advantages that formal languages offered, however, they were difficult for untrained practitioners to use. A person unfamiliar with such formal language constructs and elements as Boolean logic, set theory, and predicate calculus had to struggle to use most of the new specification languages. 

<p> Fortunately, a third situation unfolded as the difficulty of using formal specification languages became apparent. CASE (Computer-Aided Software Engineering) tools, now more commonly and simply called software development tools, came to the marketplace. These tools made drawing specifications an easy alternative to writing them. People could draw and annotate decision, state, and object diagrams, as well as many other technical diagrams, on a computer screen quickly and attractively. Once a diagram was in the computer, a software development tool could take over and convert the information in the drawing tool into a formal specification language representation. Another development tool could transform that representation into test cases. By the end of the 1980s, then, the software testing community had begun to recognize the failures of code-based testing, identified the benefits of formal language specifications, and was moving toward tool-assisted, specification-based testing. 

<p> Historically, software product evolution has been driven by technology. Product evolution typically progressed from academic research to corporate research and development to commercialization and finally to industrial use. But the software testing tools of the 1980s did not evolve in this pattern. Instead, entrepreneurs shortcut traditional evolution by going straight to practicing testers to find out what they needed to expedite and improve their testing processes. Testing tool evolution was user-driven, not technology driven. What users needed and wanted guided entrepreneurs to build specific testing tools. At least one major user of testing tools, the US Army, started to fund entrepreneurial efforts to develop and commercialize specification-based testing tools in the 1980s [USAR90]. The earliest versions of such tools relied heavily on the foundational research published in professional literature. However, as the 1980s testing tools matured, entrepreneurs refined and enlarged on the foundational theorems that researchers had put forward. Today, testing tool evolution often is supported by entrepreneurial innovation and capital as well as academic research. 

<p> The "publish or perish" dictum motivates many academic researchers to publish information about 
their work. Extreme time pressures and fear of divulging technical secrets often deter people in 
commercial organizations, particularly entrepreneurial ones, from writing about their work. What 
practicing testers find, then, when they want to read about testing is a great body of research or 
proposal-for-research material but few publications about applying theory and automating the 
everyday work of testing. This tutorial was prepared especially for practicing testers to help them 
bridge the gap between theory and application. 

<h2>Stepping through This Tutorial</h2>

<p> The first chapter of this tutorial is called Fundamentals. It provides an overview of 
specification-based software testing and a case study showing how automated test generation, 
execution, and evaluation were carried out on an object-oriented system. 

<p> Since a hands-on tester must create, execute, and evaluate test cases, the body of this tutorial is 
organized around these testing jobs. The three central sections of this tutorial are self-descriptively 
titled Test Generation, Test Execution, and Test Evaluation. In automated testing these activities 
can be performed at the system, integration, and object or unit level of testing and should be 
started as early as possible. 

<p> The content of a specification determines the level of testing to be done. If the specification 
describes a system, then system-level testing can be performed as the case study in Chapter 1 
exemplifies. If a specification describes two or more pieces of a system (that is, subsystems, 
components, and the like) the pieces can be integrated for testing (that is, integration testing). If a 
specification describes a small object or program, object-level testing can be performed as the 
example in Appendix 2 illustrates. Look for information about tools that help testers work at 
different levels of testing in Chapter 5, beginning on page 83. 

<p> The last section of this tutorial is called Software Testing Tools. It helps the tester identify, 
evaluate, select, and implement testing tools and methods. However, finding and buying tools or 
methods is wasted effort if an organization does not adapt its culture to automation. This tutorial 
ends with a case study that shows how a testing methodology was implemented at Leeds & 
Northrup in the 1980s. The L&N project was an early effort to re-engineer a software testing process 
in preparation for testing automation. The L&N study is still used today as a model for technology 
transfer. 

<h2>Reading This Tutorial</h2>

<p> In 1992, in an effort to reach software testers effectively through the printed word, I started a diary 
about the reading habits of testers. I made notes every time a tester gave me a tidbit of information about this subject. Judging from that diary, most testers will read this tutorial in bits and pieces. Practicing testers, especially, seem to like to read segments of information, preferably no more than eight magazine pages in length. Usually they will take breaks between their readings, sometimes lengthy ones, and then come back to technical literature to pick up another segment of information. 

<p> Most papers or segments in this tutorial are fairly self-contained, but where they are not, references, prerequisites, explanations, or directions to other parts of the tutorial are provided. Those who read this tutorial front to back in close-together sittings may notice some overlaps in information. Such overlaps usually occur because included information comes from several authors writing about closely related subjects or from one author revisiting an idea or issue in another segment. For testers who read in bits and pieces, such minor repetitions will be useful memory refreshers. 

<p> Different authors sometimes assign different meanings to words in this tutorial, as do authors 
throughout the software industry. However, each author contributing to this tutorial has made a 
conscientious effort to define key words at first use. The definitions embedded in the papers should 
serve readers in lieu of a glossary. 

