<title>Search for Simplicity - Bio</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" background="../../sand.gif">

<h2>About the Author</h2>
<p><b>Per Brinch Hansen</b> joined Regnecentralen, Copenhagen in 1962 and participated in the programming of a Cobol compiler. From 1967 to 1970 he was responsible for the development of the <I>RC 4000 multiprogramming system,</I> one of the earliest systems based on message communication. Per Brinch Hansen wrote the first book on <I>Operating System Principles</I> (1973), which has been published in six languages.</p>

<p>From 1972 at California Institute of Technology he pioneered the development of programming languages for parallel computing. At Caltech he developed <I>Concurrent Pascal</I> and wrote the <I>Solo</I> operating system in the language (1975). In 1976, he became the first chairman of computer science at USC and wrote the first book on parallel programming, <I>The Architecture of Concurrent Programs</I> (1977). From 1984 to 1988 Per held a professorship in computer science at the University of Copenhagen. He is currently a distinguished professor at Syracuse University. His recent interest has been the development of programming paradigms for parallel scientific computing, described in his book, <I>Studies in Computational Science</I> (1995).</p>

<p><a href="../bp07566.htm"><img src="../../return2.gif" align=bottom width=35 height=35 border=0> Return to Search for Simplicity </a></font></p>

