<head>
<title> Automating Software Specification-Based Testing - Bio</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" background="../../sand.gif">

<h2>About the Author</h2>
<p>While serving in the US Marine Corps in Viet Nam the early 1960s, <b>Robert M. Poston</b> started to see the need for software reliability in a very immediate way. Bob was responsible for verifying operation of software-driven electronic counter measure systems in aircraft. Pilots relied on these systems to help them avoid enemy missiles. If a system malfunctioned in flight, a pilot might not come back to base alive. Under these pressing circumstances, Bob learned the importance of keeping records of all system failures and using those records to help prevent errors in new systems.

<p>Although Bob was a dedicated Marine for nearly eight years, he decided to leave the Corps in 1967 to pursue a civilian career in software development and to carry on his quest for software reliability. His goal was to work in as many areas and aspects of software development and testing as possible to understand and to share with others how to create highly reliable software. He has made good progress toward that goal. 

<p>In the course of Bob's civilian career, he has managed operations of NASA's Western Test Range at Vandenberg AFB, California, where he directed the work of 750 people preparing for missile launches. He headed software projects on the Trident Submarine while working for RCA. He founded and presided for 12 years over a small company called Programming Environments, Inc., that specialized in software quality and development productivity. At his company Bob learned to balance reliability with time-to-market pressures.

<p>Bob has invented and marketed software tools, participated in software testing research projects, led national and international standards efforts, written over 60 articles about software quality and testing, served as a charter member of the editorial board of IEEE Software, and lectured and taught in thousands of professional forums. He served as quality and testing specialist on President Reagan's 1984 People-to-People software engineering delegation to China, and throughout his career has received numerous industry achievement awards. Today he is focused on automating software testing.

<p>Bob holds a BSEE degree from California State Polytechnic University and has received extensive specialized professional training from such institutions as the University of California. For the last 32 years Bob's wife, Diana, has helped him keep a journal of his experiences in software development and testing. </p>

<p><a href="../bp07531.htm"><img src="../../return2.gif" align=bottom width=35 height=35 border=0> Return to Automating Software Specification-Based Testing</a></font></p>

<p><hr size=6></p>

<p><a href="../../pubs/pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</a> | <a href="../../cshome.htm">Computer
Society home page</a> </p>

