<html>
<head>
<title> Process-Centered Software Engineering - Bio</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" background="../../sand.gif">

<h2>About the Authors</h2>
<p><b>Pankaj Garg</b> has been an active researcher in the area of process modeling and has developed several software engineering environments. He was one of the early proponents of the use of
hypertext technology for managing software engineering information. He has been a lead member of Matisse and SMART projects, research prototypes built on Hewlett-Packard's industry standard Softbench environment. With Sanjay Bhansali, he has developed the process programming by hindsight technique for evolving PSEEs. More recently, he has been working on programming tools for distributed applications.

<p> Pankaj Garg was an All-University Pre-Doctoral Merit Fellow of the Graduate School, University of Southern California, for the academic years 1984-87. He has published about 20 research articles in conferences and journals, and holds one U.S. patent for monitoring distributed systems. With Mehdi Jazayeri, Garg has taught tutorials on the topic of process-centered software engineering environments at several international conferences. He received a Bachelor of Technology in Computer Science from Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur, India, in 1984. He received a Master's degree and a Ph.D in Computer Science from the University of Southern California, Los Angeles, in 1986 and 1989 respectively. He can be reached at garg@hpl.hp.com

<p><b>Mehdi Jazayeri</b> is a professor of computer science and heads the Distributed Systems Department at the Technical University of Vienna. He is interested in software engineering, programming languages, and distributed and parallel systems. His industrial experience includes eight years at Hewlett-Packard Laboratories as a researcher and project manager on various distributed and parallel systems projects; five years managing the development of compilers and programming environments at Synapse Computer Corporation and Ridge Computers; and one year as senior scientist at TRW Vidar.  He started his career as an assistant professor of computer science at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.  He has been a Fulbright Scholar at the University of Helsinki (1979) and a visiting professor at the Politecnico di Milano (1988). He has taught courses at Santa Clara University, Georgia Institute of Technology, and San Jose State University. 

<p>He has coauthored two textbooks, <I>Fundamentals of Software Engineering</I> (Prentice Hall 1990), and <I>Programming Language Concept</I> (John Wiley 1987, 2nd edition). Together with Pankaj Garg, he has developed and given several tutorial on process-centered software engineering environments at international conferences. Mehdi Jazayeri is a member of ACM and a Senior Member of IEEE.</p>

<p><a href="../bp07103.htm"><img src="../../return2.gif" align=bottom width=35 height=35 border=0> Return to Process-Centered Software Engineering</a></font></p>

