</DOCHDR>
<!--This file created 9/26/96 9:55 AM by Claris Home Page version 1.0--><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>Relevance and insight in experimental studies</TITLE>   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 1.0">   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=50 BOTTOM=584 LEFT=49 RIGHT=617></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="../../../expert.gif" X-SAS-UseImageWidthX-SAS-UseImageHeight ALIGN=bottom></P><P><A HREF="x5010.htm">Trends and Controversies</A><BR><A HREF="http://www.itc.cmu.edu/~expert/script.html">Reply</A><BR><A HREF="http://www.itc.cmu.edu/~expert/responses.html">Readreponses</A><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE><H2>Getting what you deserve from data</H2><H3>Paul R. Cohen, Department of Computer Science, University ofMassachusetts, Amherst</H3><P>This essay's focus will appear at first to be a narrow,prescriptive little corner of the methodological landscape. Dataanalysis is often dismissed as no more complicated than calculatingsome means and comparing them with <I>t</I> tests or the like.Consequently, experiments and analyses are inefficient, requiringmore data than necessary to show an effect; they waste data, failingto show effects; and they sometimes induce hallucinations, suggestingeffects that don't exist. I am the last person to suggest thatmethodology boils down to statistics (see <I>Empirical Methods forArtificial Intelligence</I>, <A HREF="#1">(1)</A> p. x), but badanalysis can spoil an entire research program, so it warrantsattention.</P><P>I will discuss three common and easily fixed problems:</P></BLOCKQUOTE><UL>   <LI>Accepting the null hypothesis, a misuse of statistical   machinery.      <LI>Inadequate attention to sources of variance, leading to   insignificant results and failure to notice interactions among   factors.      <LI>Multiple pairwise comparisons, leading to nonexistent effects.      <P>I have constructed a data set to illustrate these problems. It   contains hypothetical assessments of confidence for boys and girls   in grades 4 through 7 and is called the gender data set. (Boys and   Girls: The Development of Gender Roles <A HREF="#2">(2)</A>   describes real studies of these factors; for real examples from   AI, see Empirical Methods; <A HREF="#1">(1)</A> the gender data   set is available from cohen@cs.umass.edu.)</P>      <P><B>Accepting the null hypothesis.</B> Suppose a researcher has   the hypothesis that girls and boys are equally confident. Table 1   shows mean confidence, averaged over grade levels. A <I>t</I> test   shows no effect of gender; boys' and girls' confidence levels are   not significantly different; therefore, the hypothesis that boys   and girls are equally confident is accepted.</P>      <P><TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH="80%">      <TR>         <TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>Mean         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>Standard Deviation         </TD></TR>      <TR>         <TD>            <P>Boys 4.271         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>.531         </TD></TR>      <TR>         <TD>            <P>Girls 3.996         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>.888         </TD></TR>   </TABLE></P>      <P><B>Table 1</B>. Hypothetical means and standard deviations for   confidence scores for boys and girls averaged over students and   grade levels.</P>      <P>This line of reasoning makes nonsense of statistical hypothesis   testing. The logic of hypothesis testing is analogous to proof by   contradiction: First, formulate a <I>null</I> <I>hypothesis</I>,   denoted <I>H </I><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT>, which is the complement of   what you hope to show. Then, derive a <I>sampling distribution</I>   of all possible sample results, given <I>H</I>   <FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT>. Then, if your sample result is very   unlikely according to this <I>H </I><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT> sampling   distribution, you may reject <I>H</I> <FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT> and   accept the alternative, complement hypothesis. The probability of   incorrectly rejecting H0, denoted <I>p</I>, is bounded by a   parameter denoted a. Conventionally, researchers set a = .05, so   they will not reject <I>H</I><FONT SIZE=2>   </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT> unless the probability of an observed   result given <I>H</I> <FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT> is <I>p</I> &lt; .05.   </P>      <P>Here's the catch: <I>H</I><FONT SIZE=2>   </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT> must be an identity, such as, "boys'   confidence is equal to girls' confidence," otherwise, it is   impossible to derive the sampling distribution. This means that   the alternative hypothesis must be an inequality (for example,   boys are more confident, less confident, or simply not equally   confident). And so, you can only <I>reject</I> an identity   hypothesis; you can never accept one. Failure to reject an   identity <I>H</I><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT> does   not make the identity true. As we will see, tests fail for reasons   that have nothing to do with the veracity of the null hypothesis,   notably large sample variance or small sample size.</P>      <P>So how are you supposed to demonstrate identities within the   framework of statistical hypothesis testing? For example, how can   you show that boys and girls really are equally confident? You   cannot <I>prove</I> anything statistically, but if you fail to   reject the null hypothesis, you can then try to show that boys and   girls are very unlikely to have different confidence levels. If   you succeed, then you have accrued support for the null hypothesis   (in addition to failing to reject it) and you may "accept" it.   </P>      <P>One approach is to derive a confidence interval for the   difference between boys' and girls' confidence. In essence, you   attempt to show that the true difference in confidence falls in a   narrow range with high probability. For example, given the data in   the gender data set, we can say with 95% confidence that the true   difference between boys' and girls' confidence lies in the   interval .275 &#177; .413 (see <I>Empirical   Methods</I>,<A HREF="#1">(1)</A> ch. 4, for formulas). This   confidence interval does not center around zero, nor is it narrow:   confidence scores in the gender data set range from 2.0 to 5.0,   and the width of the interval around the difference of boys' and   girls' scores is .826. So for the gender data set, we cannot find   support for the identity hypothesis. Although we couldn't reject   it, we also cannot accept it.</P>      <P>A second way to demonstrate identities depends on the   <I>power</I> of statistical tests. Power is the probability that a   test will reject the null hypothesis if it is false. Several   factors affect power. Some tests are intrinsically more powerful   than others. For example, you might test whether the means or the   medians of two groups are significantly different, but a test of   means will generally be more powerful than a test of medians   because the mean summarizes more information about a group than   the median. Sample size and sample variance also affect power; in   general, as the former increases and the latter decreases, a given   test is increasingly likely to reject the null hypothesis   correctly. Now, suppose an extremely powerful test fails to find a   difference between boys' and girls' confidence. Then, you could   argue that the test would have found a difference if one exists,   and it didn't, so you "accept" the null hypothesis that boys and   girls are identical. On the other hand, if the test is weak (which   it is, in the gender data set), then the failure to find a   difference between boys and girls does not mean they are   identical. Computing the power of a test is more involved than   computing confidence intervals (see <I>Empirical Methods</I>,   <A HREF="#1">(1)</A> sec. 4.9 for details).</P>      <P><B>Inadequate attention to variance.</B> Suppose our null   hypothesis, <I>H</I><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT>, is   that boys and girls are equally confident, and our alternative   hypothesis, <I>H</I> <FONT SIZE=1>1</FONT>, is that boys are more   confident. As noted above, a t test of the gender data fails to   reject <I>H</I><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT>, so we   cannot conclude <I>H</I> <FONT SIZE=1>1</FONT>. Many analyses   published in the AI literature stop here-with the result of a   <I>t</I> test-but, this result is very misleading. To understand   why, it will help to review how t tests (indeed, all statistical   tests) work. Test statistics such as t compare the magnitude of an   observed effect to the variance of the sampling distribution given   <I>H</I><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT>. This variance   is called the <I>standard error.</I> In general, increasing the   sample size decreases the standard error and makes the observed   effect more significant; whereas increasing sample variance   increases the standard error and decreases significance. Thus,   three factors affect whether an observed effect is statistically   significant: the magnitude of the effect (for example, a   difference of .275 in mean confidence), sample size, and sample   variance. The researcher controls sample size, and has indirect   control over sample variance. Obviously, if the researcher   controlled all three factors, there would be no point to running   an experiment.</P>      <P>One might boost an observed effect to significance by   collecting a very large sample, but this tactic wastes data. More   important, it neglects the most informative cause of insignificant   results, sample variance. Sometimes, sample variance is large and   truly random, and nothing can be done about it. But usually,   sample variance reflects the combined influence of several   factors. If you can tease these influences apart, you can get   statistically significant results with no additional data, and a   better understanding of the data as well.</P>      <P>To illustrate, Table 2 shows a two-way analysis of variance of   the gender data set. Two-way analysis of variance decomposes the   sample variance into four parts: two represent the effects of the   factors (called <I>main effects</I>), one represents the   interaction between the factors (called the <I>interaction   effect</I>), and one is due to random chance (called   <I>error</I>). The mean square column in Table 2 gives the   relative magnitudes of these components. (Mean squares are just   summed, squared deviations divided by degrees of freedom, both   listed in Table 2-that is, they are variances.) F statistics test   whether the main effects and interaction effect are large relative   to the effect of random chance. The main effect of grade level is   highly significant (<I>p</I> = .0027), whereas the main effect of   gender is insignificant (<I>p</I> = .1287). There is a tantalizing   interaction effect (<I>p</I> = .0482): Apparently, the effect of   grade-level on confidence depends on gender, or conversely, the   effect of gender on confidence depends on grade.</P>      <P><TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH="80%">      <TR>         <TD>            <P>Source         </TD><TD>            <P>Degree of Freedom         </TD><TD>            <P>Sum of Squares         </TD><TD>            <P>Mean of Square         </TD><TD>            <P>F         </TD><TD>            <P>Probability (<I><FONT SIZE=1>P</FONT></I> )         </TD></TR>      <TR>         <TD>            <P>Gender         </TD><TD>            <P>1         </TD><TD>            <P>.907         </TD><TD>            <P>.907         </TD><TD>            <P>2.407         </TD><TD>            <P>.1287         </TD></TR>      <TR>         <TD>            <P>Grade         </TD><TD>            <P>3         </TD><TD>            <P>6.312         </TD><TD>            <P>2.104         </TD><TD>            <P>5.581         </TD><TD>            <P>.0027         </TD></TR>      <TR>         <TD>            <P>Interaction         </TD><TD>            <P>3         </TD><TD>            <P>3.247         </TD><TD>            <P>1.082         </TD><TD>            <P>2.871         </TD><TD>            <P>.0482         </TD></TR>      <TR>         <TD>            <P>Error         </TD><TD>            <P>40         </TD><TD>            <P>15.08         </TD><TD>            <P>.377         </TD><TD>            <P>         </TD><TD>            <P>         </TD></TR>   </TABLE></P>      <P><B>Table 2.</B> Analysis of variance showing a significant main   effect of grade level and a significant interaction effect.</P>      <P>The means of each grade-gender combination complete the picture   (see Table 3). Boys&iacute; confidence decreases gradually from   4.467 in fourth grade to 4.0 in seventh grade (all children start   out overconfident), whereas girls' confidence starts lower (3.75),   peaks in fifth grade, and then drops. In short, boys' confidence   follows a different developmental pattern than does girls'. The   interaction effect in Table 2 picks up this difference.</P>      <P><TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH="70%">      <TR>         <TD>            <P><B>Grade</B>         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>4         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>5         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>6         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>7         </TD></TR>      <TR>         <TD>            <P><B>Boys</B>         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>4.467         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>4.450         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>4.167         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>4.000         </TD></TR>      <TR>         <TD>            <P><B>Girls</B>         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>3.750         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>4.650         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>4.450         </TD><TD>            <P ALIGN=CENTER>3.133         </TD></TR>   </TABLE></P>      <P><B>Table 3.</B> Mean confidence for boys and girls at four   grade levels.</P>      <P>So, does gender affect confidence? The <I>t</I> test says no,   but the analysis of variance, which decomposes sample variance   further, says the effect of gender is felt through its interaction   with grade level. This interaction effect is invisible to the   <I>t</I> test: it becomes clear only when two factors are analyzed   for their independent and joint effects. The additional main   effect and interaction effect "soak up" some of the sample   variance that made the original t test insignificant. By   concentrating on sample variance, we see that the effect of gender   on confidence changes with age. Had we attempted to boost the   effect of gender in the original <I>t</I> test by collecting a   larger sample, we would have wasted data and missed this important   dependency.</P>      <P><B>Multiple comparisons.</B> At this juncture in an analysis,   researchers might be tempted to compare individual mean scores.   For example, to see whether boys have significantly higher scores   at each grade level than girls, you would compare 4.467 to 3.750,   4.450 to 4.650, and so on, with individual <I>t</I> tests. This   tactic leads to the problem of multiple comparisons. Recall that   every statistical test has a probability, <I>p</I> &lt; a, of   incorrectly rejecting <I>H</I><FONT SIZE=2>   </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT>. Note that a refers to a single test;   we'll mark this fact by adding a subscript-"c" for "comparison"-to   a. Suppose we conduct two tests with ac = .05. What is the   probability that at least one test incorrectly rejects   <I>H</I><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT>? Clearly, it is   1 - (1 - ac)<SUP><FONT SIZE=1>2</FONT></SUP> = .0975. In general,   if we conduct n tests, the probability that at least one   incorrectly rejects <I>H</I><FONT SIZE=2>   </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT> is</P>      <P ALIGN=CENTER>a<FONT SIZE=1>e</FONT>=( 1 - (1 -   a<FONT SIZE=1>c</FONT>)<SUP>n</SUP></P>      <P>This "experimentwise error," a<FONT SIZE=1>e</FONT>, is not   precisely known because the tests are generally not independent   (see <I>Empirical Methods</I>, <A HREF="#1">(1)</A> p. 190). If we   compare boys and girls at all four grade levels, setting   a<FONT SIZE=1>c</FONT> = .05, the probability of at least one   error is approximately 1 - (1 -   .05)<SUP><FONT SIZE=2>4</FONT></SUP> = .185. In other words, the   probability of detecting a difference between boys and girls where   none exists is roughly one in five. I have reviewed papers in   which authors report dozens of pairwise comparisons, virtually   guaranteeing that some apparently significant results are   spurious. Unfortunately, there is no way to know which of the   apparent results are wrong.</P>      <P>Clearly, any solution to the problem of multiple comparisons   involves a tradeoff between a<FONT SIZE=1>e</FONT> and   a<FONT SIZE=1>c</FONT>. You can favor a<FONT SIZE=1>e</FONT>, but   this requires reducing ac, making it harder to reject   <I>H</I><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=1>0</FONT> on a given   test, which means that some weaker effects are no longer   significant. Or, you can favor a<FONT SIZE=1>c</FONT>, resulting   in elevated probabilities of one or more spurious tests. I   recommend a hybrid approach, where you conduct <I>n</I> tests with   a stringent a<FONT SIZE=1>c</FONT>, designed to give   a<FONT SIZE=1>e</FONT> ( .05, and then you conduct all the tests   again with the usual a<FONT SIZE=1>c</FONT> = .05. Finally, you   compare the results: which tests were significant with   a<FONT SIZE=1>c</FONT> = .05 but not with the more stringent   a<FONT SIZE=1>c</FONT>? These are the tests that might be   spurious, and if you care deeply about any of them, you might   attempt to reduce variance or increase sample size to boost them   to significance (see <I>Empirical Methods</I>,   <A HREF="#1">(1)</A> pp. 195-205, for details).</P>      <P>I have described three errors in data analysis and how to fix   or compensate for them. I selected these three because they are   common and easy to fix, and because they can ruin your research.   These are not trifling errors. You should not accept the null   hypothesis simply because you cannot reject it; you must provide   additional support for it. If you fail to notice interactions   between factors, you might conclude that a factor has no effect,   when its effect is actually realized through interactions with   another factor. If you run multiple comparisons without correcting   ac, some will probably be spurious. I have noticed that many AI   researchers worry about relatively subtle aspects of statistical   practice but neglect the issues I have raised here. For instance,   one colleague ran scores of uncorrected pairwise comparisons   because she thought she wasn't allowed to run an analysis of   variance. True, the analysis of variance assumes normally   distributed populations (for that matter, so does the t test that   was used for the pairwise comparisons), but any errors that might   have been induced by violating this assumption are minuscule   compared with the errors almost certainly induced by multiple   uncorrected comparisons.</P>      <b>References</b>      <P><a name="1">1. P.R. Cohen, Empirical Methods for Artificial Intelligence,   MIT Press, Cambridge, Mass., 1995.</P>      <P><a name="2">2. C.R. Beal, Boys and Girls: The Development of Gender Roles,   McGraw-Hill, New York, 1994.</P>         <P><src img="x5010sa.gif">      <P>Paul R. Cohen is a professor of computer science at the   University of Massachusetts, Amherst, and the director of the   Experimental Knowledge Systems Laboratory. His research is in   campaign planning, simulation, machine learning, and the   development of conceptual structure from sensorimotor interaction.   He received his PhD from Stanford in computer science and   psychology, and his MS from UCLA and his BA from the University of   California at San Diego, both in psychology. He is the program   cochair for the Second International Conference on Intelligent   Data Analysis and is a fellow of the AAAI. Contact him at the   Dept. of Computer Science, Box 34610, Univ. of Massachusetts,   Amherst, MA 01003-4601; cohen@cs.umass.edu;   http://eksl-www.cs.umass.edu/~cohen/home.html.</P>         <P><HR></P><P><I><A HREF="../../../expert.htm">IEEE Expert Online</A></I> |<A HREF="../../../depart.htm">Departments</A> |<A HREF="../../../feature.htm">Features</A> |<A HREF="../../../ai-www/ai-www.htm">AI on the WWW</A> |<A HREF="../../../board/board.htm">Editorial Board</A><BR><A HREF="../../../../pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</A> |<A HREF="../../../../../cshome.htm">Computer Society home page</A></P><P>Send comments and questions about <I>IEEE Expert Online</I> toAnne Humphreys and Managing Editor Dick Price,<A HREF="mailto:ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu,dprice@computer.org">ah34+@andrew.cmu.eduand dprice@computer.org</A>. Send general comments and questionsabout the IEEE Computer Society's Web site to<A HREF="mailto:webmaster@computer.org">webmaster@computer.org</A></P><P><FONT SIZE=2>Personal use of this material is permitted. However,permission to reprint/republish this material for advertising orpromotional purposes or for creating new collective works for resaleor redistribution must be obtained from the IEEE. By choosing to viewthis document, you agree to all provisions of the copyright lawsprotecting it.</FONT></P><P><FONT SIZE=2>Copyright (c) Institute of Electrical and ElectronicsEngineers, Inc. All rights reserved.</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML