<html><head><title>Goals for Growth</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><img src="../../../expert.gif" border=0 height=41 width=510><p><a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a></p><body><blockquote><h2>Goals for Growth</h2> <h3>Stephen E. Cross</h3><p><img src="x2002a1.gif" hspace=10 border=0 height=203 width=150 align=left>I hope you find this an exciting and informative issue. We continueour tracks on intelligent control, AI in civil engineering, andknowledge acquisition, and are starting an AI applications track,edited by Dan O'Leary. This issue also features an article onenterprise modeling, supplemented by our Executive Insightdepartment. Our other departments focus on ongoing work at Ohio State(World Impact), neural networks (Trends and Controversies), and theevolution of the World Wide Web (Internet Services). As usual,Expert's staff has worked very hard to produce an on-time, qualityissue. Also, check out Expert Online at <a href ="http://www.computer.org/pubs/expert/expert.htm">http://www.computer.org/pubs/expert/expert.htm</a>. Manythanks to <a href = "mailto:ah34@andrew.cmu.edu">Anne Humphreys</a>for continuing her excellent work on our on-line presence.<P>You should receive this issue at about the time we hold our annualEditorial Board meeting. This year's meeting is on August 4, 1996, inPortland, Oregon, the site of the National Conference on ArtificialIntelligence (sponsored by the American Association on ArtificialIntelligence). As I write this, I'm thinking about the meeting'sagenda and the goals I would like to see the magazine accomplish in1997 and beyond. As I prepare, I'm updating the magazine's businessplan for review at the meeting (see the <a href ="#sidebar">sidebar</a>).<P>How are we doing with respect to the plan that our board approved lastsummer? Not too badly in terms of quality, although there will alwaysbe ways that we can improve. A few accomplishments stand out. We havesuccessfully, I think, refocused the magazine on intelligentsystems. We continue to be one of the most respected and highly citedAI publications. I'm very pleased with how the magazine is evolvingand the excellent support that I receive from the editorial board, thedepartment editors, and the Computer Society's professional staff. Thecomments I receive from readers are generally favorable, and thosethat are critical have helped us to focus on new topic areas and toimprove both our publication philosophy and content. Our on-lineversion of the magazine has received rave reviews.<P>Regarding the readership goals in the business plan, I'm veryconcerned. At the end of 1994, our readership (measured bysubscriptions) was 9,341. At the end of 1995, it was 8,338. That's a10% decline, which is typical for most technical magazines. Initialindications for 1996 are that we are up four to five percent, but thatis hardly enough.<P>We are doing everything we can to increase readership. If we do notincrease readership, our production budget will be decreased, makingit ever harder to produce a high-quality magazine. Please encourageyour colleagues to subscribe. Instead of giving them a copy of themagazine, give them a subscription form or this email address:member-services@computer.org. If you think of ways we can publicizethe magazine better, please contact Dick Price (<a href ="mailto:dprice@computer.org">dprice@computer.org</a>) or me (<a href ="mailto:scross@cs.cmu.edu">scross@cs.cmu.edu</a>).<P>I believe we are meeting the other goals that are described in theplan, by implementing the thrusts listed in the sidebar. Ourpublication calendar now extends 18 months into the future (the backcover lists the next six issues). We have introduced new departments,in many cases as a direct result of suggestions from our readers, andwe have strengthened our editorial policies through the help ofexcellent guest editors and reviewers. We will soon be introducingspecial tracks and departments on technology transition and increasingour focus on industry needs. I hope that we will have an IndustryAdvisory Board (akin to IEEE Software's IAB) by the end of the year.<P>We need to improve in four areas that deal with technical coverage andeditorial policy: emphasizing the evaluation of research,understanding industry needs, stressing engineering approaches, andhighlighting visionary systems. Let me briefly discuss each.<P><ul><li><b>Evaluation</b> A fundamental criticism we received from ourSound Off Feedback (Feb. '96) was that articles should devote morespace to the evaluation of achievements. At our editorial boardmeeting, I intend to discuss changes to our editorial policy andreview procedures to accomplish this. Some obvious questions centerboth on technology and systems-level perspectives. Why was thetechnique chosen? How was it tested? How does it contrast to otherapproaches? How does it scale?  Is it robust? What advantages does ithave over other approaches-AI and non-AI? I'd like to introduce amini-symposium to discuss evaluation from an applications and industryperspective. If you can recommend anyone to participate, pleasecontact me.<P><li><b>Industry needs</b> The Summer 1996 issue of IEEE ComputationalScience & Engineering published an informative mini-symposium, "WhatIndustry Needs from Academia: CSE Education in the 21st Century." Itcomprised eight short position statements from industry leaders. Ihope to introduce our IAB later this year through a similar piece.<P><li><b>Engineering</b> As our field matures, issues in software andsystems engineering become more critical. I firmly believe that wehave an opportunity to contribute significantly to engineering-in boththe engineering of intelligent systems and the insertion ofintelligence into design and engineering. Expert's February, April,and June 1997 issues deal directly with this. We are also looking forcase-study articles that deal with intelligent systems that have beenfielded for more than one year. What has been the experience in using,maintaining, and extending these systems?<P><li><b>Visionary systems</b> The rise of the World Wide Web, emergenceof information appliances, and explosive progress along multipletechnology fronts (such as speech technology) mean that new kinds ofsystems are possible. Not surprisingly, the June 24th Business Week'scover feature was "The Information Appliance." Two enablingtechnologies the magazine described were intelligent software agentsand speech understanding. We need to be as proactive in articulatingthe "world of the possible" as are the leading publications read byour management.<P></ul>As I continue to plan for this year's board meeting, I will focus oninitiatives to enhance your magazine. As always, I would appreciateyour insights and thoughts.<P><a name = "sidebar"><h3>Summary of the IEEE Expert business plan</h3><h3>Our mission</h3> Be the premiere magazine in intelligent systemtechnology-for the producers and consumers of the technology(researchers, educators, system builders, and their management).<P><h3>Our goals</h3><ul><li>Double the size of the readership by 1998.<li>Achieve a ratio of contributors from industry versus academics of40/60 for articles and 60/40 for departments.</ul><h3>Critical success factors</h3><ul><li>Carry authoritative, informative, balanced reviews of the issuesthat our readers most want and need to know about.<li>Sustain a reputation as a prestigious, refereed publication, sothat the best authors submit articles.<li>Provide timely information in an accessible, informative style.<li>Reach our intended audience in significant numbers.<li>Be profitable.</ul><h3>Near-term challenges</h3><ul><li>Publish on time, six times a year.<li>Create a long-range publication calendar that reflects ourreaders' interests and needs.<li>Have an editorial board that reflects our readership (withincreased international and industry membership).<li>Introduce new departments (with amplified, extended electronic coverage).<li>Create an industry advisory board.</ul><h3>Editorial plan</h3>Immediately initiate actions that will:<ul><li>insure relevancy to an applications-focused readership.<li>increase awareness among potential subscribers.<li>increase international exposure and membership.<li>maintain Expert's reputation as a publisher of high-quality articles.</ul><h3>Thrusts</h3><ol><li>We will create and maintain a publication calendar with an 18-month horizon.<P><li>Each special issue and special track will contain articles thatdescribe the technology and applications based on the technology. Theprimary goal is to provide "information you can use."<P><li>We will introduce new departments and features to provide timelyinformation to our readers. We will extend these ideas via electronicaccess (Expert On Line- <a href ="http://www.computer.org/pubs/expert/expert.htm">http://www.computer.org/pubs/expert/expert.htm</a>)to provide interaction opportunities for readers.<P><li>One new department will focus on technology transition. This willlet the magazine examine different methods for the management ofadvanced technology. In addition, for the first year, the departmentwill highlight international centers, thus increasing our readers'awareness of the international community, and the community'sawareness of Expert.<P><li>We will revise the document of understanding (which specifies aGuest Editor's duties), editorial guidelines, and review forms toensure consistently high-quality review and timely feedback toauthors.<P><li>We will start creating the Industry Advisory Board by recruitingat least five industry leaders to serve on the Editorial Board.<P></ol><hr><a href=mailto:scross@cs.cmu.edu>Stephen E. Cross</a> is the directorof the Information Technology Center at Carnegie Mellon University andthe Editor-in-Chief of IEEE Expert.  <p>Information Technology Center<br>School of Computer Science<br>Carnegie Mellon University<br>5000 Forbes Avenue<br>Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania<br>15213-3891<br>(412) 268-5543-phone<br>(412) 268-5576-fax<br>scross@computer.org<br><p>Point of contact:<br>Mary Anne Cowden<br>Administrative Associate<br>mac@cs.cmu.edu<br>(412) 268-6714-phone<br><hr><p><p><i><A HREF="../../../expert.htm">IEEE Expert Online</A></i> | <a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a> | <a href="../../../feature.htm">Features</a> | <A HREF="../../../ai-www/ai-www.htm">AI on the WWW</A> | <A HREF="../../../board/board.htm">Editorial Board</A><BR><p><P> <A HREF="../../../../pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</A> | <A HREF="../../../../../cshome.htm">Computer Society home page</A> </P><p>Send comments and questions about <i>IEEE Expert Online</i> to Anne Humphreys and Managing Editor Dick Price, <a href=mailto:ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu,dprice@computer.org>ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu and dprice@computer.org</a></p><p>Send general comments and questions about the IEEE Computer Society's Web site to <a href=mailto:webmaster@computer.org>webmaster@computer.org</a></p><P><font size=-1><i>Copyright (c) Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, Inc. All rights reserved.</P><P>Personal use of this material is permitted. However, permission to reprint/republish this material for advertising or promotional purposes or for creating new collective works for resale or redistribution must be obtained from the IEEE.</P><P>By choosing to view this document, you agree to all provisions of the copyright laws protecting it.</i></font></P></blockquote></body></html>
