<TITLE>World Impact</title><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img src="../../../expert.gif"><p><a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a><P><blockquote><h2>Intelligent control at the OSU Control Research Lab</h2><P><h3>Kevin M. Passino and Umit Ozguner, Ohio State University</h3>As reported in the series of articles that began in <i>IEEE Expert's</i>April issue and concludes here, the field of intelligent control haswitnessed remarkable growth recently. Two main trends fuel this surge:our increasing understanding of how bio- logical systems operate andastounding advances in computer technology. Together, these advancesencourage the development of the field of intelligent control byproviding alternative strategies for designing and implementingcontrollers for dynamical systems.<P>As remarkable as this growth has been, development of the resultingintelligent controllers still fits within the conventional engineeringmethodology for the construction of control systems. (<a href ="#1">1</a>) Thus, effective intelligent-control research requires ateam of investigators well-grounded in the theory and application ofconventional control methods. The Control Research Laboratory at OhioState's Department of Electrical Engineering is one such group (seethe "CRL team" sidebar).<P>This report includes some of the major players at the CRL and gives anoverview of the work going on there.<P><h3>Educational program</h3><P>The CRL's very active educational program involves directed research,formal classroom instruction, and several laboratories. Controlcourses offered in the Department of Electrical Engineering includefeedback control systems (undergraduate), control systems laboratory(undergraduate), feedback control systems (graduate), digital controlsystems, linear system theory I, linear system theory II, nonlinearsystems, control laboratory I, control laboratory II (IntelligentControl Laboratory), stochastic control, adaptive control, optimalcontrol, large-scale systems, robust control, and intelligentcontrol.<P>The Department of Electrical Engineering offers additional courses incomputers, signal processing, robotics, power systems, and many otherareas. Associated departments also give courses in control andintelligent systems, including intelligent diagnostic methods in theChemical Engineering Department and several artificial intelligencecourses in the Computer and Information Science Department.<P>Laboratories are an integral part of our educational program, enablingour students to solidify theoretical concepts and apply controlmethods to practical applications for the lab's sponsors. As describedin the following paragraphs, the CRL has several research andeducational laboratories.<P><i>Undergraduate Control Laboratory</i>. Students study lead-lagcompensation, proportional-integral-derivative control (PID),continuous and discrete-time implementations, and analogcomputers. The laboratory is also equipped with five PC stations withhigh-speed data-acquisition cards, and a general-purpose interfacebus, digital scope, programmable function generator, plotter, andprinter.<P><i>Intelligent Systems and Digital Control Laboratory</i>. Developed withsupport from the National Science Foundation, this laboratory is usedfor control laboratories I and II, senior design projects, andresearch:<P><ul><li><i>Control laboratory I</i>. Students gain hands-on experience indesigning, simulating, analyzing, and implementing real-timecontrollers, and learn about measurement techniques andinterfacing. Each lab addresses hardware and software aspects ofreal-time control. Types of control schemes that are covered includeon/off, PID, state feedback with and without observer, pulsewidthmodulation, variable structure, and adaptive control. Students canalso conduct experiments in temperature and motor control.<P><li><i> Control laboratory II (Intelligent Control Laboratory) </i>. Studentslearn about the hardware and software for real-time control andcomputer-aided-control system design packages (including a fuzzysystem design toolbox), and implement several intelligentcontrollers. Fuzzy control and adaptive fuzzy control receive specialemphasis. Additional projects include the use of neural networks orgenetic algorithms for control. To test intelligent control methods,students run experiments in process control, vibration damping in aflexible-link robot, swing-up and balancing of a rotational invertedpendulum, and balancing a ball on a beam.<P>The laboratory has five PC stations, each with a high-speed dataacquisition card and an Ethernet connection. In addition, each of theexperiments conducted here has its own interface electronics. Twoadditional experiments for the laboratory are currently underconstruction-an inverted pendulum on an inverted wedge and amagnetically levitated ball.<P><i>Senior design projects</i>. The CRL offers an engineering designcourse, a group project for seniors, that focuses on wheeledrobots. Teams of students work on control, sensing, and computerinterfacing, and on other topics needed to design and build anautonomous wheeled robot in an industry-like environment. CRL facultydirectly supervise other individual senior design projects.</ul><P><h3>Research program</h3><P>A variety of industrial and government sponsors support ourconventional and intelligent control research in the following:<P><ul><li><i> Fuzzy control</i>--dealing with direct, adaptive, and supervisorycontrol; fuzzy identification and estimation via learning fromexamples, and from least squares, gradient, and clustering methods;and stability analysis, analysis of limit cycles, and analysis ofsteady-state tracking error.<P><li><i> Neural control</i>--involving supervised training of neuralcontrollers, identification and adaptive control methods, stability ofneural control systems, and associative memories.<P><li><i> Genetic algorithms for control</i>--working with genetic algorithmsfor computer-aided-control system design, identification, andestimation; and adaptive and supervisory control.<P><li><i> Expert and planning systems for control</i>--studying systems fordirect and supervisory control and analyzing stability analysis ofclosed-loop systems that use expert controllers or planning systems ascontrollers.<P><li><i> Structural and functional hierarchies</i>--methods for layeringhierarchical intelligent controllers, distributed intelligent systems,mathematical analysis of structured hierarchies, intelligent andautonomous control architectures, and fundamental characteristics ofhierarchical intelligent controllers.<P><li><i> Hybrid systems</i>--including modeling, coupling of continuous anddiscrete state systems, controllability and stability analysis, usingsliding mode and decentralized control ideas, and applications tointelligent and other transportation systems.<P><li><i> Conventional control</i>--involving adaptive control, robust control,decentralized control and large-scale systems, system identification,nonlinear control, wavelets for control, sliding-mode control, andgame theory.<P></ul>CRL students and researchers study a variety of method applicationsand implementations, including<P><ul><li>Automotive systems (brakes, suspension, transmissions, electricvehicles).<P><li>Intelligent transportation systems (automated highways).<P><li>Process control (paper machines, distillation column, glassfurnace).<P><li>Aircraft control (fault tolerance, flexibility effects).<P><li>Aircraft engine control and estimation.<P><li>Flexible structures (trusses and robots).<P><li>Autonomous vehicles.<P><li>Manufacturing systems.<P><li>Robotics.<P></ul>Much of the research in intelligent control proceeds in parallel withthe development of conventional controllers. Sometimes, it isnecessary to spend a significant amount of time using theory (such asstability analysis) and experimental testbeds to determine thetrade-offs between conventional and intelligent controlmethods. Conventional methods will often supply very good solutions sothat intelligent control methods may not be needed (or desirable, ifmore difficult to implement). In other situations, intelligent controloften offers very effective solutions that out-perform conventionalmethods.<P><h2>Research laboratories and affiliated center</h2>Several facilities support our experimental work in control systemdevelopment.<P><i>Automotive Control Systems Laboratory</i>. This laboratory studies brakingsystem control, control over a network in a vehicle, continuouslyvariable transmissions, and electric vehicles (for example, control ofswitched-reluctance motors). Other related studies that have involvedfield work include brake system control and integrated control ofbraking and suspension.<P><i>Autonomous Vehicles Laboratory</i>. A variety of autonomous vehicles areconstructed here, including carts (for senior design projects) and arobotics transporter. This laboratory also supports CRL efforts todevelop automated highway systems.<P><i>Flexible Structures Laboratory</i>. Research is conducted on vibrationdamping in several types of beams, trusses, and robots. For instance,there have been studies on the control of a large interconnectedvibration experiment, a 16-foot cantilevered mass structure withslewable, flexible panels providing a multibody experiment platform; adeployable, planar, three-bay truss on air bearings; and a two-linkflexible robot.<P><i>Center for Intelligent Transportation Research</i>. Affiliated with theCRL and directed by Umit Ozguner, this interdepartmentalcenter undertakes a broad range of activities, including thedevelopment, with the support of Honda, of a multivehicle testbed atthe Transportation Research Center (East Liberty, Ohio) that includesseveral automobiles under full steering/braking/throttle control,traffic and transportation research, simulation and virtual realitystudies, and several student projects.<P>Often, the CRL works with its sponsors performing field experimentssuch as vibration damping at NASA and Wright Laboratories, automotivecontrol with Ford or GM, and various process control experiments.<P><b>Reference</b><P><ol><a name = "1"><li>K.M. Passino and U. Ozguner, "Intelligent Control: FromTheory to Application," IEEE Expert, Vol. 11, No. 2, Apr. 1996,pp. 28-30.<P></ol>Kevin M. Passino's biography appears in Expert's April 1996 issue,p. 30. Reach him at the Dept. of Electrical Engineering, Ohio StateUniv., 2015 Neil Ave., Columbus, OH 43210-1272; <a href ="mailto:passino@osu.edu">passino@osu.edu</a>; <a href ="http://eewww.eng.ohio-state.edu/~passino">http://eewww.eng.ohio-state.edu/~passino</a>. <P>Umit Ozguner's biography appears in Expert's April 1996 issue,p. 30. Reach him at the Dept. of Electrical Engineering, Ohio StateUniv., 2015 Neil Ave., Columbus, OH 43210-1272; <a href ="mailto:ozguner.1@osu.edu">ozguner.1@osu.edu</a>; <a href =http://eewww.eng.ohio-state.edu/~umit">http://eewww.eng.ohio-state.edu/~umit</a>.<P>CRL team<P>The CRL has grown steadily in the 15 years since it was formed in theDepartment of Electrical Engineering. Current CRL faculty include JoseB. Cruz, Jr., Hooshang Hemami, Hitay Ozbay, Umit Ozguner,Kevin M. Passino, Vadim Utkin, Stephen Yurkovich, and Yuan Zheng (seeFigure A).<P>The CRL also participates in several interdisciplinary activities. Inparticular, the following people and departments contribute to CRLresearch: Aeronautical and Astronautical Engineering (Rama Yedavalli,Hayrani Oz), Chemical Engineering (James Davis, Bhavik Bakshi),Computer and Information Science (Judith Gardiner, Feng Zhao,B. Chandrasekaran), Mathematics (Bostwick Wyman), and MechanicalEngineering (K. (Cheena) Srinivasan, Giorgio Rizzoni).<P>The CRL group in electrical engineering usually has visiting faculty,several postdoctoral researchers or research scientists, and 35-40graduate students.<P><P>Figure A. From left to right: Hooshang Hemami, Umit Ozguner,Stephen Yurkovich, Kevin M. Passino, Vadim Utkin, and HitayOzbay.<P><img src = "x8082s1.gif"><P><P><BR><hr><p><i><A HREF="../../../expert.htm">IEEE Expert Online</A></i> | <a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a> | <a href="../../../feature.htm">Features</a> | <A HREF="../../../ai-www/ai-www.htm">AI on the WWW</A> | <A HREF="../../../board/board.htm">Editorial Board</A><BR><p><P> <A HREF="../../../../pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</A> | <A HREF="../../../../../cshome.htm">Computer Society home page</A> </P><p>Send comments and questions about <i>IEEE Expert Online</i> to Anne Humphreys and Managing Editor Dick Price, <a href=mailto:ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu,dprice@computer.org>ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu and dprice@computer.org</a></p><p>Send general comments and questions about the IEEE Computer Society's Web site to <a href=mailto:webmaster@computer.org>webmaster@computer.org</a></p><P><font size=-1><i>Copyright (c) Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, Inc. All rights reserved.</P><P>Personal use of this material is permitted. However, permission to reprint/republish this material for advertising or promotional purposes or for creating new collective works for resale or redistribution must be obtained from the IEEE.</P><P>By choosing to view this document, you agree to all provisions of the copyright laws protecting it.</i></font></P></body></html>
