<TITLE>Neural-network speech processing for toys and consumer electronics</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img src="../../../expert.gif"><p><a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a><br><a href="http://www.itc.cmu.edu/~expert/script.html">Reply</a><br><a href="http://www.itc.cmu.edu/~expert/responses.html">Read reponses</a><br><blockquote><h2>Neural-network speech processing for toys and consumer electronics</h2><h3>Michael C. Mozer, Sensory Inc. and the University of Colorado, Boulder</h3>The ongoing challenge in speech research is the recognition ofcontinuous, unconstrained speech. In comparison, isolated wordrecognition with small vocabularies is easy. Many research efforts andcommercial ventures aim at the high-end problem. Sensory Inc. hassuccessfully focused on the low end, producing a family of inexpensivespeech-recognition ICs for markets such as interactive toys, consumerelectronics, electronic learning aids, telecommunication devices,security systems, and household appliances. These markets areextremely cost-conscious and demand solutions in the under-five-dollarprice range. Previous low-cost solutions relied on coarse propertiesof the speech signal, such as the amplitude envelope or zero crossingrates, and typically yielded poor recognition performance. Digitalsignal processor-based approaches can achieve adequate performance butare beyond the low-cost market's reach. Sensory uses a neuralnetwork-based approach that provides robust performance at a low cost.<P>Sensory's general-purpose RSC-164 controller performs four speechrecognition functions. Speaker-independent recognition worksregardless of the user's age, accent, or gender and withoutuser-specific training; it can handle predefined vocabularies of up to15 alternatives. Speaker-dependent recognition requires user trainingbut works for vocabularies of up to 60 alternatives that are notspecified in advance. System designers can realize arbitrarily largevocabularies for both recognizers by switching the set of alternativeson the basis of the context in which a response is requested. Therecognizers can also reject an utterance as not belonging to thecurrent recognition set-for example, when the user responds "maybe" toa yes/no query. Speaker verification recognizes a stored passwordspoken by a particular speaker for security applications. Wordspotting picks out a key word from continuous speech.<P>In addition to its speech recognition functions, the RSC-164 performspolyphonic music synthesis, speech synthesis, sound effects, and voicerecord and playback, and can drive and communicate with theapplication product. It thus serves as a single-chip solution forspeech recognition, synthesis, and application product control.<P>The RSC-164 is a 4-Mips, 8-bit microcontroller with an instruction setsimilar to Intel's MCS51. It has on-board analog-to-digital anddigital-to-analog conversion, digital filtering, automatic gaincontrol, 384 bytes of RAM, 64 Kbytes of ROM, 16 programmablegeneral-purpose I/O lines, and an external memory bus, and can drive aspeaker directly via a pulsewidth modulator.<P>The neural-network architectures and algorithms that underlie speechsignal analysis in the RSC-164 are fairly traditional, but the RSC-164imposes some interesting challenges. First, RAM, which consumes alarge area on a chip, is minimal; the 384 available bytes of RAMincludes storage for the current speech pattern to be recognized. So,the implementation must minimize the use of intermediate statevariables, and on-line learning is quite restricted becausebackpropagation training, which would require dynamic storage ofmultiple patterns, is infeasible. Second, although the microcontrolleris relatively fast, it does not have hardware floating-pointarithmetic, and software emulation is quite slow. Thus, the neural netmust be implemented primarily with fixed-point computation. Third,while the digital filtering provides key information about the speechsignal, it is not as rich a representation as the full powerspectrum. To make the most of the data available, Sensory used expertknowledge about salient features of the speech signal in constructingthe neural-net input representation.<P><b>Speaker-independent recognition.</b> Figure 1a shows the basic processingstages that occur when an acoustic signal is presented forspeaker-independent recognition. A segmentation stage determines wherethe utterance begins and ends in the continuous input stream, aproblem made difficult by background noise in naturalenvironments. Once segmented, the utterance passes through a set ofdigital filters. Time normalization is then performed and acousticfeatures are extracted from the filter outputs. This preprocessingproduces a fixed-size vector of about a hundred elements that servesas input to a neural-network recognizer. On the basis of the contextin which the utterance is made, a network is selected that has theappropriate set of response alternatives. he network models theprobability distribution of each word class, conditional on the inputpattern. Included among the response alternatives is a "none of theabove" category, into which any word or sound that's not a member ofthe recognition set is classified.<P><img src = "x40041.gif"><P><b>Figure 1. Overviews: (a) speaker-independent recognition algorithm;(b) speaker-dependent recognition algorithm.</b><P>As is typical in neural-net applications, an appropriate inputrepresentation is essential. Because the input representation is atleast as important to the recognizer's success as the type ofclassifier used, we have put much effort into selecting optimal filterparameters and feature-extraction algorithms. Having an appropriatecorpus of training examples is also crucial to the recognizer'ssuccess. Sensory employs a staff of linguists who collect speechsamples, roughly 400 per vocabulary word. They try to match thedistribution of speakers in the training corpus with the distributionof eventual users of the product, by age, gender, and regionalaccent. They also match conditions of data collection to conditions ofeventual usage-noisy environments, room echoes, and the speaker'sphysical state. Neural-net training occurs off line, using the grabbag of tricks that have become standard in the field, including crossvalidation and Bayesian methods for model selection, the adding ofweight constraints between neighboring input frames, and ensemblemethods. Altogether, over 2,000 networks are trained in selecting theone that will end up in the application product.<P>Speaker-independent recognition with a vocabulary of a dozenalternatives achieves recognition accuracies better than 95% in actualuse.<P><b>Speaker-dependent recognition.</b> In speaker-dependent recognition, theuser trains the system by speaking several examples of each vocabularyitem. These examples serve as <i>templates</i>, which the system thenserially compares with an <i>unknown</i> input pattern. Figure 1b shows thebasic processing stages involved in this comparison. Dynamic timewarping aligns the unknown pattern to the template. The standardspeech-recognition approach is to use the alignment score as themeasure of how well the unknown pattern matches the template, and thento choose the template with the best match score. However, we havesignificantly improved performance by comparing the warped unknownpattern with the template, using a neural network, as shown in Figure1b. The neural network is trained in advance to produce high matchscores when the template and unknown pattern represent the sameutterance, and low scores otherwise. Speaker-dependent recognitionachieves accuracies of 98% with 30-word vocabularies.<P><b>Speaker verification.</b> The RSC-164's speaker verification functionoperates very much like speaker-dependent recognition, although thetraining methodology and performance criterion are different. Speakerverification decisions can result in two types of errors. <i>Falseaccepts</i> occur when the match score is high enough so that the unknownpattern is believed to match the stored password-that it is the sameutterance spoken by the same speaker. <i>False rejects</i> occur when thematch score is too low, even though the speaker and the utterance arethe same as in the stored password. By varying the match threshold,the RSC-164 can trade off false accepts against false rejects. It canselect the threshold to minimize either false accepts or falserejects. The equal error rate for speaker verification-when thethreshold is set such that false accept and reject rates are equal-is1.5%.<P><b>Announced products.</b> The RSC-164 recently received <i>EDN Magazine's</i>"Innovation of the Year Award" in the ICs and semiconductorscategory. In addition to the RSC-164, Sensory has developed twospecial-purpose ICs, one based on speaker verification (VoicePassword) and the other on speaker-dependent recognition (VoiceDirect). The first products using Sensory's speech-recognitiontechnology were available in late 1995. Current products includeelectronic learning aids (Fisher-Price, Tiger/Playskool, Tomy, andVTech) and speaker verification for automobile remote security systems(CrimeStoppers, Guardian International, Omega Research). Over a dozenother products are under development. Sensory will sell millions ofneural network-based speech-recognition chips in 1996.<P><hr><b>Michael C. Mozer</b> is an associate professor in the Institute ofCognitive Science and the Department of Computer Science at theUniversity of Colorado, Boulder, and also serves as the Director ofNeural Network Technologies for Sensory Inc. His research interestsinclude neural-network models of human perception, attention, andawareness, and applications of neural-network predictive and controltechniques for home automation. He received a PhD in psychology andcognitive science at the University of California, San Diego. Reachhim at the Computer Science Dept., Univ. of Colorado, Boulder, CO80309-0430; <a href ="mailto:mozer@cs.colorado.edu"><i>mozer@cs.colorado.edu</i></a><P><P><BR><hr><p><i><A HREF="../../../expert.htm">IEEE Expert Online</A></i> | <a href="../../../depart.htm">Departments</a> | <a href="../../../feature.htm">Features</a> | <A HREF="../../../ai-www/ai-www.htm">AI on the WWW</A> | <A HREF="../../../board/board.htm">Editorial Board</A><BR><p><P> <A HREF="../../../../pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</A> | <A HREF="../../../../../cshome.htm">Computer Society home page</A> </P><p>Send comments and questions about <i>IEEE Expert Online</i> to Anne Humphreys and Managing Editor Dick Price, <a href=mailto:ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu,dprice@computer.org>ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu and dprice@computer.org</a></p><p>Send general comments and questions about the IEEE Computer Society's Web site to <a href=mailto:webmaster@computer.org>webmaster@computer.org</a></p><P><font size=1>Copyright (c) Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, Inc. All rights reserved.</P><P>Personal use of this material is permitted. However, permission to reprint/republish this material for advertising or promotional purposes or for creating new collective works for resale or redistribution must be obtained from the IEEE.</P><P>By choosing to view this document, you agree to all provisions of the copyright laws protecting it.</font></P>
