<!--This file created 9/23/96 10:51 AM by Claris Home Page version 1.0--><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>knight.html</TITLE>   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 1.0">   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=66 BOTTOM=624 LEFT=8 RIGHT=538>   <TITLE> It's time for your evaluation </TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="../../../expert.gif" X-SAS-UseImageWidthX-SAS-UseImageHeight ALIGN=bottom></P><P><A HREF="x5010.htm">Trends and Controversies</A><BR><A HREF="http://www.itc.cmu.edu/~expert/script.html">Reply</A><BR><A HREF="http://www.itc.cmu.edu/~expert/responses.html">Readreponses</A><BR></P><BLOCKQUOTE><H2>It's time for your evaluation</H2><H3>Kevin Knight, USC/ISI</H3><P>If there is a word that strikes fear into the hearts of speech andnatural-language researchers, it is "evaluation." It's not that wedon't like evaluation--mostly, we do--it's just that we've developedthis knee-jerk response: "Another evaluation? Already? But we justdid an evaluation!"</P><P>Well, that's an exaggeration. But funder-promoted, commonevaluations have profoundly affected our research in years past. Inthese evaluations, researchers agree on a number of tasks andcriteria for success, then work independently on those tasks. In manycases, funding agencies provide sample inputs and outputs in advance,but withhold test data until "evaluation day." Several months later,participating researchers gather at a specialized workshop to discussresults and techniques. Whether you're interested in machinetranslation, morphology, speech-query processing, informationextraction, or information retrieval, there is a common evaluationsomewhere where you can test your ideas in an empirical,quantitatively scored setting.</P><P>I'd like to describe why I think these common evaluations (or"bake-offs") are compelling--first some weaknesses, then somestrengths.</P><P>The weaknesses of bake-offs are familiar to many: the intervalsbetween evaluations are too short, different research sites tend toconverge on a single technology, and simple, robust strategies beatcomplex ones every time. Simple strategies win partly because ofnormal software engineering demons, but mostly because knowledgeacquisition is easier for simple representations. That's whynatural-language people don't talk so much about AI and semanticsthese days: sure it's nice, but what does it buy you? For instance,there is no shortage of ideas about how semantic analysis could helpimprove information retrieval, but the interesting thing is that veryfew of those ideas have panned out in evaluations. This is animportant result. It means things aren't as simple as we oftenbelieve, and it means that great opportunities are still out therefor AI and semantics research. It also means we're turning out awhole bunch of natural-language PhDs who have never seen an AI-stylemeaning representation, cast in terms of a domain/world model, usingthe power of first-order logic. This is a problem.</P><P>These bake-offs have a number of strengths, too, and these areless well known. For one, the common evaluations truly inspire thedissemination of knowledge and techniques. There is a strong elementof "how'd they <I>do</I> that?" in which scientists dissect oneanother's papers, and fly to one another's sites. These evaluationsare compelling not because someone else <I>can</I> duplicate yourmethods and results, but because they <I>will</I>. Furthermore, apost-talk question such as, "Couldn't you do this with a 10-line Unixscript?" is likely to provoke an answer such as "Really? Great!"</P><P>Common evaluations also promote the problem-centered view of AIover the technique-centered view. This encourages researchers toinvestigate, import, and mold techniques from other fields.Evaluations also give weird ideas a fair shake, while weeding outconventional ideas that "should" work, but don't.</P><P>Most importantly, the common evaluation gets researchers to agreeon tasks they'd like to tackle and to be explicit about ways ofmeasuring success. (In general, it's researchers who set up theevaluation criteria, not funders.) Doing this right is what reallymakes an evaluation compelling. How do you evaluate amachine-translation system? For speech recognition, do you stressspeaker independence or vocabulary size, or can you mix and match?Should syntactic parsers be tested on real newspaper text or onmade-up garden-path sentences? Who will provide the collections ofright answers useful for testing (and training)? There are a lot ofopen debates about what we should be measuring, and how, which drives(and is driven by) the usual search for new and better techniques.These debates tackle hard evaluation questions, especially hard insuch areas as semantics and discourse.</P><P>These debates are <I>not</I> about experimental methodology-datapoints and standard deviations. My view on methodology is: use commonsense. If you want to convince me that your 91% accuracy results aregood, be sure to compare your strategy to the simplest, dumbestbaseline strategy (which had better do worse than 91%!). If there arecases where the right answer isn't clear, have a couple of people dothe task and measure their rate of agreement. Pore over training datato get ideas; don't even glance at test data. And so on. Thepublished literature is full of experiments that either convinced youor didn't-imitate the convincing ones in your own work. If you haveto do statistical significance tests to prove your method, that's notso compelling; the compelling part of your experiment is probablyelsewhere. What makes an AI experiment compelling is kind of likewhat makes an AI knowledge base compelling: you need to have all theparentheses in the right places, but it's the content that counts.</P><P>Finally, if what you're doing isn't yet ready to be quantitativelyevaluated, then stick to your guns. Argue elegance, argueexpressiveness, argue the long view. Don't let the "empiricists"intimidate you: we're all empiricists!</P><P><img src="x5010sb.gif">   <P>Kevin Knight is a senior research scientist at the Universityof Southern California's Information Sciences Institute. Hisresearch interest include artificial intelligence, naturallanguage processing, semantics, machine translation, unification,neural networks, and heuristic search. He received his BS fromHarvard and his MS and PhD from Carnegie Mellon University.Contact him at USC/ISI, 4676 Admiralty Way, Marina del Rey, CA90292; <a href=mailto:"knight@isi.edu">knight@isi.edu</a>;<a href="http://www.isi.edu/natural-language/people/knight.html">http://www.isi.edu/natural-language/people/knight.html</a>.</P>   <P><HR></P><P><I><A HREF="../../../expert.htm">IEEE Expert Online</A></I> |<A HREF="../../../depart.htm">Departments</A> |<A HREF="../../../feature.htm">Features</A> |<A HREF="../../../ai-www/ai-www.htm">AI on the WWW</A> |<A HREF="../../../board/board.htm">Editorial Board</A><BR><A HREF="../../../../pubs.htm">Computer Society Publications</A> |<A HREF="../../../../../cshome.htm">Computer Society home page</A></P><P>Send comments and questions about <I>IEEE Expert Online</I> toAnne Humphreys and Managing Editor Dick Price,<A HREF="mailto:ah34+@andrew.cmu.edu,dprice@computer.org">ah34+@andrew.cmu.eduand dprice@computer.org</A>. Send general comments and questionsabout the IEEE Computer Society's Web site to<A HREF="mailto:webmaster@computer.org">webmaster@computer.org</A></P><P><FONT SIZE=2>Personal use of this material is permitted. However,permission to reprint/republish this material for advertising orpromotional purposes or for creating new collective works for resaleor redistribution must be obtained from the IEEE. By choosing to viewthis document, you agree to all provisions of the copyright lawsprotecting it.</FONT></P><P><FONT SIZE=2>Copyright (c) Institute of Electrical and ElectronicsEngineers,